<!-- pp. 13-32 -->

## Introduction (continued)

### Renaissance's Unprecedented Success

- **Renaissance Technologies Medallion fund**: 66% average annual returns
- Over $100 billion in trading profits generated
- Outperforms all legendary investors (Warren Buffett, George Soros, Peter Lynch, Steve Cohen, Ray Dalio)
- Recent years: $7 billion+ annually in trading gains — more than Under Armour, Levi Strauss, Hasbro, Hyatt Hotels combined
- Just ~300 employees vs. thousands at competitors

### Simons's Personal Fortune

- **Jim Simons net worth**: ~$23 billion (wealthier than Elon Musk, Rupert Murdoch, Laurene Powell Jobs)
- Average Renaissance employee: nearly $50 million in firm's hedge funds
- "Create wealth in the manner of fairy tales full of kings, straw, and lots and lots of gold"

### The Revolution Simons Pioneered

- **Decision to use data and mathematics** instead of intuition/instinct/traditional research
- Inspired quantitative revolution that swept investing world
- By early 2019: **quant investors control ~30% of stock trading**, topping individual and traditional investors
- MBAs once scoffed at scientific approach; now coders dismiss MBAs

> "If we have enough data, I *know* we can make predictions." — Jim Simons

### Broader Impact Beyond Finance

- Methods embraced across industries: Silicon Valley, government, sports, medicine, military
- Crunching statistics, automating tasks, relying on algorithms — **three decades before** these became mainstream
- Developed strategies to corral talent and turn raw brainpower into wealth
- Making money from math was once impossible; Simons made it reality

### Simons as Modern-Day Medici

- Subsidizes salaries of thousands of public-school math/science teachers
- Developing autism treatments
- Expanding understanding of origins of life
- Questions raised: Does influence of senior executive **Robert Mercer** (most responsible for Trump 2016 victory) create problems?
- Mercer plucked Steve Bannon and Kellyanne Conway from obscurity, stabilized Trump campaign
- Mercer's daughter Rebekah: key role in Brexit campaign

### Central Questions

- What does it mean that mathematicians/scientists predict markets better than veteran investors?
- Do Simons and colleagues have fundamental understanding that eludes others?
- Are human judgment and intuition inherently flawed vs. models and automated systems?
- Can automated systems handle data deluge?
- Do quantitative methods create new, overlooked risks?

### The Core Paradox

> **Simons and team *shouldn't* have been the ones to master the market**

- Simons never took finance class, didn't care about business
- Until age forty, only dabbled in trading
- Decade later, still hadn't made progress
- Did **theoretical math** (most impractical kind), not applied mathematics
- Firm located in sleepy North Shore Long Island town
- Hired mathematicians/scientists who **don't know anything** about investing or Wall Street
- Some outright suspicious of capitalism
- Yet they changed how investors approach markets, leaving industry pros "in the dust"

> "It's as if a group of tourists, on their first trip to South America, with a few odd-looking tools and meager provisions, discovered El Dorado and proceeded to plunder the golden city, as hardened explorers looked on in frustration."

### Author's Research Process

- Over 400 interviews with 30+ current and former Renaissance employees
- Spoke with friends, family, others familiar with events
- Some took substantial personal risk to help tell story
- Simons eventually spoke with author (spent 10+ hours discussing certain periods)
- Asked author not to write book, never fully warmed to project, but was gracious
- Refused to discuss Renaissance's trading and most activities

### Book Approach

- Nonfiction based on first-person accounts and recollections
- Appeals to general reader and quantitative finance/math professionals
- Will reference: **hidden Markov models**, **kernel methods of machine learning**, **stochastic differential equations**
- Also: broken marriages, corporate intrigue, panicked traders

### The Enduring Lesson

> "For all his insights and prescience, Simons was blindsided by much that took place in his life. That may be the most enduring lesson of his remarkable story."

## Prologue

### Fall 1990: Simons at Age 52

- Still working despite already living "a full life" of adventure, accomplishment, prosperity
- Office on 33rd floor, midtown Manhattan high-rise
- Nearly 5'10", slight stoop, graying thinning hair
- Craggy features, glint of mischief — reminded friends of **Humphrey Bogart**
- Heavy smoker (oversize ashtray on cluttered desk)

### Twelve Years of Struggle

- Spent twelve years searching for successful investing formula
- Early trading relied on intuition/instinct — ups and downs made him "sick to his stomach"
- At one point, employee worried Simons was contemplating suicide
- Recruited two renowned mathematicians to trade with him — **partnerships crumbled amid losses and acrimony**
- Year earlier, results so awful he was forced to halt investing
- Some expected him to pull the plug entirely

### Partnership with Elwyn Berlekamp

- Second marriage and third business partner
- Working with **Elwyn Berlekamp**, game theorist
- Built computer model to digest data torrents and select ideal trades
- Scientific and systematic approach to remove emotion from investing

> "If we have enough data, I *know* we can make predictions." — Simons to colleague

### The Deeper Motivation

- PhD at age 23
- Acclaimed government code-breaker
- Renowned mathematician
- Groundbreaking university administrator
- Needed new challenge, bigger canvas
- Wanted to solve market's age-old riddle, conquer investing world
- "Would be remarkable" — wanted to be the one to use math to beat market
- Could make millions, maybe more, perhaps influence world beyond Wall Street

> "In trading, as in mathematics, it's rare to achieve breakthroughs in midlife."

- Convinced he was on verge of something special, maybe historic
- Merit cigarette lodged between two fingers

### The Pestering Phone Calls

- Called **Berlekamp** repeatedly about gold prices
- Berlekamp in California office near UC Berkeley campus, continued teaching
- Serious, slim, blue eyes behind thick glasses
- When Berlekamp discussed trading with Berkeley business school graduates, they mocked the methods as "quackery"

> "Oh, come on. Computers can't compete with human judgment." — Berkeley graduate to Berlekamp

> "We're gonna do things *better* than humans can." — Berlekamp's response

### The Golden Age of Traditional Investing

- **George Soros, Peter Lynch, Bill Gross** and others divining investment direction
- Producing enormous profits with intelligence, intuition, old-fashioned research
- Simons didn't know how to estimate cash flows, identify new products, forecast interest rates
- Digging through price information — no proper name for this trading
- Involved **data cleansing, signals, backtesting** — terms Wall Street pros unfamiliar with
- Few used email in 1990, internet browser not invented, algorithms barely known
- Idea that formulas might guide daily lives or that math professors might use computers to trounce celebrated investors "seemed far-fetched if not outright ludicrous"

### Early Signs of Success

- Simons upbeat and confident by nature
- Detected early signs of success for computer system
- Besides, once-thriving venture investments going nowhere
- Didn't want to return to teaching
- Urged Berlekamp: "Let's work on the system... Next year, I know, we can be up 80 percent"

> *Eighty percent in a year? Now he's really gone too far.* — Berlekamp's thought

- Eventually Berlekamp quit — fresh blow for Simons

> "The hell with it, I'm just going to run it myself." — Simons to friend

## Part One: Money Isn't Everything

## Chapter One

### 1952: Fourteen-Year-Old Jimmy at Breck's Garden Supply

- Winter 1952, trying to earn spending money
- Working in stockroom, so lost in thought he misplaced sheep manure, planting seeds, everything
- Owners asked him to walk aisles and sweep floors — mindless, repetitive task
- Demotion felt like stroke of luck: left alone to ponder math, girls, future

> *They're paying me to think!*

- Weeks later, couple asked about long-term plans
- "I want to study mathematics at MIT"
- They burst out laughing — young man so absentminded couldn't track gardening supplies hoped to be math major at MIT?

> "They thought it was the funniest thing they had ever heard." — Simons recalls

### Family Background: Parents' Influence

- **Marcia and Matthew Simons** welcomed James Harris in spring 1938
- Only child after Marcia suffered subsequent miscarriages
- Sharp intellect, outgoing personality, subtle wit
- **Marcia**: volunteered in Jimmy's school, never worked outside home, funneled dreams into son

> "She was ambitious for me... She saw me as her project." — Simons

- **Matty**: one of ten children, hustled from age six (newspapers, hauling bags at train station)
- Quit high school to work full time, tried night school but too tired
- Kind, soft-spoken, easygoing
- Enjoyed coming home, spinning tales to Marcia about Cuba's bridge to Florida
- Marcia gullible, Matty concocted outrageous stories — family game to crack Jimmy up

> "She didn't usually get it, but I did." — Simons

### Matty's Career Path

- Sales manager for **20th Century Fox**, driving to New England theaters
- **Shirley Temple** biggest star, Matty under contract to Fox
- Cobbled her films with 4-5 others, convinced theaters to pay for package
- Promoted to sales manager
- Father-in-law **Peter Kantor** asked him to work at shoe factory, promised ownership stake
- Matty obligated to join family business

### Peter Kantor: The Flamboyant Grandfather

- Shoe factory produced upscale women's shoes, successful but money "flew out almost as fast as it came in"
- Heavyset, flamboyant, favored expensive clothing, drove late-model Cadillacs, wore elevator shoes (five-foot-four stature)
- Blew wealth on horse races and paramours
- On paydays, let Jimmy and cousin **Richard Lourie** hold piles of cash "as high as our heads"

> "We both loved it." — Richard recalls

### Peter's Influence on Jimmy

- Projected insouciance and love of life
- Native of Russia, shared naughty stories about old country (wolves, women, caviar, vodka)
- Taught grandsons Russian phrases: "Give me a cigarette," "Kiss my ass"
- Kept $1,500 in breast pocket at all times
- Found dead with that exact amount, surrounded by Christmas cards from "dozens of appreciative female friends"

### Matty's Career Disappointment

- Never received promised ownership share
- Later told son he wished he hadn't forgone promising/exciting career

> "The lesson was: Do what you like in life, not what you feel you 'should' do." — Simons

### Jimmy's Early Mathematical Genius

- What Jimmy liked most: **think about mathematics**
- Preoccupied with numbers, shapes, slopes
- Age three: doubled numbers, divided in half, figured all powers of 2 up to 1,024
- On beach trip: Matty stopped for gasoline, perplexing young boy
- Jimmy reasoned: after using half tank, another half remains, then half of that — **never reaching empty**

### Zeno's Paradox

- Four-year-old stumbled onto classic mathematical problem
- If one must travel half remaining distance before reaching destination, how can one ever arrive?
- **Zeno of Elea** first addressed dilemma — most famous group of paradoxes, challenged mathematicians for centuries

### Childhood Personality

- Only child, sat with thoughts for long stretches, talked to himself
- In nursery school, climbed tree, sat on branch to ponder
- Marcia sometimes had to force him down to play with other children
- Determined to focus on own passions
- Age eight: family doctor **Dr. Kaplan** suggested medicine career ("ideal profession for a bright Jewish boy")
- Jimmy bristled: "I want to be a mathematician or a scientist"
- Doctor tried to reason: "Listen, you can't make any money in mathematics"
- Jimmy wanted to try

### School Years

- Smart and mischievous, displayed mother's self-assurance and father's impish humor
- Loved books, visited library to take out four/week (well above grade level)
- Mathematical concepts captivated him most
- **Lawrence School in Brookline**: class president, finished near top of grade
- Lost to young woman who didn't find herself lost in thought as often

### Childhood Observations

- Friend who was quite wealthy — struck by comfortable lifestyle

> "It's nice to be very rich. I observed that. I had no interest in business, which is not to say I had no interest in money."

### Adventures and Mischief

- Friend **Jim Harpel**: rode trolleys to Bailey's Ice Cream in Boston for pints
- Older: sneaked into burlesque shows at Old Howard Theatre
- One Saturday morning: Harpel's father noticed binoculars around necks
- "You boys going to the Old Howard?"
- *Busted.*
- "How'd you know, Mr. Harpel?"
- "Not much bird watching around here"

<!-- pp. 33-52 -->

## Chapter 1 (continued): Early Academic Life

### MIT Thesis and Early Career Crisis

- **1962**: Completed thesis "On the Transitivity of Holonomy Systems" (geometry of multidimensional curved spaces)
- Defined *holonomy* as "parallel transport of tangent vectors around closed curves in multiple-dimensional curved spaces"
- Won prestigious three-year teaching position at MIT
- **At 23, Simons experienced existential crisis**: "Is this it? Am I going to do this my whole life?"
- Loved mathematics but needed new adventure, craved overcoming odds and defying skepticism

### Colombia Business Venture (Failed)

- After one year at MIT, returned to Bogotá with schoolmates **Esquenazi** and **Mayer**
- Started local factory producing vinyl floor tile and PVC piping
- Financing from Esquenazi's father-in-law **Victor Shaio**; Simons and his father took small stakes
- Business went well, so Simons returned to academia (1963)

### Harvard Years (1963-1964)

- Accepted research position at Harvard, taught partial differential equations
- Popular professor: informal style, cracked jokes, rarely wore jacket or tie
- **Hidden financial stress**: borrowed money for Colombia floor-tile factory, persuaded parents to mortgage their home
- Taught two additional courses at Cambridge Junior College in secret to pad income
- **Barbara Simons on Jim's money drive**: "Jim understood at an early age that money is power. He didn't want people to have power over him."
- **Mounting pressures led to decision to take a break**

## Chapter 2: Institute for Defense Analyses

### The IDA Years (1964-1968)

- **1964**: Quit Harvard to join **Institute for Defense Analyses** (IDA) in Princeton, NJ
- Princeton division hired mathematicians to assist NSA in detecting and attacking Russian codes
- **Salary doubled** and began paying off debts
- IDA taught Simons to develop mathematical models to discern and interpret patterns in seemingly meaningless data
- Learned **statistical analysis** and **probability theory**, tools that would influence his later work

### Code-Breaking Work

- Simons created algorithms for his computer to test strategies
- **Awful at designing computer programs** — relied on in-house programmers for actual coding
- "I learned I liked to make algorithms and testing things out on a computer," Simons said
- **Early achievement**: helped develop ultrafast code-breaking algorithm, solving long-standing problem
- Intelligence experts discovered Soviets sent coded message with incorrect setting — Simons and two colleagues seized the glitch, gained insight into internal construction of enemy system
- **Earned trip to Washington, DC** for personal thanks from Defense Department officials

### IDA Culture

- All employees given same title: *technical staff member*
- Routinely shared credit, champagne toasts after solving thorny problems
- Collegial environment: afternoon tea with chess, puzzles, Go
- **Lenny Baum** (accomplished code-breaker) developed group credo: "Bad ideas is good, good ideas is terrific, no ideas is terrible"
- **Lee Neuwirth** (division deputy director): "It was an idea factory"
- ~25 employees, most with doctorates
- Hired for brainpower, creativity, ambition rather than specific expertise
- Assumption: researchers would find problems to work on and be clever enough to solve them

### IDA Eccentricities

- Simons and Barbara threw dinner parties with rum-heavy Fish House Punch
- High-stakes poker matches lasting until morning (Simons often walked away with fistfuls of colleagues' cash)
- **Simons arrested once**: racked up so many parking tickets in beat-up Cadillac, ignored summonses, police threw him in jail. Mathematicians bailed him out.
- One cryptologist discovered in bathrobe wearing nothing more in computer room (thrown out of home, living in office)
- Another staffer typed with bare, smelly toes instead of fingers

### Early Trading Ideas at IDA

- Computing power becoming advanced, but securities firms slow to embrace new technology
- **28-year-old Simons conceived idea**: use a company to electronically trade and research stocks
- Shared idea with boss **Dick Leibler** and IDA's best programmer
- Both agreed to join company to be named **iStar**
- **Neuwirth discovered the plot**: they had left business plan on Xerox machine
- **Plan failed to raise money**, eventually dropped
- **Didn't feel like setback** — Simons was making progress on *minimal varieties* research

### Minimal Varieties Research

- **Differential equations**: describe derivatives of mathematical quantities (relative rates of change)
- Used in physics, biology, finance, sociology
- Newton's equation (net force = mass × acceleration) is a differential equation
- **Partial differential equations (PDEs)**: equations involving derivatives with respect to time *and* space
- Used to describe elasticity, heat, sound

### Plateau's Problem and Minimal Varieties

- **Joseph Plateau** (19th century Belgian physicist): asked whether surfaces with "minimal" areas always exist
- Experimented with soap films stretching across wire frames
- Soap film has minimal area compared to any other surface with same wire frame boundary
- New York mathematician proved yes for ordinary 2D surfaces (1930)
- **Simons wanted to extend to higher dimensions** (minimal varieties)
- Mathematicians immerse themselves in work for years, sometimes dreaming about problems
- Simons wasn't just solving equations — hoped to discover and codify universal principles, rules, and truths
- **Albert Einstein**: argued natural order in world; mathematicians search for evidence of that structure

### Breakthrough in Minimal Varieties

- Conversations with **Frederick Almgren Jr.** (Princeton professor who solved problem in 3 dimensions) helped Simons achieve breakthrough
- Created partial differential equation (became known as **Simons equation**)
- Developed uniform solution through six dimensions, proposed counterexample in dimension seven
- Later, three Italians including **Fields Medal winner Enrico Bombieri** showed counterexample correct
- **1968**: Published "Minimal Varieties in Riemannian Manifolds" — foundational paper for geometers, proved crucial in related fields
- Continues to garner citations, underscore enduring significance
- **Established Simons as one of world's preeminent geometers**

### Stock-Trading System Development at IDA

- IDA granted researchers flexibility, so Simons examined stock market
- **With Baum and two other colleagues**: developed newfangled stock-trading system
- Published internal classified paper "Probabilistic Models for and Prediction of Stock Market Behavior"
- **Proposed method claiming annual gains of at least 50 percent**
- Ignored fundamental economic statistics (earnings, dividends, corporate news) — what code breakers termed "fundamental economic statistics of the market"
- **Searched for "macroscopic variables"** capable of predicting market's short-term behavior
- Posited market had as many as eight underlying "states" (e.g., "high variance," "good")

### The Hidden Markov Model Approach

- **Didn't try to identify or predict states using economic theory** or conventional methods
- Didn't address *why* market entered certain states
- **Used mathematics to determine set of states best fitting observed pricing data**
- Model made bets accordingly; *whys* didn't matter — just strategies to take advantage of inferred states
- **Poker analogy**: players surmise opponent's mood and adjust strategies. Don't need to know *why* opponent is glum/exuberant, just identify the moods
- **Used hidden Markov model** — sophisticated mathematical tool
- Just as gambler might deduce market's state from price movements

### Revolutionary Aspects of the Approach

- Paper was crude for late 1960s
- Made naive assumptions (trades under "ideal conditions," no trading costs)
- **Trailblazer**: Until then, investors sought underlying economic rationale or used *technical analysis* (graphs of past price movements)
- **Third approach**: more sophisticated, reliant on math and science tools
- Suggesting one could deduce "signals" capable of conveying useful information about expected market moves
- **Contemporaries**: **Harry Markowitz** (University of Chicago Nobel laureate, father of modern portfolio theory) searched for anomalies in securities prices, as was **Edward Thorp** (attempted early computerized trading, gaining head start on Simons)
- **Simons and colleagues argued**: not important to understand all underlying levers, but to find mathematical system matching them well enough to generate consistent profits
- Model foreshadowed revolutions in finance — *factor investing* (use of models based on unobservable states), quantitative investing

### Simons's Success at IDA (By 1967)

- Thriving: matching wits with Russians, making progress in math research, learning to manage big brains
- Gaining understanding of power of computation
- **Distinctive ability**: identifying most promising ideas of colleagues
- **Neuwirth**: "He was a terrific listener. It's one thing to have good ideas, it's another to recognize when others do. If there was a pony in your pile of horse manure, he would find it."

### Vietnam War Controversy

- **Leibler discussing retirement**, Simons in line to become deputy director
- **Vietnam War protests** cropped up including at Princeton
- Few Princeton students realized IDA division supporting NSA was in neighborhood until article in *Daily Princetonian*
- Simons and colleagues weren't doing war-related work, many vehemently against effort
- When Jim and Barbara's daughter Liz went to sleepaway camp, her friends got candy; Liz got peace necklaces
- Code breakers' unhappiness with war didn't stop Princeton students from protests, sit-in blocking IDA entrance
- Building trashed, Neuwirth's car pelted with eggs, called "baby killer"

### Simons's Letter to New York Times

- *New York Times* published opinion piece by **General Maxwell D. Taylor** (Sunday magazine cover story)
- Taylor (decorated war veteran, chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff, convinced JFK to send combat troops) argued US winning war, nation should rally around effort
- **Simons wrote six-paragraph letter** arguing better uses of nation's resources than war in Vietnam
- "It would make us a stronger country to rebuild Watts than to bomb Hanoi. It would make us stronger to construct decent transportation on our East Coast than to destroy all bridges in Vietnam."
- Newspaper published letter, Simons pleased with himself
- Didn't get much reaction from colleagues, figured Taylor fine with difference of opinion

### Getting Fired from IDA

- Stringer for *Newsweek* contacted Simons about Defense Department employees opposed to war
- Simons said he and colleagues generally worked on personal projects half time, government projects rest
- Since he opposed war, Simons said, decided to devote all time to own mathematics research until fighting ended, then only do Defense Department work
- **This was not true** — Simons hadn't formally established clean break from defense work, probably shouldn't have shared with public
- "I was twenty-nine. No one had ever asked to interview me. And I was a wise guy."
- Told Leibler about interview; Leibler gave Taylor heads-up about forthcoming *Newsweek* article
- **Leibler returned with disturbing news**: "You're fired."
- **Simons**: "What? You can't fire me, I'm a *permanent* member."
- **Leibler**: "Jim, the only difference between a permanent member and temporary member is a temporary member has a contract. You don't."
- **Three days later**: President Lyndon Johnson announced halting of US bombing missions (sign war effort ending)
- Simons figured news meant he could reclaim job; Leibler told him not to bother

### Post-IDA Uncertainty

- **By then, Simons had three young children**
- Little idea what to do next, but getting fired convinced him he needed to gain control over future
- Wasn't quite sure how
- **Minimal-varieties paper gaining attention**, fielded offers from schools and companies including IBM
- Told **Leonard Charlap** (friend, fellow mathematician) teaching seemed dull, might join investment bank to sell convertible bonds
- When Charlap said didn't know what convertible bonds were, Simons launched into long description
- **Charlap disappointed**: Simons was one of world's premier young mathematicians, not someone meant to hawk Wall Street's latest product

### SUNY Stony Brook Offer

- **Letter from John Toll** (president of SUNY Stony Brook, public university on Long Island ~60 miles from NYC)
- School spent five years searching for someone to lead math department
- To extent school had reputation, it was for drug use problem on campus
- **Toll determined to change things**: physicist recruited by Governor Nelson Rockefeller, leading $100M government-funded drive to turn school into "Berkeley of the East"
- Already recruited Nobel Prize–winning physicist **Chen Ning Yang**
- Now focusing on revitalizing math department
- **Offered Simons position of chairman** — chance to be own boss, build department as wished
- "I want it," Simons told Toll

### Building the Stony Brook Math Department (1968+)

- **At age 30 (1968)**, Simons moved family to Long Island, began charming recruits and building department
- **Early target**: **James Ax** (Cornell mathematician who won prestigious Cole Prize in number theory year earlier)
- Ax unlikely to bolt Ivy League powerhouse for unheralded school like Stony Brook
- Had wife, young son, bright future at Cornell
- **But Simons and Ax friendly as grad students at Berkeley**, stayed in touch
- Simons and Barbara drove five hours northwest to Ithaca to meet with Ax
- **Wooed Ax**: promised major salary increase
- Later hosted Ax and family in Stony Brook, drove to West Meadow Beach in Brookhaven on Long Island Sound (picturesque views)
- Back in Ithaca, Ax and wife Barbara received care packages from Simons packed with pebbles and reminders of Stony Brook's temperate climate

### Ax's Recruitment Success

- **Ax took time deliberating**, frustrating Simons
- One day Simons walked into office in tennis outfit, flung racket to ground: "If this job requires any more ass-licking I'm out of here!"
- **Entreaties paid off**: Ax became first brand-name academic to join Stony Brook
- "He really wore us down with his little tricks," Barbara Ax says
- **Ax's decision sent message** that Simons meant business

### Recruiting Strategy

- Raided other schools, refined pitch focusing on what it might take to lure specific mathematicians
- Those who valued money got raises
- Those focused on personal research got lighter class loads, extra leave, generous research support, help evading onerous administrative requirements
- **One potential hire**: "Jim, I don't want to be on a committee."
- **Simons**: "How about the library committee? It's a committee of one."

### Hiring Philosophy

- Valued "killers" — those with single-minded focus who wouldn't quit on math problem until arriving at solution
- Told another colleague some academics were "super smart" yet weren't original thinkers worthy of position at university
- "There are guys and there are *real* guys," he said
- **Created collegial, stimulating environment** like at IDA
- Kept teaching loads at reasonable levels
- Invited colleagues to join him and Barbara on newly purchased 23-foot boat docked on Long Island Sound
- Unlike some top-flight academics, Simons relished interacting with colleagues
- Would wander into professor's office asking what projects working on, how he could be helpful (much like at IDA)
- **Hershel Farkas**: "It's unusual for someone to think of the well-being of colleagues"

### Simons's Personal Style

- Put mathematicians and students at ease, dressing more informally than others at school
- **Rarely wore socks, even in frigid New York winters** (practice continued into his eighties)
- "I just decided it takes too much of my time to put them on," Simons says

### Social Life at Stony Brook

- Simons and Barbara hosted weekly parties at which academics, artists, left-leaning intellectuals removed shoes and mingled on white shag carpet
- Discussed news, played chess, worked on puzzles, competed at Go, chatted about politics and other topics
- **Made mistakes** — let future Fields Medal winner **Shing-Tung Yau** get away after young geometer demanded tenure
- **But assembled one of world's top centers of geometry**, hiring twenty mathematicians while learning to identify nation's best minds and how to recruit and manage them

<!-- pp. 53-72 -->

## Launching Monemetrics

### Simons Names His Firm
- Named company **Monemetrics** — combining "money" and "econometrics"
- Would use math to analyze financial data and score trading gains
- At IDA: built computer models to spot signals in enemy communications noise
- At Stony Brook: identified and managed talented mathematicians
- Now: hire a team to pore through market data, identify trends, develop mathematical formulas to profit

### Recruiting Lenny Baum

#### Baum's Background
- Born 1931, son of Russian Jewish immigrants who fled to Brooklyn
- Father Morris worked in hat factory, eventually became manager and owner
- **Lenny Baum**: 6 feet tall, barrel chest, high school top sprinter and tennis team member
- Delicate hands suggested someone more comfortable with textbooks than sports
- Met **Julia Lieberman** at Brighton Beach — she fled Czechoslovakia in 1941 on last boat from Europe
- Both attended Harvard: Lenny graduated 1953, earned PhD in mathematics
- Julia: fourth in class at Boston University, master's in education and history at Harvard

#### Baum at the IDA
- Joined IDA in Princeton after Harvard PhD
- **Even more successful at codebreaking than Simons** — credited with some of IDA's most important, still-classified achievements
- **Lee Neuwirth**: "Lenny and some others were definitely higher than Jim in what we in management used to call 'lifeboat order'"

#### The Baum-Welch Algorithm
- Late 1960s: Baum and **Lloyd Welch** developed algorithm to analyze **Markov chains**
- **Markov chain**: sequences of events where probability of what happens next depends only on current state, not past events
  - Example: baseball — if batter has 3 balls and 2 strikes, order of fouls doesn't matter; next pitch determines outcome
- **Hidden Markov process**: chain governed by unknown underlying parameters/variables
  - See results but not the "states" that explain progression
  - Example: runs scored each inning with no obvious pattern
- **Baum-Welch algorithm**: estimates probabilities and parameters within complex sequences with little information beyond output
  - For baseball: could guess game situations that produced scores even without knowing sport rules
  - Can infer sense of sport's rules from distribution of scores

> "The Baum-Welch algorithm gets you closer to the final answer by giving you better probabilities," — Lloyd Welch

- Algorithm allows computer to teach itself states and probabilities
- **One of twentieth century's notable advances in machine learning**
- Enabled first effective speech recognition system and even **Google's search engine**
- Most of Baum's hundreds of papers remained classified
- His wife **Julia** felt he wasn't getting recognition or pay he deserved
- Baum children had little idea what father did (he said work was classified)
- Baum told daughter **Stefi**: "We're not making bombs" (controversy about Vietnam War flared)

#### Baum's Personality
- Homebody who spent little time socializing or playing poker
- Most evenings: sat quietly on faux-leopard-skin couch, scribbling on yellow pad with pencil
- When facing challenging problem: stopped, gazed into distance, pondered
- Fit stereotype of absentminded professor — once came to work with half a beard (became distracted thinking about mathematics while shaving)
- Eyesight deteriorating: suffered from **cone-rod dystrophy** (disorder affecting retina cone cells)
- Difficult to engage in visual activities like tennis
- Ball hit Baum in head at net; same in Ping-Pong (clear blue eyes would see ball then lose it)
- Remained upbeat, focusing on pleasures: walking two miles/day near Princeton campus
- Could read and write despite vision decline
- Maintained unbreakable optimism

> "Let the problem be," — Lenny Baum (his motto, usually with smile)
> "It will solve itself."

### Baum Joins Simons (1977)

#### The Invitation
- After Simons left IDA for Stony Brook, Baum became frustrated
- Broke Russian code and identified spy, but FBI too slow arresting suspect
- Expressed irritation, became discouraged about unit's future
- Wrote internal memo emphasizing need for better recruitment
- 1977: Simons reached out asking Baum to spend day at Monemetrics office on Long Island
- Baum chuckled at invitation — knew little about trading despite earlier theoretical paper with Simons
- Cared so little about investing that he left family portfolio entirely in wife's hands
- Agreed to help as favor to old friend

#### The Yen Discovery
- Simons set charts of daily closing values of major currencies in front of Baum
- Baum scrutinized data, quickly determined some currencies (especially **Japanese yen**) moved in steady, straight lines over time
- Perhaps Simons was right — some inherent structure in markets
- **Baum's hypothesis**: yen's steady climb might be due to Japanese government (under foreign pressure) intervening to buy currency "in precise Japanese manner" to make exports less competitive
- Either way, mathematical model might map and ride trends in currencies

#### Early Success
- Baum began working with Simons once a week
- By 1979, age 48, Baum was immersed in trading (just as Simons hoped)
- Top chess player in college, felt he'd discovered new game to test mental faculties
- Received one-year leave from IDA
- Moved family to Long Island, rented three-bedroom Victorian house lined with tall bookcases
- Julia drove Baum back and forth to Simons's office daily (eyesight had worsened)

> "Let's see if we can make a model," — Jim Simons

- Didn't take long to develop algorithm directing Monemetrics to buy currencies if they moved below recent trend line, sell if they veered too far above
- Simple work, but Baum seemed on right path, instilling confidence

> "Once I got Lenny involved, I could see the possibilities of building models," — Jim Simons

### Building the Fund

#### Raising Capital
- Simons called friends including **Jimmy Mayer** and **Edmundo Esquenazi** to invest
- Showed charts demonstrating how he and Baum would have made had they used math-focused strategy over previous years
- Mayer: impressed by possibilities
- Failed to raise full $4 million target, but came close enough to begin

#### Naming the Fund
- Called fund **Limroy** — amalgam of:
  - **Lord Jim** (protagonist of Joseph Conrad novel)
  - **Royal Bank of Bermuda** (handled money transfers)
- Advantages: tax-related, offshore location
- Name blended high-finance with character known for wrestling with ideals of honor and morality

#### The Hedge Fund Structure
- Limroy would be a **hedge fund** — loosely defined term for private investment partnerships managing money for wealthy individuals/institutions
- Pursue variety of strategies including hedging (protecting from losses in overall market)
- Monemetrics would invest a bit of money for Simons, testing strategies in various markets
- If tactics looked profitable, Simons would place same trades in Limroy (much bigger, investing for outsiders)
- Baum would share in 25% cut firm claimed from all trading profits

### Recruiting James Ax

#### Ax's Background and Contribution
- Simons asked **James Ax** (prized recruit at Stony Brook) to check out strategies
- Like Baum a year earlier, Ax knew little about investing and cared even less
- Immediately understood what colleagues were trying to accomplish
- Became convinced they were onto something special
- Not only could Baum's algorithm succeed in currencies, **similar predictive models could be developed to trade commodities** (wheat, soybeans, crude oil)
- Simons persuaded Ax to leave academia, setting him up with own trading account
- Now Simons was *really* excited: two of most acclaimed mathematicians working to unlock market secrets, enough cash to support efforts

### Trading Philosophy Emerges

#### The Contrarian Bet
- Year or two earlier, Baum couldn't stop thinking about math; now trading occupied his mind
- Summer 1979: lying on beach with family, Baum mulled extended weakness in **British pound**
- Conventional wisdom: currency could only fall in value
- Expert who advised Simons/Baum made so much selling pounds he named son **Sterling**
- Baum sat straight up, overcome with excitement
- Convinced buying opportunity at hand
- Raced to office, telling Simons **Margaret Thatcher** (Britain's new prime minister) was keeping currency at unsustainably low levels

> "Thatcher is sitting on the pound. She can't hold it down much longer." — Lenny Baum

- Baum said needed to buy pounds, but Simons was amused rather than swayed

> "Lenny, it's too bad you didn't come in earlier. Thatcher stood up. . . . The pound just rose five cents." — Jim Simons

- That morning, Thatcher decided to let pound rise
- Baum was unfazed

> "That's nothing! It's going to go up fifty cents—maybe more!" — Lenny Baum

#### Major Wins
- Baum was right
- Kept buying British pounds, currency kept soaring
- Followed with accurate predictions for Japanese yen, West German deutsche mark, Swiss franc
- Gains had South American investors calling Simons with congratulations and encouragement
- Fund grew by tens of millions of dollars
- Fellow mathematicians scratched heads about why Simons discarded promising career to sit in makeshift office trading currency contracts
- Equally stunned that Baum and Ax had joined him
- Even Simons's father seemed disappointed
- 1979 bar mitzvah party for Simons's son Nathaniel: **Matty Simons** told Stony Brook mathematician:

> "I liked to say, 'My son, the professor,' not 'My son, the businessman.'" — Matty Simons

### Expanding Trading

#### Moving Beyond Currencies
- Simons spent little time looking back
- After early currency winnings, amended Limroy's charter to allow trading **US Treasury bond futures contracts** and commodities
- Simons and Baum (now with own separate investment accounts) assembled small team to build sophisticated models identifying profitable trades in currency, commodity, and bond markets
- Simons was having blast exploring lifelong passion for financial speculation while trying to solve markets — perhaps greatest challenge he'd encountered
- Joked wife **Marilyn** at last could "hang out with people and know what they were talking about"

### Greg Hullender Joins

#### Hullender's Background
- **Greg Hullender**: 19-year-old on verge of getting kicked out of Caltech
- Sharp and creative but trouble focusing on schoolwork, did poorly in many courses
- Later diagnosed with **attention-deficit disorder**
- Frustrated by struggles, as were school administrators
- Last straw: caught running unauthorized, high-stakes trading operation out of dorm room
- Friends pooled cash, handed to Hullender
- Purchased stock options before 1978 market rally, turning $200 into $2,000 in days
- Soon everyone in dorm wanted in, throwing money at Hullender
- Began repackaging stock options purchased through brokerage at Merrill Lynch, reselling to eager students

> "It was like my own stock exchange," — Greg Hullender (says with pride)

- Merrill Lynch officials weren't amused
- Citing Hullender for violating account terms, brokerage pulled plug
- School kicked him out
- Sitting in dorm waiting to be expelled, startled by 7 a.m. phone call from Simons
- Simons heard about unlicensed operation through Caltech grad student
- Impressed by Hullender's understanding of financial markets and moxie
- Offered **$9,000/year salary plus share of firm's profits** to come to New York to program computers and help trade

#### Hullender's Appearance and Personality
- Round, cherubic face, shaggy brown hair, boyish smile
- Looked like teenager heading to summer camp, not cross-country trip to join unknown trading operation
- Rail-thin with thick, oversize glasses
- Kept pens in front pocket with brown case for spectacles
- Made him appear especially guileless
- Hadn't met Simons or Baum, wary of job offer

> "Jim's firm sounded like the shadiest thing in the world." — Greg Hullender

- But: "I was in my dorm room waiting to get kicked out—it's not like I had a lot of options"

#### Starting Work
- Moved to Long Island, staying with Simons and family for several weeks
- Rented room in nearby Stony Brook dormitory
- Didn't have driver's license, so Simons lent bicycle to get to work
- At office: Simons (wearing usual open-collared cotton shirt and loafers) gave tutorial on trading approach
- Currency markets affected by government actions and others
- Firm hoped to develop detailed, step-by-step algorithms to identify "trends that result from hidden actors influencing the market"
- Not unlike what Simons did at IDA to break enemy code

### The Piggy Basket System

#### Building the Model
- Hullender began writing program to track firm's results
- Within six months, figures showed **disturbing losses** — Simons's shift to bond trading had gone awry
- Clients kept calling, now asking why losing so much money rather than extending congratulations
- Simons seemed to take downturn hard, growing anxious as losses increased
- One rough day: Hullender found boss lying supine on couch in office
- Hullender sensed Simons wanted to open up, perhaps make confession

> "Sometimes I look at this and feel I'm just some guy who doesn't really know what he's doing," — Jim Simons

- Hullender was startled — until that moment, Simons's self-confidence seemed boundless
- Now appeared to second-guess decision to ditch mathematics to try to beat market
- Still on couch, as if in therapist's office, Simons told Hullender about **Lord Jim**
- Centers on failure and redemption
- Character had high opinion of himself, yearned for glory but failed miserably in test of courage
- Condemned himself to life filled with shame
- Simons sat up, turned to Hullender

> "He had a really good death, though. Jim died nobly." — Jim Simons
> *Wait, is Simons contemplating suicide?*

- Hullender worried about boss and own future
- Realized had no money, alone on East Coast, boss on couch talking about death
- Tried reassuring Simons but conversation turned awkward

#### Recovery and New Determination
- Following days: Simons emerged from funk, more determined than ever to build **high-tech trading system guided by algorithms** (step-by-step computer instructions) rather than human judgment
- Until then, Simons and Baum relied on crude trading models plus own instincts
- Approach left Simons in crisis
- Sat down with **Howard Morgan** (technology expert hired to invest in stocks)
- Shared new goal: building sophisticated trading system fully dependent on preset algorithms that might even be automated

> "I don't want to have to worry about the market every minute. I want models that will make money while I sleep. A pure system without humans interfering." — Jim Simons

#### Collecting Historic Data
- Technology for fully automated system wasn't there yet, but wanted to try more sophisticated methods
- Suspected need for reams of historic data so computers could search for persistent and repeating price patterns across large swath of time
- Bought stacks of books from World Bank and elsewhere
- Reels of magnetic tape from various commodity exchanges
- Each packed with commodity, bond, and currency prices going back decades (some to before WWII)
- Ancient stuff almost no one cared about, but Simons had hunch might prove valuable
- Hullender's **PDP-11/60 computer** couldn't read older data (formatting outdated)
- Hullender surreptitiously carried reels to nearby **Grumman Aerospace** headquarters (friend Stan worked there)
- Around midnight when things slowed at defense contractor, Stan let Hullender fire up supercomputer
- Spent hours converting reels so could be read on Simons's computer
- Friends caught up over coffee as reels spun

#### Manual Data Collection
- To gather additional data: Simons had staffer travel to lower Manhattan
- Visit Federal Reserve office to painstakingly record interest-rate histories and other information not yet available electronically
- For more recent pricing data: tasked former Stony Brook secretary and new office manager **Carole Alberghine** with recording closing prices of major currencies
- Each morning: Alberghine went through *Wall Street Journal*
- Climbed on sofas and chairs in firm's library room to update various figures on graph paper hanging from ceiling and taped to walls
- Arrangement worked until Alberghine toppled from perch, pinching nerve and suffering permanent injury
- Simons enlisted younger woman to scale couches and update numbers

#### Testing Strategies
- Simons recruited sister-in-law and others to input prices into database Hullender created
- Track prices and test various trading strategies based on:
  - Mathematical insights
  - Intuitions of Simons, Baum, and others
- Many tactics focused on **momentum strategies**
- Also looked for potential correlations between commodities:
  - If currency went down three days in row, odds of going down fourth day?
  - Do gold prices lead silver prices?
  - Might wheat prices predict gold and other commodity prices?
- Simons even explored whether natural phenomena affected prices
- Hullender and team often came up empty, unable to prove reliable correlations
- Simons pushed them to keep searching

> "There's a pattern here; there *has* to be a pattern." — Jim Simons (insisted)

#### The Piggy Basket
- Eventually developed system that could dictate trades for various commodity, bond, and currency markets
- Office's single computer wasn't powerful enough to incorporate all data
- Could identify a few reliable correlations
- Trading system had **live hogs as component** — Simons named it **"Piggy Basket"**
- Built to digest masses of data and make trading recommendations using tools of **linear algebra**
- Produced row of numbers
  - Example: "0.5, 0.3, 0.2" = currency portfolio should be 50% yen, 30% deutsche marks, 20% Swiss francs
- After Piggy Basket churned out recommendations for ~40 different futures contracts
- Staffer would get in touch with firm's broker
- Deliver buy-and-sell instructions based on those proportions
- System produced **automated trade recommendations, rather than automated trades**
- Best Simons could do at the time

### Early Results and Setbacks

#### Initial Success
- For a few months: Piggy Basket scored big profits
- Trading about $1 million of Monemetrics' money
- Team generally held positions for day or so, then sold
- Encouraged by early results, Simons transferred several million dollars of additional cash from Limroy account into model
- Scoring even larger gains

#### The Potato Debacle
- Then something unexpected happened
- Computerized system developed unusual appetite for **potatoes**
- Shifted two-thirds of cash into futures contracts on New York Mercantile Exchange representing millions of pounds of **Maine potatoes**
- One day: Simons got call from unhappy regulators at **Commodity Futures Trading Commission**
- Monemetrics was close to cornering global market for these potatoes, they said, with alarm
- Simons had to stifle giggle — yes, regulators were grilling him
- Had to realize Simons hadn't meant to accumulate so many potatoes
- Couldn't even understand why computer system was buying so many
- Surely CFTC would understand that

> "They think we're trying to corner the market on spuds!" — Jim Simons (told Hullender with amusement after hanging up)

- Regulators somehow missed humor in Simons's misadventure
- Closed out potato positions, costing Simons and investors millions of dollars
- Soon, he and Baum had lost confidence in system
- Could see Piggy Basket's trades, were aware when it made and lost money
- But Simons and Baum weren't sure *why* model was making its trading decisions
- Maybe computerized trading model wasn't the way to go after all, they decided

#### Hullender Departs (1980)
- 1980: Hullender quit to go back to school
- Leaving college prematurely weighed on him
- Ashamed he couldn't help Simons make more progress on computerized trading system
- Couldn't understand math Simons and Baum were using
- Was lonely and miserable
- Weeks earlier: revealed to colleagues he was gay
- They tried to make him comfortable, but young man felt increasingly out of place

> "I just felt I had a better chance meeting someone compatible in California. Some things are more important than money." — Greg Hullender (eventually earned degree, became machine-learning specialist for Amazon and Microsoft)

### Return to Traditional Trading

#### New Approach
- With Hullender gone and Piggy Basket malfunctioning, Simons and Baum drifted from predictive mathematical models to more traditional trading style
- Began looking for undervalued investments while reacting to market-moving news
- Investing $30 million in various markets
- Simons thought might help if could get hands on news from Europe before rivals
- Hired Parisian studying at Stony Brook to read obscure French financial newsletter and translate before others had chance
- Also consulted with economist named **Alan Greenspan** (later would become Federal Reserve chair)
- Set up red phone in office that rang whenever urgent financial news broke
- He and Baum could enter trades before others
- Sometimes phone rang and they were nowhere to be found
- Sent new office manager **Penny Alberghine** (Carole's sister-in-law) racing to find them
- Be it in local restaurant or shop or even men's room, where she'd pound on door to get their attention

> "Come back in! Wheat's down thirty points!" — Penny Alberghine (screamed once)

#### Office Culture
- Simons's cheeky, irreverent sense of humor put team at ease
- Would tease Alberghine about thick New York accent
- She'd mock remains of his Boston inflection
- Once: Simons became elated receiving especially high interest rate for money firm held in bank account

> "Investors are getting eleven and seven-*fucking*-eighths!" — Jim Simons (exclaimed)

- When young employee gasped at blue language, Simons flashed grin

> "I know—that *is* an impressive rate!"

- Few times a week: **Marilyn** came by to visit, usually with baby **Nicholas**
- Other times: **Barbara** checked in on ex-husband
- Other employees' spouses and children also wandered around office
- Each afternoon: team met for tea in library
- Simons, Baum, others discussed latest news and debated direction of economy
- Simons also hosted staffers on his yacht, *The Lord Jim*, docked in nearby Port Jefferson

#### Simons's Daily Routine
- Most days: sat in office wearing jeans and golf shirt
- Staring at computer screen, developing new trades
- Reading news and predicting where markets were going, like most everyone else
- When especially engrossed in thought: Simons would hold cigarette in one hand and chew on cheek
- **Baum** in smaller nearby office trading own account
- Favored raggedy sweaters, wrinkled trousers, worn Hush Puppies shoes
- To compensate for worsening eyesight: hunched close to computer
- Trying to ignore smoke wafting through office from Simons's cigarettes

#### Business Expansion
- Traditional trading approach going so well that when boutique next door closed, Simons rented space and punched through adjoining wall
- New space filled with offices for new hires:
  - Economist
  - Expert intelligence analyst
- Provided expert intelligence and made own trades, helping boost returns
- Same time: Simons was developing new passion — backing promising technology companies
- Including electronic dictionary company called **Franklin Electronic Publishers** (developed first hand-held computer)

#### Rebranding
- 1982: Simons changed Monemetrics' name to **Renaissance Technologies Corporation**
- Reflecting developing interest in upstart companies
- Simons came to see himself as venture capitalist as much as trader
- Spent much of week working in office in New York City
- Where he interacted with hedge fund's investors while also dealing with tech companies

#### Family Life
- Simons also took time to care for children, one needing extra attention
- **Paul** (Simons's second child with Barbara) had been born with rare hereditary condition called **ectodermal dysplasia**
- Paul's skin, hair, sweat glands didn't develop properly
- Was short for age, teeth were few and misshapen
- To cope with resulting insecurities: Paul asked parents to buy stylish and popular clothing hoping to fit in with grade-school peers
- Paul's challenges weighed on Simons
- Sometimes drove Paul to Trenton, New Jersey
- Where pediatric dentist made cosmetic improvements to Paul's teeth
- Later: New York dentist fitted Paul with complete set of implants, improving self-esteem
- Baum was fine with Simons working from New York office, dealing with outside investments, and tending to family matters
- Baum didn't need much help

### Baum's Success and Philosophy

#### Trading Style
- Making so much money trading various currencies using intuition and instinct
- Pursuing systematic, "quantitative" style of trading seemed waste of time
- Building formulas was difficult and time-consuming
- Gains figured to be steady but never spectacular
- By contrast: quickly digesting office's news ticker, studying newspaper articles, analyzing geopolitical events seemed exciting and far more profitable

> "Why do I need to develop those models? It's so much easier making millions in the market than finding mathematical proof." — Lenny Baum (asked daughter Stefi)

- Simons respected Baum too much to tell him how to trade
- Besides: Baum was on roll
- Firm's computer firepower was limited, making any kind of automated system likely impossible to implement
- Baum liked to pore over economic and other data, close door to office, lie back on green sofa
- Reflecting for long periods on next market move

> "He'd lose track of time. He was a bit spacey." — Penny Alberghine

#### Buy-and-Hold Strategy
- When Baum emerged: usually placed buy orders
- Optimist by nature, liked to purchase investments and sit on them until they rose
- No matter how long it took
- Courage was needed to hold on to investment positions
- Baum told friends he was proud he didn't buckle when others grew weak in knees

> "If I don't have a reason for doing something, I leave things as they are and do nothing." — Lenny Baum (wrote to family members, explaining tactics)
> "Dad's theory was buy low and hold on forever." — Stefi

#### Remarkable Returns
- Strategy enabled Baum to ride out market turbulence
- Rack up more than **$43 million in profits between July 1979 and March 1982**
- Nearly double his original stake from Simons
- In latter year: Baum grew so bullish about stocks
- Insisted on missing firm's annual outing on Simons's yacht
- Preferring to monitor market and buy more stock futures
- Around noon when Baum grudgingly joined colleagues, Simons asked why he looked so glum

> "I got half of what I wanted. Then I had to come to this lunch." — Lenny Baum

#### Stock Market Success (1982)
- Baum probably should have stayed in office
- Had correctly identified that year's historic bottoming out of US stock market
- As stocks soared and profits piled up: Lenny and Julia purchased six-bedroom, turn-of-the-century home on Long Island Sound
- Julia still drove old Cadillac but no longer worried about money
- Trading life had less salutary impact on husband despite mounting gains
- Once relaxed and upbeat: Baum turned serious and intense
- Fielding calls from Simons and others well into evening
- Debated how to react to news of day

> "He was like a different person." — Stefi (recalls)

### The Gold-Coffee Disasters

#### Gold Bubble (1979-1980)
- Baum's penchant for holding on to investments eventually caused rift with Simons
- Tension started back fall 1979
- Each purchased gold-futures contracts at around $250/ounce
- Late that year: Iranian government took 52 American diplomats and citizens hostage
- Russia invaded Afghanistan to support country's communist regime
- Resulting geopolitical jitters pushed gold and silver prices higher
- Visitors to Long Island office watched as Baum (normally quiet and introspective) stood exuberantly cheering gold higher
- Simons sat nearby, smiling
- By January 1980: gold and silver prices were soaring
- When gold topped $700 in frenzied two-week period, **Simons dumped his position**
- Locking in millions of dollars of profits
- As usual: Baum couldn't bear to sell
- One day: Simons was speaking with friend who mentioned his wife (a jeweler) was rifling through closet
- Removing gold cuff links and tie clips to sell

> "Are you going broke or something?" — Jim Simons (asked with concern)
> "No—she can cut the line to sell." — friend
> "There's a *line* to sell gold?"

- Friend explained people around country were queuing up to sell jewelry, taking advantage of surging prices
- Simons turned scared — if supply of gold was swelling, that could crush prices
- Back in office, Simons gave Baum an order

> "Lenny, sell right now."

> "No—the trend will continue."
> "Sell the fucking gold, Lenny!"

- Simons ignored Simons, driving him crazy
- Baum was sitting on more than $10 million of profits
- Gold had skyrocketed past $800/ounce
- Sure more gains were ahead

> "Jim nagged me. But I couldn't find any specific reason or news for action, so I did nothing." — Lenny Baum (later told family)

- Finally on January 18: Simons dialed firm's broker and pressed phone to Baum's ear

> "Tell him you're selling, Lenny!"
> "Alright, alright." — Lenny Baum (grumbled)

- Within months: gold had raced past $865/ounce
- Baum was bitterly complaining that Simons had cost him serious money
- Then bubble burst — just a few months later, gold was under $500/ounce

#### Coffee Disaster (Later Period)
- Bit later: Baum discovered native of Colombia who worked at brokerage firm **E. F. Hutton**
- Claimed to have insights into coffee-futures market
- When Colombian predicted higher prices: Baum and Simons built some of largest positions in entire market
- Almost immediately: coffee prices dropped 10%, costing them millions
- Once again: Simons dumped holdings but Baum couldn't bear selling
- Eventually: Baum lost so much money he had to ask Simons to get rid of coffee investment for him
- He was unable to do it himself
- Baum later described episode as "the dumbest thing I ever did in this business"
- Baum's eternal optimism was beginning to wear on Simons

> "He had the buy-low part, but he didn't always have the sell-high part." — Jim Simons (later said)

#### Move to Bermuda and Bond Market Collapse (1983-1984)
- By 1983: Baum and family had moved to Bermuda
- Enjoyed island's idyllic weather and favorable tax laws
- Island's beauty reinforced Baum's upbeat nature and bullish instincts
- US inflation seemed under control
- Federal Reserve Chair **Paul Volcker** predicted decline in interest rates
- Baum purchased tens of millions of dollars of US bonds — ideal investment for that environment
- But panic selling overcame bond market in late spring 1984
- Amid surging bond issuance by Reagan administration and rapid US economic growth
- As losses grew: Baum maintained typical equanimity
- But Simons feared troubles could take firm down

> "Lighten up, Lenny. Don't be stubborn." — Jim Simons

- Baum's losses kept growing
- Huge wager that yen would continue to appreciate also backfired
- Placing Baum under even more pressure

> "This cannot continue!" — Lenny Baum (said one day, staring at computer screen)

- When value of Baum's investment positions had plummeted 40%
- Triggered automatic clause in agreement with Simons
- Forcing Simons to sell all of Baum's holdings and unwind their trading affiliation
- Sad denouement to decades-long relationship between esteemed mathematicians

### Aftermath and Legacy

#### Baum's Later Life
- Ultimately: Baum proved prescient
- In subsequent years: both interest rates and inflation tumbled, rewarding bond investors
- By then: Baum was trading for himself
- He and Julia had returned to Princeton
- Years with Simons had been filled with such stress that Baum rarely enjoyed full night's sleep
- Now he was rested and had time to return to mathematics
- As grew older: Baum focused on prime numbers and unsolved **Riemann hypothesis**
- For fun: traveled country competing in Go tournaments
- Memorizing board or standing over it to compensate for ever-declining eyesight
- In eighties: Baum enjoyed walking two miles from home to Witherspoon Street near Princeton University campus
- Stopping to smell budding flowers along way
- Passing drivers sometimes slowed to offer assistance to slow, well-dressed older gentleman
- He always declined help
- Baum would spend hours sitting in sun at coffee shops
- Striking up conversations with strangers
- Family members sometimes found him gently comforting homesick undergraduates
- Summer 2017, weeks after finalizing latest mathematics paper: **Baum passed away at age 86**
- His children published paper posthumously

#### Impact on Simons
- Baum's losses in 1984 trading debacle left deep scars on Simons
- Halted firm's trading and held disgruntled investors at bay
- Once staffers eagerly greeted frequent calls from Simons's friends asking "How are we doing?"
- Now that fund was losing millions of dollars daily: Simons instituted new rule with clients — **no performance results until end of each month**
- Losses had been so upsetting that Simons contemplated giving up trading to focus on expanding technology businesses
- Simons gave clients opportunity to withdraw their money
- Most showed faith, hoping Simons could figure out way to improve results
- But Simons himself was racked with self-doubt

> "There's no rhyme or reason." — Jim Simons (told friend, setback was "stomach-wrenching")

- Simons had to find a different approach

## Chapter Four

> Truth . . . is much too complicated to allow for anything but approximations.
> — **John von Neumann**

### Jim Simons was miserable

- Hadn't abandoned flourishing academic career to deal with sudden losses and grumpy investors
- Had to find different method to speculate on financial markets
- Lenny Baum's approach (reliant on intellect and instinct) just didn't seem to work
- Also left Simons deeply unsettled

> "If you make money, you feel like a genius. If you lose, you're a dope." — Jim Simons (told friend)

- Called **Charlie Freifeld** (investor who had made him millionaire speculating on sugar contracts) to share frustrations

> "It's just too hard to do it this way. I have to do it mathematically." — Jim Simons (sounded exasperated)

- Simons wondered if technology was yet available to trade using mathematical models and preset algorithms
- To avoid emotional ups and downs from betting on markets with only intelligence and intuition
- Simons still had **James Ax** working for him
- Mathematician who seemed perfectly suited to build pioneering computer trading system
- Simons resolved to back Ax with ample support and resources, hoping something special would emerge
- For a while, it seemed an investing revolution was at hand

<!-- pp. 73-92 -->

## Chapter 4: James Ax and the Birth of Axcom

### James Ax's Background and Personality

- **James Ax**: acclaimed mathematician with chiseled looks, biting humor, but chronically angry
- Bronx native, attended **Stuyvesant High School**, graduated with honors from **Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn**
- Made notable contributions to microwave physics, radar, US space program
- Father abandoned family when Ax was seven, leaving deep wounds
- Suffered from **Crohn's disease** — stomach pain and fatigue plagued him until late teens
- **1961**: earned PhD in mathematics from **University of California, Berkeley**

### Academic Career at Cornell

- Became friends with **Jim Simons** at Berkeley, greeted Simons after Barbara gave birth
- Professor at **Cornell University**, helped develop **number theory** branch
- Collaborated with **Simon Kochen** (mathematical logician) to solve **Emil Artin's** fifty-year-old conjecture
- Weekly poker game with colleagues in Ithaca — stakes grew to hundreds of dollars
- Ax couldn't beat Kochen at poker, suspected Kochen read his facial expressions
- Summer evening: showed up wearing ski mask to conceal his face — still lost
- **Simon Kochen**: "It wasn't his face. Jim tended to straighten up in his chair when he had a good hand."

### The Ax-Kochen Theorem

- Together solved famous mathematical problem using **techniques from left field** (mathematical logic for number theory problems)
- **1967**: won **Frank Nelson Cole Prize in number theory** (awarded once every five years)
- Ax promoted to full professor at Cornell at age **twenty-nine** — youngest ever

### Move to Stony Brook

- **1969**: received call from Simons to join **Stony Brook's** mathematics department
- Wife Barbara weary of Ithaca's brutal winters, drawn to ocean
- Cornell threatened to register protest with **Governor Rockefeller** over losing Ax
- Soon after arriving at Stony Brook: told colleague mathematicians do best work by age thirty
- Publication rate dwindled, threw himself into poker, chess, fishing — seeking distractions from mathematics
- Battled depression, frequent arguments with wife Barbara
- Rumors of infidelities emerged

### Divorce and Deteriorating Behavior

- After bitter divorce, lost custody of sons **Kevin and Brian** — little contact with boys
- At department meetings, interrupted colleagues so frequently **Leonard Charlap** carried a bell to ring each time Ax cut someone off
- Got into fistfight with associate professor — colleagues pulled them apart
- Despite interpersonal drama, **Michael Fried** turned down tenured position at **University of Chicago** to join Ax at Stony Brook
- Fried: muscular, six-foot athlete with wavy auburn hair, thin mustache — "closest the math world could expect to come to the macho-man look"
- Relationship frayed when Fried suspected Ax appropriating his work without proper credit
- Ax threatened Fried at grievance-airing meeting: **"I'm going to do everything I can to ruin your career, fair or foul"**
- Fried walked out, never spoke to Ax again

### Joining Simons's Trading Venture (1978-1979)

- When Simons first talked to Ax about trading (1978), Ax viewed markets as boring
- Changed mind after visiting Simons's office, seeing **Lenny Baum's** early trading models
- Simons portrayed investing as **ultimate puzzle**, promised to back Ax with own account
- **1979**: Ax joined Simons in strip-mall office near pizza parlor and women's clothing store
- Early work: **trend-following** (moving averages) — tested if average price over 10, 15, 20, or 50 days predicted future moves
- Ax's predictive models had potential but were crude — data riddled with errors and faulty prices
- Trading wasn't automated — made by phone twice daily (morning and end of day)

### Sandor Straus Joins as Data Specialist

- **Sandor Straus**: earned PhD in mathematics from Berkeley (1972), moved to Long Island for teaching job at Stony Brook
- Outgoing, gregarious, strong teaching reviews, wore John Lennon-style glasses, long brown hair in ponytail
- Worried about future — **subpar mathematician**, inept at department politics, under $20,000 salary
- **1976**: joined Stony Brook's computer center helping faculty develop computer simulations
- Spring **1980**: as **Hullender** prepared to leave **Monemetrics**, Ax recommended Straus as computer specialist
- Simons offered to double Straus's salary — torn between security and risky trading firm
- Father and friends advised against leaving steady job, but Straus accepted
- Requested **one-year leave of absence** from Stony Brook rather than resigning

### Straus's Data Obsession

- Ax wanted to invest using **technical analysis** — forecasting based on patterns in past market data
- Straus directed to dig up all historic information to improve predictive models
- Telerate machines (dominating trading floors) didn't have interface for collecting/analyzing data
- Pieced together custom-built database: purchased historic commodity-price data on magnetic tape from **Dunn & Hargitt** (Indiana firm)
- Discovered data feed with **tick data** (intra-day fluctuations) — eventually wrote program on **Apple II** to collect and store it
- Simons and Ax didn't even have way to use all the data Straus gathered — but Straus collected it anyway "in case it came in handy"

### Data Quality Problems

- Straus became obsessed locating pricing data before others realized its value
- Over long stretches, some commodity prices didn't seem to move — twenty minutes with no single trade?
- Odd gap years earlier: no futures trading in Chicago over couple of days (major flood suspended trading)
- **Inconsistencies bothered Straus** — hired student to write programs detecting unusual spikes, dips, gaps
- Working in small windowless office next to Ax, down spiral staircase from Simons
- Painstaking work checking prices against yearbooks from commodity exchanges, futures tables, *Wall Street Journal* archives
- No one had told Straus to worry about prices — **transformed into data purist**, foraging and cleaning data the world cared little about
- Saw himself as **explorer on trail of untold riches** with almost no one in pursuit

> "I'm not going back to that computer center." — Sandor Straus

### Straus's Impact on Trading

- Straus's data helped Ax improve trading results, putting him in rare spirits
- Ax still gambled, played racquetball, bowled, traveled to Las Vegas
- Captured third place in backgammon's **World Amateur Championship** — mentioned in *New York Times*
- **Reggie Dugard** (programmer): "He had to have competition, and he had to win."
- Ax discovered trading as absorbing as any challenge he'd encountered
- He and Straus programmed past price moves into model, hoping to predict future

> "There's something here." — Jim Simons, encouraging new approach

### Henry Laufer Joins

- Simons asked **Henry Laufer** (well-regarded Stony Brook mathematician) to help one day a week
- **Ax**: number theorist; **Laufer**: explored functions of complex numbers — complementary skills
- Distinct personalities — Laufer sometimes brought infant into office in car seat while Ax looked on askance
- Laufer created computer simulations testing whether strategies should be added to trading model
- Strategies based on **mean reversion**: prices tend to revert after initial move higher or lower
- Buy futures contracts that opened at unusually low prices vs. previous close; sell if began day much higher
- Simons made own improvements, insisted team work together and share credit
- Ax had difficulty with request, stressing over recognition and compensation

> "Henry is overstating his role." — Ax complained to Simons
> "Don't worry about it. I'll treat you both equally." — Simons

- For next six months, Simons refused to speak to Laufer (though Laufer was so caught up in work he barely noticed)

### Office Dynamics

- Ax pushed conspiracy theories (especially Kennedy assassination), demanded staff call him "Dr. Ax" (they refused)
- Asked **Penny Alberghine** to tell driver to move car because sun glare bothered him
- **Alberghine**: "He had no personal self-confidence and always took things the wrong way. I would pray that it wouldn't upset him or aggravate him."
- Ax and team making money, but unclear if Simons would keep trading effort going
- When employee received job offer from **Grumman** (defense contractor with free turkey signing bonus), Straus supported decision to leave

### Move to California (1985) — Axcom Limited

- **1985**: Ax surprised Simons with news he was moving to warmer climate for sailing, surfing, racquetball year-round
- Straus also wanted to flee Northeast cold
- Settled in **Huntington Beach, California** (37 miles from Los Angeles) — established **Axcom Limited**
- Simons received **25% of profits**, agreed to provide trading help and communicate with clients
- Ax and Straus managed investments, split remaining **75% ownership**
- Laufer returned to teach at Stony Brook, continued trading with Simons in spare time
- Ax had another motive he didn't share: dealing with enduring sadness from divorce, blamed on ex-wife
- Abandoned his children, much as his father had vanished from his life years earlier
- Wouldn't speak to boys again for more than **fifteen years**

### Huntington Beach Office Setup

- Located on top floor of two-story office park owned by Chevron subsidiary
- Oil wells pumped in parking lot, crude oil smell permeated neighborhood
- No elevator — used stair crawler to get hulking **VAX-11/750** (300 megabytes disk storage) into office
- Immense **Gould superminicomputer** (900 megabytes, size of large refrigerator) moved via truck onto forklift, deposited via second-floor balcony
- **By 1986**: trading **twenty-one different futures contracts** — British pound, franc, deutschmark, Eurodollars, commodities (wheat, corn, sugar)
- Mathematical formulas developed by Ax and Straus generated most moves; few decisions based on Ax's judgment calls
- Computer sent electronic message to broker **Greg Olsen** before trading start and late afternoon
- Example: **"If wheat opens above $4.25, sell 36 contracts"**

### Trading Challenges

- Olsen bought/sold futures via phone to floor brokers at commodity/bond exchanges
- Results of partially automated system sometimes impressive; often frustrating
- Neither Simons nor Huntington Beach team unearthing new ways to make money or improve strategies
- Some rivals had caught on to their approaches
- Simons considered possible influence of **sunspots and lunar phases** — few reliable patterns
- Straus's cousin worked at **AccuWeather** — made deal to review Brazilian weather history to predict coffee prices (proved waste of time)
- Data on public sentiment and holdings of fellow futures traders yielded few dependable sequences

### Ax's California Lifestyle

- Spent time searching for algorithms, but also playing racquetball, learning windsurfing, attending to midlife crisis
- Broad shoulders, muscular build, wavy brown hair — looked like chilled-out surfer, **anything but relaxed**
- Staged intense **weight-loss competitions**, determined to trounce officemates
- Before weigh-in: packed on pounds gorging on melon (calculated he'd quickly shed weight laden with water)
- Furiously biked to work in sun hoping to lose weight — arrived so drenched placed underwear in office microwave to dry (microwave burst into flames)

### Simons's Visits and Smoking Problem

- Several times a year, Simons flew to California to discuss potential trading approaches — visits produced more misery than breakthroughs
- Some staff embraced health-conscious lifestyles; Simons still **chain-smoking three packs of Merits a day**
- Employee: "No one wanted to be with him as he smoked in the office, so we'd go out for lunch and try to get him to work outside as long as we could."
- After lunch, Simons suggested returning to office — team dreaded being cooped up with smoke, manufactured excuses to stay away
- Eventually Ax decided needed to trade in more sophisticated way

### Markov Chains and Stochastic Equations

- Ax believed financial markets shared characteristics with **Markov chains** — sequences of events where next event depends only on current state
- Each step impossible to predict with certainty, but future steps can be predicted with some accuracy via capable model
- When Simons and Baum developed hypothetical trading model at IDA (decade prior), they too described market as Markov-like process
- To improve predictive models, Ax concluded time to bring in someone with experience developing **stochastic equations** (broader family including Markov chains)
- Stochastic equations model *dynamic* processes evolving over time, can involve high level of uncertainty
- Straus recently read academic literature suggesting trading models based on stochastic equations could be valuable tools

### René Carmona Recruited

- **René Carmona**: 41-year-old native of France, later became professor at **Princeton University**
- Didn't know much about markets or investing, but **stochastic differential equations were his specialty**
- These equations make predictions using data appearing random; weather-forecasting models use them
- Axcom team viewed investing through math prism — understood markets to be complicated and evolving, difficult to predict over long stretches (just like stochastic process)
- Simons, Ax, Straus didn't believe market was truly **"random walk"** or entirely unpredictable
- Though clearly had elements of randomness (like weather), mathematicians argued probability distribution could capture futures prices as well as any other stochastic process
- Carmona eager to lend hand — consulting for local aerospace company, liked idea of picking up extra cash working for Axcom few days a week

> "The goal was to invent a mathematical model and use it as a framework to infer some consequences and conclusions. The name of the game is not to *always* be right, but to be right often enough." — René Carmona

- Carmona wasn't certain approach would work, or even that it was much better than less-quantitative strategies embraced by most others

> "If I had a better understanding of psychology or traders on the floor of the exchange, maybe we would do that." — Carmona

### Carmona's Early Work and Frustration

- Used Straus's data to try improving Axcom's existing mathematical models
- Work didn't lead to many useful advances — Carmona's models more sophisticated but didn't seem to work much better
- Later, Renaissance would fully embrace stochastic differential equations for risk management and options pricing, but for now couldn't find way to profit (frustrating Carmona)
- **By 1987**: plagued by guilt — pay came from portion of Ax's personal bonus, yet contributing next to nothing
- Decided to spend summer 1987 working full-time at Axcom hoping more time devoted to models would lead to greater success
- Made little headway, further aggravating him — Ax and Straus didn't seem to mind, but Carmona felt awful

> "I was taking money from them and nothing was really working." — Carmona

### Breakthrough: Nonlinear Regressions

- Axcom had been employing various approaches using pricing data to trade, including relying on **breakout** signals
- Also used simple **linear regressions** — basic forecasting tool analyzing relationships between two data sets under assumption relationships remain linear
- Example: plot crude-oil prices on x-axis, gasoline prices on y-axis, place straight **regression line** through points, extend line → predict prices at pump for given oil price level
- **Problem**: Market prices sometimes all over the place — model dependent on simple linear regressions generally does poor job predicting prices in complex, volatile markets (freak snowstorms, panic selling, turbulent geopolitical events)
- Straus had collected dozens of data sets with closing prices from various historical periods
- **Carmona's idea**: needed regressions capturing **nonlinear relationships** in market data
- Different approach: have computers search for relationships in data Straus amassed
- Perhaps could find instances in trading past of similar trading environments, then examine how prices reacted
- By identifying comparable trading situations and tracking what subsequently happened to prices, could develop sophisticated and accurate forecasting model capable of **detecting hidden patterns**

### Data Modeling Innovation

- For approach to work, Axcom needed *a lot* of data, even more than Straus had collected
- To solve problem, Straus began to **model data** rather than just collect it
- Dealt with gaps in historical data using computer models to make educated guesses about what was missing
- Didn't have extensive cotton pricing data from 1940s, but maybe *creating* data would suffice
- Like inferring what missing jigsaw puzzle piece might look like by observing pieces already in place
- Carmona suggested letting model run show by digesting all various pieces of data and spitting out buy-and-sell decisions
- **Proposing early machine-learning system** — model would generate predictions for various commodity prices based on complex patterns, clusters, correlations Carmona and others didn't understand and couldn't detect with naked eye

### Kernel Methods and Machine Learning

- Elsewhere, statisticians were using similar approaches — called **kernel methods** — to analyze patterns in data sets
- Back on Long Island, **Henry Laufer** working on similar machine-learning tactics in own research, set to share with Simons and others
- Carmona wasn't aware of this work — simply proposing using sophisticated algorithms to give Ax and Straus framework to identify patterns in current prices that seemed similar to those in past

> "You should use this." — Carmona urged colleagues

### Simons's Resistance to "Black Box"

- When they shared approach with Simons, he blanched
- Linear equations they'd been relying on generated trade ideas and capital allocation Simons could understand
- By contrast, wasn't clear why Carmona's program produced its results
- Method wasn't based on model Simons and colleagues could reduce to set of standard equations — bothered him
- Carmona's results came from running program for hours, letting computers dig through patterns then generate trades
- To Simons, it just didn't *feel* right

> "I can't get comfortable with what this is telling me. I don't understand why [the program is saying to buy and not sell]." — Simons told team

- Later, Simons became more exasperated

> "It's a black box!" — Simons said with frustration

### Ax and Carmona Defend the Approach

- Carmona agreed with Simons's assessment, but persisted

> "Just follow the data, Jim. It's not me, it's the data." — Carmona

- Ax (developing friendship with Carmona) became believer in approach, defending it to Simons

> "It works, Jim. And it makes rational sense... humans can't forecast prices." — Ax to Simons

- Let computers do it, Ax urged — exactly what Simons originally hoped to do
- Yet Simons still wasn't convinced of radical approach
- In his head, Simons all-in on concept of relying on models
- His heart wasn't quite there yet, it appeared

> "Jim liked to figure out what the model was doing. He wasn't super fond of the kernel." — Straus recalls

### Building Historical Data and Testing

- Over time, Straus and colleagues created and discovered additional historical pricing data, helping Ax develop new predictive models relying on Carmona's suggestions
- Some weekly stock-trading data they'd later find went back as far as **1800s** — reliable information almost no one else had access to
- At the time, team couldn't do much with data, but ability to search history to see how markets reacted to unusual events would later help Simons's team build models to **profit from market collapses and other unexpected events**, helping firm trounce markets during those periods

### Initial Success with Higher Dimensional Kernel Regression

- When Axcom team started testing approach, quickly began to see improved results
- Firm began incorporating **higher dimensional kernel regression approaches** — seemed to work best for **trending models** (predicting how long certain investments would keep moving in trend)
- Simons convinced they could do even better — Carmona's ideas helped, but weren't enough
- Simons called and visited, hoping to improve Axcom's performance
- Mostly served as **pool operator** — finding wealthy investors for fund, keeping them happy, attending to various technology investments making up about half of $100 million assets now held by firm

### Seeking More Mathematical Firepower

- Seeking even more mathematical firepower, Simons arranged for well-respected academic to consult with firm
- That move would lay groundwork for historic breakthrough

<!-- pp. 93-112 -->

## Chapter 5: Berlekamp Joins (cont'd)

### Kelly's Formula and Bet Sizing
- **John Larry Kelly Jr.** published paper on analyzing information transmitted over networks—strategy also applicable to wagering
- Kelly's system: profit at racetrack by obtaining true odds vs posted odds
- Formula grew from Shannon's information theory work
- Key insight: **importance of sizing bets properly**—accurate information + properly sized wagers = advantage
- Berlekamp had zero interest in finance initially, but Kelly's portfolio theory intrigued him

> "To my shock, all his math was right. I used to think of Southerners as dumb—Kelly changed my view." —Berlekamp

### Berlekamp's Berkeley Years (1964-1986)
- 1964: Deep rut after breakup, accepted UC Berkeley teaching job
- Completed doctorate, became assistant professor in electrical engineering
- Married **Jennifer Wilson** (1966) after noise complaint led to introduction
- Became expert in decoding digital information for NASA satellite images (Mars, Venus)
- Cofounded branch of mathematics: **combinatorial game theory**
- Wrote **Algebraic Coding Theory** (classic textbook)
- Created **Berlekamp's algorithm** for polynomial factorization over finite fields—crucial for cryptography
- Late 1960s: coding theory work gained attention at **Institute for Defense Analyses**
- 1968: began classified work for IDA, spending years in Berkeley and Princeton
- Met Simons at IDA but didn't hit it off initially despite shared MIT/Berkeley/IDA background

> "His mathematics were different from mine. And Jim had an insatiable urge to do finance and make money. He likes action.... I've always viewed poker as a digression, of no more interest to me than baseball or football—which is to say hardly any." —Berlekamp

- Berlekamp returned to Berkeley as professor around time Simons built Stony Brook department
- 1973: Berlekamp became part owner of cryptography company, thought Simons might want stake
- Simons couldn't afford $4 million but served on board—Berlekamp noted he was good listener, made sensible recommendations

### Eastman Kodak Windfall (1985-1986)
- 1985: **Eastman Kodak** acquired Berlekamp's block codes company for satellite communications
- Windfall of several million dollars brought marriage challenges
- Determined to protect wealth, bought top-rated municipal bonds
- Spring 1986: rumor Congress might remove tax-free status of munis—crushed their value
- Congress never acted, but experience taught Berlekamp that investors sometimes act irrationally
- Former roommate warned against stocks: executives "lie to shareholders," making most shares "dicey prospects"
- Roommate suggested commodities instead
- Berlekamp called Simons for commodities advice

### First Visit to Axcom (1988)
- Simons thrilled to receive Berlekamp's call: "I have just the opportunity for you"
- Invited Berlekamp to Huntington Beach couple times a month to learn trading
- Berlekamp flew to office in 1988 with eager anticipation
- **Jim Ax** approached with annoyed look: "If Simons wants you to work for us, he'll have to pay for you. I know I'm not."
- Ax wanted Berlekamp out *right away*—took him aback
- Decided to stick around like George Costanza in *Seinfeld* episode
- Learned Ax and Simons were feuding over who should pay Axcom's mounting expenses

### Axcom's Trading Strategies
- Despite brainpower and help from **Sandor Straus** and others, Axcom's model focused on two simple strategies:
  1. **Chased prices**: bought commodities moving higher/lower, assuming trend would continue
  2. **Reversion strategy**: wagered price moves petering out would reverse
- Ax had superior pricing data thanks to Straus's clean historic data collection
- Price movements often resembled past patterns—enabled better determination of trend continuation vs ebbing
- Computing power improved, became cheaper—enabled more sophisticated models including Carmona's **kernel methods** (early machine learning)
- Axcom averaged annual gains ~20%, topping rivals
- Yet Simons kept asking why returns weren't better

### Competition Heating Up
- Rivals multiplying—**John Murphy** (Merrill Lynch analyst) published *Technical Analysis of the Financial Markets*
- Buying expensive/selling cheap contradicted academic theory (buy cheap/sell expensive)
- **Warren Buffett** and big-name investors embraced *value* investing
- Aggressive traders including hedge-fund manager **Paul Tudor Jones** adopted trend following similar to Simons's approach
- Simons needed new approaches to stay ahead

### Berlekamp's Critique of Axcom
- Told Ax: Axcom's models didn't size trades properly—should buy/sell larger amounts when model showed better chance of profit
- Precepts learned from Kelly: "We ought to be loading up here"
- Ax unimpressed, replied halfheartedly: "We'll get to that"
- Berlekamp discovered other problems:
  - Firm traded gold, silver, copper, hogs, meats, grains, other commodities
  - Buy/sell orders emailed to broker **Greg Olsen** at open/close each day
  - Axcom held investments for weeks/months at a time
  - **Dangerous approach**: markets volatile, infrequent trading precluded jumping on new opportunities, led to losses during extended downturns
  - Urged shorter-term opportunities—get in and get out
- Ax brushed him off, citing cost of rapid trading
- Besides, Straus's intraday data riddled with inaccuracies—not "cleaned" yet—couldn't create reliable short-term model
- Ax consented to giving Berlekamp research assignments but mostly ignored recommendations—called them "tinkering"

### Axcom's 1987 Success
- 1987: Axcom scored double-digit returns, sidestepping October crash (Dow plummeted 22.6%)
- Ignoring trading model, Ax presciently purchased Eurodollar futures which soared, helping offset losses
- Word spreading: Simons had math wizards attempting new strategy
- **Edward Thorp** (pioneering quantitative trader) showed interest but canceled meeting after due diligence

> "I learned Simons was a chain-smoker and going to their offices was like walking into a giant ashtray." —Thorp (moved to Newport Beach, California)

### Limroy Shutdown, Medallion Launch (March 1988)
- Some clients didn't have faith in Simons's venture-capital adventures
- To keep investors, Simons shut down Limroy in March 1988
- Sold off venture investments, launched offshore hedge fund with Ax focused solely on trading
- Named fund **Medallion** in honor of prestigious math awards each had received
- Within six months, Medallion suffering—some losses traced to shift in Ax's focus

### Ax's California Isolation
- After moving to California, Ax rented quiet home with boat slip in Huntington Harbor (5 miles from office)
- Soon searched for more isolated spot, eventually renting seaside estate in Malibu
- Ax never truly enjoyed company of others, especially coworkers
- Became even more detached, managing ~dozen employees remotely
- Went into office just once a week
- Sometimes Berlekamp flew in for meeting only to discover Ax hadn't budged from Malibu
- After marrying accountant **Frances**, became even less inclined to travel
- Sometimes called to make requests entirely unrelated to algorithms/predictive models

> "Okay, so what kind of cereal do you want me to bring?" —employee overheard saying to Ax

- As Ax became more disengaged, Axcom's results deteriorated

> "The research wasn't as aggressive. When the boss isn't present, the dynamics aren't the same." —Carmona

### Ax's Eccentricities
- **Competent mathematician but incompetent research manager** —Berlekamp
- Looking for more seclusion, Ax purchased spectacular home on cliff in Pacific Palisades atop hill overlooking Santa Monica Mountains
- Carmona drove there once a week to bring food, books, necessities
- Engaged in grueling paddle tennis matches while Carmona listened to conspiracy theories
- Colleagues saw Ax as hermit, theorizing he chose coastal homes to avoid dealing with people on at least one side
- After staffer installed salt lick in yard to attract deer, Ax spent long stretches staring from window
- Relied on instincts for part of portfolio, edging away from sophisticated models he and Straus developed
- Much as Baum drifted toward traditional trading years earlier, Simons initially uncomfortable with Carmona's "kernels"
- Quantitative investing didn't come naturally, even to math professors
- Ax figured West Coast *New York Times* printed in Torrance (~40 miles away), arranged next day's paper delivered just after midnight
- Made trades in overnight international markets based on government official comments in paper
- Installed enormous TV screens to monitor news, communicate with colleagues via video
- Drove white Jaguar, played racquetball, spent time on mountain bike
- At one point fell headfirst, prompting emergency brain surgery
- Firm's results strong first half 1988, then losses hit
- Ax confident rebound imminent, but Simons grew concerned
- Squabbling again—Ax wanted to upgrade computers (faster trading), but no way Simons would pay
- Simons resisted writing checks
- Tensions grew, Ax complained Simons wasn't meeting share of responsibilities

### The Breaking Point (Spring 1989)
- By spring 1989, Ax developed healthy respect for Berlekamp—fellow world-class mathematician sharing competitive streak
- Still wasn't implementing Berlekamp's trading suggestions
- Realized in a bind, few others around to listen to complaints about Simons
- One day Ax looked somber when Berlekamp visited
- Fund losing money for months, now down nearly 30% from middle of previous year
- Axcom's soybean-futures holdings collapsed when Italian conglomerate attempt to corner market came undone
- Mounting competition from other trend followers also having effect
- Ax showed Berlekamp letter from Simons's accountant **Mark Silber**:
  - Ordering Axcom to halt all trading based on struggling longer-term predictive signals
  - Until Ax and team produced plan to revamp/improve operations
  - Simons would only allow short-term trading (10% of activity)
- Ax furious—he was in charge of trading, Simons's job was handling investors

> "How can he stop me from trading? He *can't* close me down!" —Ax, voice rising

- Ax remained certain fund's performance would rebound
- Trending strategies require living through tough periods when trends ebb (new ones often around bend)
- Simons's trading halt violated partnership agreement
- Ax going to sue Simons

> "He's been bossing me around too long!" —Ax

- Berlekamp tried to calm Ax down
- Lawsuit costly, take forever, might not succeed
- Besides, Simons had good argument: Technically Axcom was trading for general partnership controlled by Simons—legal right to determine firm's future
- Ax didn't realize it, but Simons dealing with own pressures
- Old friends/investors calling, worried about steep losses
- Some couldn't take pain, withdrew cash
- When Simons dealt with Straus and others at office, was curt
- All could see losses mounting, mood soured
- Simons decided Ax's strategies too simple
- Only way to prevent clients from bailing, keep firm alive: curtail long-term trades (causing losses) while reassuring investors they'd develop new/improved tactics
- Ax didn't want to hear it
- Set out for Huntington Beach to elicit colleague support
- He had little luck—Straus didn't want to pick sides, was uncomfortable in middle of escalating battle
- Ax became enraged

> "How can you be so disloyal!" —Ax screaming at Straus

- Straus didn't know how to respond: "I sat there feeling stupid"
- Simons spent >decade backing various traders, attempting new investment approach
- Hadn't made much headway—Baum flamed out, Henry Laufer wasn't around much
- Fund with Ax/Straus down to $20 million amid mounting losses
- Simons spending more time on side businesses than trading
- Heart didn't seem to be in investment business
- Straus and colleagues convinced Simons might shutter firm

> "It wasn't clear Jim had any faith. And it wasn't clear if we would survive or fold." —Straus

- Straus and wife spent hours at night preparing for worst, calculating spending habits, tallying accumulated wealth
- Two young children played nearby in den
- Discussed where they might move if Simons closed Axcom, gave up trading
- Back in office, bickering between Simons and Ax continued
- Straus listened as Ax screamed over phone at Simons and Silber
- All became too much

> "I'm going on vacation. You guys work this out." —Straus finally told Ax

### Berlekamp's Buyout Offer (Summer 1989)
- By summer 1989, Ax felt boxed in—using second-tier lawyers on contingency while Simons employed top-flight New York attorneys
- Obvious Simons would outlast him in legal fight
- One day, Berlekamp presented idea: "Why don't I buy your stake in the firm?"
- Privately, Berlekamp beginning to think he might turn Axcom around
- Only spending day or two each month at firm
- Wondered how it might fare if he focused full attention on improving trading system
- No one figured out how to build computer system to score huge gains—maybe Berlekamp could help

> "I was hooked on the intellectual exercise." —Berlekamp

- Ax decided he didn't have better option, agreed to sell most Axcom shares to Berlekamp
- After deal completed:
  - Berlekamp owned 40% of firm
  - Straus and Simons with 25% each
  - Ax retained 10%
- Ax holed up in home for months, speaking to wife and few others
- Eventually began slow, remarkable transformation
- Ax and wife moved to San Diego, where he finally learned to relax a bit
- Wrote poetry, enrolled in screenwriting classes
- Completed science-fiction thriller called *Bots*
- Went online, read academic paper about quantum mechanics by **Simon Kochen**
- Decided to reconnect with former Princeton colleague
- Soon collaborating on academic papers about mathematical aspects of quantum mechanics
- Emptiness remained—tracked down younger son **Brian**
- One day picked up phone to call Brian in dormitory room at Brown University (Providence, RI)
- Hadn't spoken in >15 years

> "Hi. This is James Ax." —tentative beginning

- Spoke for hours that evening, first of series of lengthy, intense conversations
- Ax shared regrets about abandoning boys, acknowledged damage anger caused
- Boys forgave Ax, eager to have father back in lives
- Over time, Ax and sons forged close relationships
- 2003: After becoming grandfather, he and **Barbara** (ex-wife) reunited, established unlikely friendship
- Three years later, age 69, Ax died of colon cancer
- On tombstone, sons engraved formula representing **Ax-Kochen theorem**

## Chapter 6: Berlekamp Takes Control

### 1980s Financial Context
- Summer 1989: financial companies claimed ~10% of US profits
- Era of greed/self-indulgence captured by *Bright Lights*, *Big City*, Madonna's "Material Girl"
- **Information advantage** fueled Wall Street gains—tips about takeovers, earnings, new products were currency
- **Michael Milken** pocketed >$1 billion in compensation 1983-1987 before insider trading investigation landed him in jail
- Others joined: **Martin Siegel**, **Ivan Boesky** (exchanged takeover info, briefcases with hundreds of thousands in $100 bills)
- By 1989, **Gordon Gekko** (*Wall Street*) defined business's aggressive, cocksure professionals
- Berlekamp was anomaly: academic with little use for juicy rumors/hot tips
- Barely knew how companies earned profits, zero interest in learning

### Berlekamp's Profile
- Approaching 49th birthday, bore little physical resemblance to Wall Street masters
- Valued physical fitness: extreme/unsafe diets, grueling bicycle rides
- Lost so much weight looked emaciated, worrying colleagues
- Balding, bespectacled, neat salt-and-pepper beard
- Rarely wore ties, stored up to 5 multicolored BIC pens in front pocket
- Even among computer nerds gaining prominence, Berlekamp stood out
- 1989 Carmel, CA conference on machine-built predictive models: seemed most absentminded professor

> "Elwyn was a little disheveled, his shirttail out and wrinkled, and his eyes darting around when he was thinking hard. But he was so smart, I saw past the quirks and wanted to learn from him." —**Langdon Wheeler**

- Around Axcom office: favored lengthy tangents/digressions, causing hand-wringing
- Said he liked to do 80% of talking in conversation—those who knew him viewed estimate conservative
- Reputation as mathematician earned respect
- Confidence that Medallion could improve performance bred optimism

### Moving to Berkeley (September 1989)
- First plan: move firm closer to Berkeley home
- Straus and wife came to support decision
- September 1989: Straus leased offices on 9th floor historic 12-story **Wells Fargo Building** (UC Berkeley's first high-rise)
- Short walk from campus
- Existing hardwire lines couldn't deliver accurate prices fast enough
- Staffer arranged satellite receiver atop **Tilden Tower** in nearby Oakland to transmit up-to-the-minute futures prices
- Month later: San Francisco rocked by **Loma Prieta earthquake** (killed 63)
- Axcom's new office didn't suffer serious damage, but shelves/desks collapsed, books/equipment damaged, satellite receiver toppled
- Inauspicious start for desperate trading operation

### Implementing Berlekamp's Vision
- Team forged ahead, Berlekamp focused on implementing promising recommendations Ax ignored
- Simons exhausted from months bickering with Ax, supported idea

> "Let's bank some sure things." —Berlekamp to Simons

- Ax resisted shifting to more frequent short-term trading, partly worried about:
  - Brokerage commissions/costs from fast-paced, higher-frequency approach offsetting profits
  - Rapid trading pushing prices enough to cut into gains (**slippage**)—Medallion couldn't measure with accuracy
- Legitimate concerns led to unwritten Wall Street rule: Don't trade too much
- Beyond costs, short-term moves generally yield tiny gains, exciting few investors
- What's point of working hard, trading frequently if upside so limited?

> "Like with baseball, motherhood, and apple pie, you just didn't question that view." —Berlekamp

- Berlekamp hadn't worked on Wall Street, inherently skeptical of long-held dogmas
- Suspected weren't especially sophisticated in analysis
- He advocated for more short-term trades
- Too many long-term moves had been duds, while Medallion's short-term trades proved biggest winners (thanks to Ax, Carmona, others)
- Made sense to build on that success
- Berlekamp enjoyed good timing—by then, most Straus's intraday data cleaned up, easier to develop fresh ideas for shorter-term trades

### The Philosophy: Technical Trading
- Goal: scrutinize historic price information to discover sequences that might repeat
- Assumption: investors exhibit similar behavior in future
- Simons's team viewed approach as sharing similarities with **technical trading**
- Wall Street establishment viewed technical trading as dark art
- Berlekamp and colleagues convinced it could work if done sophisticated/scientific manner
- **But only if trading focused on short-term shifts rather than longer-term trends**

### Casino Analogy
- Buying/selling infrequently magnifies consequences of each move
- Mess up couple times, portfolio doomed
- Make lots of trades, each individual move less important, reducing overall risk
- Berlekamp and colleagues hoped Medallion could resemble gambling casino
- Just as casinos handle so many daily bets they only need to profit from bit more than half, Axcom wanted fund to trade so frequently it could score big profits making money on bare majority of trades
- With slight statistical edge, law of large numbers would be on their side (just as for casinos)

> "If you trade a lot, you only need to be right 51 percent of the time. We need a smaller edge on each trade." —Berlekamp to colleague

### Short-Term Trading Oddities
- As scrutinized data looking for short-term strategies, began identifying intriguing oddities
- Prices for some investments often fell just before key economic reports, rose right after
- But prices didn't *always* fall before reports came out, didn't *always* rise in moments after
- Whatever reason, pattern didn't hold for **US Department of Labor's employment statistics** and some other data releases
- But enough data to indicate when phenomena most likely to take place
- Model recommended purchases just before economic releases, sales almost immediately after
- Searching for more, Berlekamp got on phone with **Henry Laufer**
- Laufer agreed to spend more time helping Simons turn Medallion around after Ax quit
- Was in basement of Simons's Long Island office with couple research assistants from Stony Brook area trying to revamp Medallion's model (just as Berlekamp/Straus doing in Berkeley)

### Day-of-Week Patterns
- Sifting through Straus's data, Laufer discovered recurring sequences based on day of week
- Monday's price action often followed Friday's
- Tuesday saw **reversions** to earlier trends
- Laufer uncovered how previous day's trading often can predict next day's activity
- Something he termed **twenty-four-hour effect**
- Medallion model began to buy late in day on Friday if clear up-trend existed, then sell early Monday
- Taking advantage of what they called **weekend effect**

### Currency Markets: Deutsche Marks
- Oddities in currency markets represented additional attractive trades
- **Deutsche marks** seemed especially rich in trading opportunity
- When currency rose one day, had surprising likelihood of climbing next day as well
- When fell, often dropped next day too
- Didn't matter if team looked month-to-month, week-to-week, day-to-day, even hour-to-hour correlations
- Deutsche marks showed unusual propensity to trend from one period to next
- Trends lasted longer than one might expect
- No correlation from one coin flip to next (25% chance getting heads twice in row)
- By contrast, Straus/Laufer/Berlekamp determined correlation of price moves in deutsche marks between any two consecutive time periods was as much as **20%**
- Meaning sequence repeated >half the time
- By comparison:
  - Team found correlation between consecutive periods 10% or so for other currencies
  - 7% for gold
  - 4% for hogs and other commodities
  - Just 1% for stocks

> "The time scale doesn't seem to matter. We get the same statistical anomaly." —Berlekamp to colleague with surprise

### Challenging the Efficient Market Hypothesis
- Correlations from one period to next shouldn't happen with any frequency
- At least according to most economists at time who embraced **efficient market hypothesis**
- Under this view: impossible to beat market by taking advantage of price irregularities—they shouldn't exist
- Once irregularities discovered, investors should step in to remove them
- Sequences witnessed in deutsche mark trading (even stronger correlations in yen) so unexpected team felt need to understand why might be happening
- Straus found academic papers arguing global central banks have distaste for abrupt currency moves
- Can disrupt economies, so they step in to slow sharp moves either direction
- Thereby extending trends over longer periods
- To Berlekamp: slow pace at which big companies like Eastman Kodak made business decisions suggested economic forces behind currency shifts likely played out over many months

> "People persist in their habits longer than they should." —Berlekamp

### Tradeable Effects
- Currency moves part of Medallion's growing mix of **tradeable effects**
- Berlekamp/Laufer/Straus spent months poring over data, working long hours glued to computers
- Examining how prices reacted to tens of thousands of market events
- Simons checked in daily (in person or phone), sharing own ideas to improve trading system while encouraging team to focus on uncovering "subtle anomalies" others overlooked
- Beyond repeating sequences that seemed to make sense, system spotted barely perceptible patterns in various markets with no apparent explanation
- Trends/oddities happened so quickly they were unnoticeable to most investors
- So faint, team took to calling them **ghosts**
- Yet kept reappearing with enough frequency to be worthy additions to mix of trade ideas
- Simons came around to view that *whys* didn't matter, just that trades worked

### Straus's Data Advantage
- As researchers worked to identify historic market behavior, wielded big advantage: more accurate pricing information than rivals
- For years, Straus collected **tick data** featuring intraday volume/pricing for various futures
- Even as most investors ignored such granular information
- Until 1989, Axcom generally relied on opening/closing data like most other investors
- To that point, much of intraday data Straus collected was pretty much useless
- But more modern, powerful **MIPS (million instructions per second)** computers in new offices gave firm ability to quickly parse all pricing data in Straus's collection
- Generating thousands of statistically significant observations within trading data to help reveal previously undetected pricing patterns

> "We realized we had been saving intraday data. It wasn't super clean, and it wasn't all the tick data, but it was more reliable and plentiful than what others were using." —Straus

### Late 1989: Confidence Building
- After ~6 months work, Berlekamp and colleagues reasonably sure rebuilt trading system (focused on commodity/currency/bond markets) could prosper
- Some anomalies/trends lasted days, others hours or even minutes
- Berlekamp and Laufer confident revamped system could take advantage
- Team found difficult to pinpoint reliable trends for stocks, but didn't seem to matter
- Found enough trading oddities in other markets
- Some trading signals weren't especially novel/sophisticated
- But many traders ignored them
- Either phenomena took place barely >50% of time, or didn't seem to yield enough profit to offset trading costs
- Investors moved on, searching for juicier opportunities
- Like fishermen ignoring guppies in nets, hoping for bigger catch
- By trading frequently, Medallion figured worthwhile to hold on to all guppies they were collecting

### Implementation: Late 1989
- Firm implemented new approach late 1989 with $27 million Simons still managed
- Results almost immediate, startling nearly everyone in office
- Did more trading than ever
- Cutting Medallion's average holding time to just day and half from week and half
- Scoring profits almost every day

### Early Problems: Canadian Dollar Manipulation
- Suddenly, problems arose
- Whenever Medallion traded Canadian dollars, fund seemed to lose money
- Almost every trade was dud
- Didn't make sense—model said Medallion should be racking up money, but losing over and over every day
- One afternoon, Berlekamp shared frustrations with Simons
- Simons called trader on floor of Chicago Board of Trade to get his take on problems

> "Don't you know, Jim? Those guys are crooks." —trader with chuckle

- Only 3 traders on exchange focused on Canadian dollar futures
- Worked hand-in-hand to take advantage of customers naive enough to transact with them
- When Simons's team placed buy order, brokers shared information, immediately purchased Canadian dollar contracts for themselves
- Pushing price up just a tad before selling to Simons, pocketing difference as profit
- Do opposite if Medallion was selling
- Small differences in price were enough to turn Canadian dollar trades into losers
- One of Wall Street's oldest tricks
- Berlekamp and fellow academics oblivious to practice
- Simons immediately eliminated Canadian dollar contracts from Medallion's trading system

### Stotler Group Crisis (Early 1990)
- Few months later (early 1990), Simons called Berlekamp with even more unsettling news

> "There's a rumor Stotler is in trouble." —Simons, anxiety in voice

- Berlekamp stunned
- Every single Medallion position held in accounts at **Stotler Group** (commodity-trading firm run by **Karsten Mahlmann**, top elected official at Chicago Board of Trade)
- Berlekamp/others viewed Stotler as safest, most reliable brokerage firm in Chicago
- If Stotler went under, account would be frozen
- In weeks it would likely take to sort out, tens of millions of dollars of futures contracts would be in limbo
- Likely leading to devastating losses
- Straus's sources at exchange confided Stotler struggling with heavy debt
- Just rumors though
- Shifting all trades/accounts to other brokers would be cumbersome, time-consuming, cost Medallion money just as turning things around
- Stotler had long been among most powerful, prestigious firms—suggesting could survive any setback
- Berlekamp told Simons he was unsure what to do
- Simons couldn't understand indecision

> "Elwyn, when you smell smoke, you get the *hell* out!" —Simons

- Straus closed brokerage account, shifted trades elsewhere
- Months later: Mahlmann resigned from Stotler and Chicago Board of Trade
- Two days later: Stotler filed for bankruptcy
- Eventually, regulators charged firm with fraud
- **Simons and firm narrowly escaped likely death blow**

### 1990: Success
- Much of 1990, Simons's team could do little wrong
- As if discovered magic formula after decade fumbling around in lab
- Rather than transact only at open/close of trading each day, Berlekamp/Laufer/Straus traded at noon as well
- System became mostly short-term moves, long-term trades representing ~10% of activity
- One day, Axcom made >$1 million (first for firm)
- Simons rewarded team with champagne (much as IDA staff passed around flutes after discovering solutions to thorny problems)
- One-day gains became so frequent drinking got out of hand
- Simons sent word champagne should be handed out only if returns rose 3% in day
- Shift did little to dampen giddiness
- For all gains, few outside office shared same regard for group's approach
- When Berlekamp explained firm's methods to business students on Berkeley campus, some mocked him

> "We were viewed as flakes with ridiculous ideas." —Berlekamp

- Fellow professors polite enough not to share criticism/skepticism, at least within earshot
- But Berlekamp knew what they were thinking

> "Colleagues avoided or evaded commenting." —Berlekamp

<!-- pp. 113-132 -->

## Chapter 6 (continued): Breakthrough

### Medallion's 1990 Success

- **Medallion gained 55.9% in 1990**, recovering from 4% loss in 1989
- Profits came after fund's hefty fees: **5% management fee + 20% performance fee**
- Simons increasingly convinced automated trading worked, wanted bigger role in fund
- Called Berlekamp almost daily, now fully engaged after years focused on side businesses

### Simons's Manual Trading Contradictions

- Despite pushing systematic approach, **Simons still traded commodities manually**
- During Iraq-Kuwait invasion (August 1990), called Berlekamp about adding gold/oil futures
- Berlekamp refused to adjust algorithms based on Simons's chart analysis
- Simons bought oil call options as "insurance" when Gulf War began, scaled positions back one-third

> "The system will determine what we trade." — Elwyn Berlekamp

- **Fundamental tension**: Simons championed removing humans from trading but couldn't resist news-driven hunches
- Spent 5-10 hours/week trading gold/copper manually, "thinking he was learning something"

### Rising Pressure and Berlekamp's Exit

- Simons kept calling with expansion requests: more staff, satellite dishes, infrastructure upgrades
- Fund managing nearly **$40 million** by late 1990
- Simons projected **80% returns** for next year, shocking Berlekamp
- Berlekamp remained part-time Berkeley professor, enjoying teaching more as Simons demanded more involvement

> "Jim was calling a lot, and I was having more fun teaching." — Elwyn Berlekamp

- **December 1990**: Axcom disbanded
  - Simons bought out Berlekamp's stake for cash
  - Straus and Ax traded Axcom shares for Renaissance equity
  - Berlekamp returned to Berkeley full-time, sold shares at **6x what he paid 16 months earlier**
  - Later founded **Berkeley Quantitative** (managed $200M+ before closing 2012)

> "It never occurred to me that we'd go through the roof." — Elwyn Berlekamp

> "I was always motivated more by curiosity. Jim was focused on money." — Elwyn Berlekamp

- Berlekamp died spring 2019 from pulmonary fibrosis complications, age 78

### Simons's Confidence Despite Competition

- Berlekamp, Ax, and Baum all departed, but Simons unfazed
- Believed he'd developed **systematic investing** using computers/algorithms for commodities, bonds, currencies
- Didn't realize approach wasn't novel — pattern recognition centuries old, many similar traders had crashed

> "Simons was a mathematician with a limited understanding of the history of investing, however. He also wasn't aware of how many traders had crashed and burned using similar methods."

- Faced "imposing obstacles that he didn't even realize were in his way"

## Chapter 7: The History of Systematic Trading

### Ancient Roots of Pattern Recognition

- **Babylonian times**: traders recorded barley/dates prices on clay tablets to forecast moves
- **16th century Germany**: **Christopher Kurz** forecasted 20-day spice prices using astrology + back-testing signals
- **18th century Japan**: **Munehisa Homma** ("god of the markets") invented **candlestick charting** for rice exchanges
  - Created reversion-to-mean strategy
  - "Markets are governed by emotions... speculators should learn to take losses quickly and let profits run"

### Modern Technical Analysis Pioneers

- **1830s Britain**: economists sold price charts to investors
- **Charles Dow**: created Dow Jones Industrial Average, launched *Wall Street Journal*
  - Applied mathematical rigor to market hypotheses
  - Birthed **technical analysis**: charting price trends, volume, patterns

### William D. Gann (Early 20th Century)

- **Texas cotton ranch** background, quit school to help family
- Opened NYC brokerage 1908, reputation for reading price charts and anticipating cycles
- Guided by Ecclesiastes: "That which has been is that which shall be... there is nothing new under the sun"
- Claimed historic reference points unlock trading profits
- Legend: turned **$130 into $12,000** in one month
- Predicted Great Depression, Pearl Harbor attack
- Developed **Law of Vibration**: geometric sequences/angles predict market action
- **Gann analysis** remains popular in technical trading

> "He was a financial astrologer of sorts." — Andrew Lo, MIT Sloan

- **Record dubious**: 1936 claimed "Dow will never sell at 386 again" (wrong)
- Wrote 8 books, penned daily newsletter, yet died with net worth of only **$100,000**

### Gerald Tsai Jr. (1960s)

- Used technical analysis to become **most influential investor of late 1960s**
- Prominence at **Fidelity Investments**: rode momentum stocks, first growth-fund manager
- Launched **Manhattan Fund** with war room: sliding/rotating charts tracking hundreds of averages/ratios/oscillators
- Kept room **55°F** to keep staff alert
- **Crushed in 1969-70 bear market**; sold out to insurance company
- Later helped build Primerica into Citigroup foundation

### Technical Trading's Mixed Reputation

- Became targets of derision: simplistic, lazy, "voodoo science"
- Despite ridicule, many investors still chart markets: **head and shoulders**, other formations
- **Stanley Druckenmiller** consults charts to confirm investment theses
- **Professor Andrew Lo**: technical analysts were "forerunners" of quantitative investing
- But methods never subjected to independent/thorough testing; rules arose from "mysterious combination of human pattern recognition and reasonable-sounding rules of thumb"

### Early Computer-Driven Trading

#### Richard Dennis (1970s-80s Chicago)

- **Chicago-based trader**: built systematic trading governed by preset rules to remove emotions/irrationality
- Age 26: distinctive presence on Chicago Board of Trade floor ("Prince of the Pit")
- **Confident system**: codified rules, shared with 20+ recruits called "turtles"
- Staked newbies with cash, sent them to trade independently
- Made **$80M in 1986**, managed **~$100M/year** by 1987
- **Crushed in 1987 crash**: latest trader with Simons-like style to burn
- Later took break for liberal politics, marijuana legalization

> "There is more to life than trading." — Richard Dennis

#### Rise of "Quants" (1980s)

- Applied mathematicians/ex-physicists recruited to Wall Street/City of London
- Built models for derivatives, mortgage products, risk analysis
- Activities became known as **financial engineering**
- Initially called **"rocket scientists"** (rocketry = most advanced science)
- Later: **quants** (short for quantitative finance specialists)
- **Emanuel Derman** (Columbia physics PhD → Goldman Sachs 1985): term was pejorative

> "People around you averted their gaze... it was bad taste for two consenting adults to talk math or UNIX or C in the company of traders, salespeople, and bankers." — Emanuel Derman, *My Life as a Quant*

#### October 19, 1987: Black Monday

- Dow plunged **23%**, largest one-day decline ever
- Blamed on **portfolio insurance**: hedging technique where computers sold stock-index futures at first sign of decline
- Selling triggered more computerized selling → eventual rout

> "The beginning of the destruction of markets by dumb computers. Or, to be fair to the computers, by computers programmed by fallible people and trusted by people who did not understand the computer programs' limitations." — Floyd Norris, *New York Times*

#### Benoit Mandelbrot and Fractals

- 1980s: **Professor Benoit Mandelbrot** demonstrated **fractals** (jagged math shapes) mimic irregularities in nature
- Argued financial markets also have **fractal patterns**
- Markets deliver **more unexpected events** than widely assumed
- Reinforced views of **Nassim Nicholas Taleb**: popular math/risk models incapable of preparing investors for **large unpredictable deviations** from historic patterns

### Why Quants Weren't Allowed to Trade

- Usually hired to help traders/stay out of the way, not trade themselves
- **Barr Rosenberg** (Berkeley economics professor): developed quantitative models to track stock factors
  - Sold computerized programs to help others forecast behavior (didn't trade himself)

#### Edward Thorp: First Modern Mathematician to Invest Sizable Sums

- Academic who worked with **Claude Shannon** (father of information theory)
- Embraced **John Kelly's proportional betting system** (influenced Berlekamp)
- First applied talents to **gambling**: prominence for large winnings
- Bestselling book **_Beat the Dealer_**: outlined systematic, rules-based gambling tactics + shifting odds insight

**1964: Thorp Turns to Wall Street**

- Read technical analysis books + **Benjamin Graham/David Dodd's _Security Analysis_** (fundamental investing foundations)

> "Surprised and encouraged by how little was known by so many." — Edward Thorp, *A Man for All Markets*

- Zeroed in on **stock warrants** (purchase shares at certain price)
- Developed formula for "correct" warrant price, detected mispricings instantly
- Programmed **Hewlett-Packard 9830** to buy cheap warrants, bet against expensive ones
- Protected portfolio from broader market jolts

**1970s: Princeton/Newport Partners**

- Helped lead hedge fund with strong gains
- Attracted well-known investors: **Paul Newman**, producer **Robert Evans**, screenwriter **Charles Kaufman**
- Trading based on computer-generated algorithms/economic models
- Southern California office always boiling hot (electricity usage)

**Louis Bachelier's Influence**

- Thorp's formula influenced by **Louis Bachelier's 1900 doctoral thesis**
- Priced Paris stock exchange options using equations similar to those later employed by **Albert Einstein** for Brownian motion
- Thesis overlooked for decades before Thorp/others recognized relevance

**1974: Wall Street Journal Front Page**

- "Computer Formulas Are One Man's Secret to Success in Market"
- Year later: driving new red **Porsche 911S**

> "A model is a simplified version of reality, like a street map that shows you how to travel from one part of the city to another. If you got them right, [you] could then use the rules to predict what would happen in new situations." — Edward Thorp

**Fund Closure (1988)**

- Thorp's fund stood at nearly **$300M**, dwarfing Simons's **$25M** Medallion
- **Princeton/Newport** ensnared in junk-bond scandal (Michael Milken, Los Angeles)
- Thorp never accused of impropriety; government dropped all charges
- Publicity crippled fund; closed late 1988 ("traumatic")
- 19-year existence: annual gains averaging **>15%** after fees, topping market returns

> "Were it not for the government's actions, 'we'd be billionaires.'" — Edward Thorp

### Gerry Bamberger and Pairs Trading (Morgan Stanley, 1980s)

- Columbia computer-science grad provided analytical/technical support for Morgan Stanley stock traders
- Created software to update traders' results (many bristled at computer help)
- Observed: buying big **blocks** of shares → prices moved higher; selling blocks → prices moved lower
- Trading altered **spread** between paired stocks even with no news
- Example: selling Coke chunk → Coke down 1-2 points while Pepsi barely moved
- Spread reverted to norm after Morgan Stanley activity subsided

**Bamberger's Opportunity**

- If bank tracked historic prices of paired stocks, could profit betting on spread reversion after block trades/unusual activity
- Bosses swayed: gave him **$500,000** + small staff
- Developed programs to exploit "temporary blips" of paired shares
- Orthodox Jew, heavy smoker, wry humor: brought **tuna sandwich in brown bag** for lunch daily
- By 1985: implementing strategy with **6-7 stocks at a time**, managing **$30M**, scoring profits for Morgan Stanley

**Nunzio Tartaglia Replaces Bamberger**

- Morgan Stanley gave Bamberger new boss: **Nunzio Tartaglia** (perceived insult)
- Bamberger quit, joined **Ed Thorp's hedge fund** (similar trades, eventually retired a millionaire)
- Short, wiry astrophysicist **Tartaglia**: sharper edges than Bamberger
- Brooklyn native, Wall Street veteran

> "Don't try to get anything by me because I come from out there." — Nunzio Tartaglia (pointing to NYC streets)

**Automated Proprietary Trading (APT)**

- Tartaglia renamed group **Automated Proprietary Trading (APT)**
- Moved to 40-foot room on 19th floor, Morgan Stanley midtown Manhattan headquarters
- Added automation; by 1987 generating **$50M annual profits**
- Team members didn't know stocks traded — strategy: wager on re-emergence of historic relationships between shares

**Statistical Arbitrage (Stat Arb)**

- New hires including Columbia computer-science professor **David Shaw**, mathematician **Robert Frey** improved profits
- Morgan Stanley traders among first to embrace **statistical arbitrage (stat arb)**
- Lots of concurrent trades, most uncorrelated to overall market
- Aimed at exploiting statistical anomalies/market behavior
- Software ranked stocks by gains/losses over previous weeks
- APT sold **short** top 10% winners within industry, bought bottom 10% losers
- Expectation: trading patterns revert
- Didn't always happen, but implemented enough times → **20% annual profits**
- Likely because investors overreact to good/bad news before calming, restoring historic stock relationships

**APT's Downfall (1988)**

- Among largest/most-secretive trading teams in world
- Buying/selling **$900M shares daily**
- Hit heavy losses; Morgan Stanley executives slashed capital by two-thirds
- Senior management never comfortable with computer model reliance; jealousies grew about Tartaglia's earnings
- Tartaglia out of job; group shut down

> "Morgan Stanley had squandered some of the most lucrative trading strategies in the history of finance."

### Robert Frey's Factor Investing and Kepler Financial

- Before APT closed, **Robert Frey** became anxious
- Heavyset man with limp (youth fall, shattered leg/hip)
- Convinced rivals catching on to statistical-arbitrage strategies
- Thorp's fund already doing similar trades

**Frey's Innovation: Deconstructing Stock Movements**

- Proposed identifying **independent variables** responsible for stock moves
- Exxon surge could be from: oil prices, dollar value, overall market momentum, etc.
- Procter & Gamble rise: healthy balance sheet + growing demand for safe stocks (investors souring on debt-heavy companies)
- Selling robust-balance-sheet stocks + buying heavy-debt stocks = bet on performance gap reverting to historic bounds

**Factor Investing**

- Handful of investors/academics mulling **factor investing**
- Frey wondered if computational statistics/math techniques could better isolate true factors moving shares

**Morgan Stanley's Rejection**

> "They told me not to rock the boat." — Robert Frey

- Frey quit, contacted **Jim Simons**, won financial backing to start **Kepler Financial Management**
- Frey + few others set up dozens of small computers to bet on statistical-arbitrage strategy
- Almost immediately: threatening letter from Morgan Stanley lawyers
- Frey hadn't stolen anything; approach developed working for Morgan Stanley
- In luck: **Tartaglia** hadn't allowed team to sign nondisclosure/noncompete agreements (wanted option to take team to rival if bonuses disappointed)
- Morgan Stanley had no strong legal grounds to stop Frey's trading
- With trepidation, Frey ignored threats and began trading

### David Shaw's D. E. Shaw (1988)

- By 1990, Simons had high hopes for **Frey/Kepler** stock success
- Even more enthused about Medallion + quantitative strategies in bond/commodity/currency markets
- Competition building; some rivals embracing similar strategies

**Simons's Biggest Competition: David Shaw**

- After leaving Morgan Stanley APT in 1988, **30-something David Shaw** (Stanford PhD) courted by Goldman Sachs
- Unsure whether to accept job offer
- Discussed options with hedge-fund manager **Donald Sussman** while sailing on Long Island Sound

> "I think I can use technology to trade securities." — David Shaw

- Sussman suggested Shaw start own hedge fund rather than work for Goldman
- Offered **$28M initial seed investment**
- Shaw swayed, launched **D. E. Shaw** in office above **Revolution Books** (communist bookstore, Union Square, Manhattan)
- First moves: purchased **two Sun Microsystems ultrafast/expensive computers**

> "He needed Ferraris. We bought him Ferraris." — Donald Sussman

**Shaw's Hiring Strategy**

- Supercomputing expert hired math/science PhDs embracing scientific trading approach
- Also hired from different backgrounds: English/philosophy majors, chess master, stand-up comedians, published writers, Olympic fencer, trombone player, demolitions specialist

> "We didn't want anyone with preconceived notions." — early D. E. Shaw executive

**D. E. Shaw Office Culture**

- Unlike boisterous Wall Street trading rooms: quiet, somber (like Library of Congress research room)
- Employees wore jeans/T-shirts
- Early internet days; academics only ones using email
- Shaw gushed to programmer about internet's possibilities

> "I think people will buy things on the internet. Not only will they shop, but when they buy something... they're going to say, 'this pipe is good,' or 'this pipe is bad,' and they're going to post reviews." — David Shaw

**Early Employee: Jeff Bezos**

- Programmer **Jeffrey Bezos** worked with Shaw few more years before moving to Seattle with then-wife **MacKenzie**
- Worked on laptop in van while traveling
- Business plan for company **Amazon.com** (originally chose "Cadabra", dropped because confused with "Cadaver")

**D. E. Shaw's Rapid Success**

- Almost immediately after starting engines, Shaw's hedge fund minted money
- Soon managing **several hundred million dollars**
- Trading array of equity-related investments
- Boasting **100+ employees**

**Simons's Challenge**

- Simons didn't have clear understanding of Shaw/others' progress
- If building something special to catch up with head start, needed help
- Called **Donald Sussman** (financier who gave Shaw support) hoping for similar boost

<!-- pp. 133-152 -->

## Chapter 8 (continued)

### Henry Laufer Joins Medallion

- **Straus** ran trading, data collection at Renaissance but lacked research ability to find hidden signals
- Simons turned to **Henry Laufer**, mathematician who had shown flair for creative solutions
- Laufer finished undergrad at City College of New York and grad school at Princeton in two years each
- Made progress on functions of complex variables and discovering **embeddings** (structures within other math structures)
- At Stony Brook (1971), focused on complex variables and algebraic geometry
- Personal life: bookish introvert who carried a slide rule, eager to marry
- Married **Marsha Zlatin**, speech-language pathology professor with upbeat personality who earned PhD

### Laufer's Transition to Trading

- Academics who shift to trading often turn nervous about market moves
- Laufer (forty-six) had different reaction: improved pay relieved stress about daughters' college costs
- Laufer became Simons's **best partner yet** after years of dealing with Baum, Ax, Berlekamp's complicated personalities
- Simons became Renaissance's big-picture guy: wooing investors, attracting talent, planning emergencies
- Laufer led research in Stony Brook office; Straus ran trading in Berkeley

### The Single Model Decision

- Laufer made crucial decision: **Medallion would employ a single trading model** rather than multiple models for different investments
- Most quant firms used collection of models for different market conditions
- Single model could draw on Straus's vast pricing data, detecting correlations and signals across various asset classes
- Narrow individual models suffer from too little data
- A single, stable model based on core assumptions about price behavior made it easier to add new investments later
- Could add investments with little trading data if deemed similar to other heavily-traded investments

### Five-Minute Bars: The Data Revolution

- Team broke trading week into ten segments (five overnight, five day sessions)
- Simons wondered if finer segmentation might reveal new patterns
- Laufer split the day in half, then quarters, eventually settling on **five-minute bars**
- Improved computer power made analyzing small slices of historic data feasible
- Example patterns emerged: bar 188 in cocoa-futures regularly fell on nervous days; bar 199 usually rebounded
- Bar 50 in gold saw strong buying on inflation-worry days; bar 63 often showed weakness

### Discovering Nonrandom Trading Effects

- Five-minute bars revealed new trends, oddities, and **nonrandom trading effects**
- Straus conducted tests to ensure signals weren't bogus; many held up
- Early discovery: certain trading bands from Friday morning predicted bands that same afternoon near close
- If markets moved higher late in day, often paid to buy futures just before close and dump them at next day's opening

### Predictive Effects and Combination Effects

- Team found predictive effects related to volatility
- Series of **combination effects**: propensity of paired investments (gold/silver, heating oil/crude oil) to move together at certain times vs. others
- Signals worked if they had **p-values** (probability values) under 0.01—statistically significant with low probability of being mirages

### The Betting Algorithm

- Simons challenged team to solve: how much to bet on each trade given limited capital?
- Which moves to pursue and prioritize?
- Laufer developed computer program to identify optimal trades: the **betting algorithm**
- Dynamic, adapting in real-time based on probabilities of future market moves—**early form of machine learning**

> "Our system is a living thing; it's always modifying. We really should be able to grow it." —Jim Simons

### Building the Team

- Only dozen employees; needed full staff to catch up to D.E. Shaw and industry powers
- **Kresimir Penavic**: Stony Brook PhD student interviewed for job
- Simons, wearing torn pants and penny loafers with cigarette dangling, wandered over during interview
- Simons dismissed Penavic's undergrad work as "trivial stuff"—most devastating put-down a mathematician could deliver
- Then Penavic mentioned unsolved algebraic problem paper; Simons insisted "That problem is *not* trivial"
- Simons started grinning: "I like you, though." Penavic was hired

### Nick Patterson: The Skeptical Cryptologist

- **Nick Patterson** joined around same time
- Patterson suspicious Simons was running a scam
- 1992: Medallion enjoyed third straight year of returns topping 33% as Laufer's short-term tactics paid off
- Not just the returns or $100 million under management—it was the *way* Simons racked up profits using computer model he and employees didn't fully understand
- Renaissance office: top floor of nineteenth-century home on North Country Road, Stony Brook
- Nine people crammed in, working on Simons-backed businesses including venture-capital investments and stock traders downstairs
- Patterson so tight on space he pushed chair/desk into empty corner of Simons's own office

### Patterson's Background

- Born in Bayswater, central London; suffered **facial dysplasia** (rare disorder distorting left face, rendering left eye blind)
- Sent to Catholic boarding school; unable to speak with parents more than once a week
- Turned classroom prowess into advantage: "I evolved into the school brain, a British stock character. I was seen as odd but useful, so they left me alone"
- Attracted to mathematics because über-competitive; gratifying to dominate
- At sixteen discovered he actually enjoyed math
- After University of Cambridge, took job writing commercial code—proved natural, gaining advantage over fellow mathematicians who didn't know programming

### Patterson's Chess and Poker Skills

- Strong chess player at London coffee shop renting chess boards
- Regular trounced players many years his senior
- Deduced shop was front for illegal, high-stakes poker game run by local thug
- Gained entrance; became stud at poker, pocketing fistfuls of cash
- Tough guy noticed Patterson's abilities, made offer: hustle chess downstairs, share winnings, he'd handle losses
- Patterson rejected: "Are you nuts? You can't make any money in *mathematics*"
- Experience taught Patterson to distrust moneymaking operations, even legitimate ones—why he was skeptical of Simons

### Patterson's Cryptology Career

- Thrived as cryptologist for British government after grad school
- Built statistical models to unscramble intercepted messages, encrypt secret messages
- Unit made famous during WWII when **Alan Turing** broke Germany's encryption codes
- Harnessed **Bayes' theorem of probability**: updating initial beliefs with new, objective information leads to improved understandings
- Solved long-standing problem, deciphering pattern others missed
- Became so valuable that top-secret documents shared with allies were labeled **"For US Eyes Only and for Nick Patterson"**

> "It was James Bond stuff." —Nick Patterson

- When new pay scale elevated administrators above cryptologists, Patterson became livid: "It was the insult, not the money. I had to get out of there"
- Moved to Institute for Defense Analyses, met Simons and Baum
- Approaching fiftieth birthday, worried about money (two children preparing for college)

### Patterson Joins Renaissance

- Senior colleague got permission to travel to Russia for amateur-radio conference
- Patterson realized Cold War was ending; had to act fast: *I'm going to lose my job!*
- Simons called urgently: "We need to talk. Will you work for me?"
- Move made sense: Simons's group analyzing messy pricing data to predict future prices
- Patterson's natural skepticism valuable for discerning true signals from market noise
- Programming skills would help
- Unlike many Renaissance employees, Patterson read business pages, knew a bit about finance: "I thought I was pretty cutting-edge because I owned an index fund"

### Patterson's Worldview

- Saw world "becoming extremely mathematical"
- Knew computer firepower expanding exponentially
- Sensed Simons had opportunity to revolutionize investing by applying high-level math and statistics

> "Fifty years earlier, we couldn't have done anything, but this was the perfect time." —Nick Patterson

### Verifying Renaissance Wasn't a Fraud

- After lugging computer into corner of Simons's office, Patterson helped Laufer with stubborn problem
- Profitable trade ideas only half the game; buying/selling can affect prices, whittling away gains
- Meaningless to know copper will rise from $3.00 to $3.10 if your buying pushes price to $3.05 before completing transaction
- Dealers and rivals can slash profits by half

### Transaction Costs and "The Devil"

- From earliest days, team wary of transaction costs called **slippage**
- Compared trades against model tracking how much firm *would have* profited/lost without trading costs
- Coined name for difference between prices they got and theoretical trades model made without costs: **The Devil**
- For a while, actual size of The Devil was a guess
- As Straus collected more data and computers became more powerful, Laufer and Patterson wrote program tracking how far trades strayed from ideal state (trading costs barely weighing on performance)
- By time Patterson arrived at Renaissance, firm could run simulator subtracting trading costs from prices received, isolating losses

### Reducing Market Impact

- To narrow gap, Laufer and Patterson developed sophisticated approaches directing trades to various futures exchanges
- Reduced market impact of each trade
- Medallion could better determine which investments to pursue—huge advantage for trading new markets
- Added German, British, Italian bonds; interest-rate contracts in London; later futures on Nikkei Stock Average, Japanese government bonds, more
- Fund began trading more frequently: first five times a day, eventually sixteen times a day
- Reduced impact on prices by focusing on periods when volume was highest
- Medallion's traders still had to pick up phone to transact, but fund was moving toward faster trading

### Why the Signals Worked

- Until then, Simons and colleagues hadn't spent much time wondering *why* their algorithms predicted prices so presciently
- They were scientists and mathematicians, not analysts or economists
- If signals were statistically significant, that was enough to include them

> "I don't know why planets orbit the sun. That doesn't mean I can't predict them." —Jim Simons (suggesting one needn't understand *why* market patterns exist to predict them)

### Spectacular 1994 Returns

- Returns piling up fast, getting absurd
- Medallion soared over 25% just in June 1994, heading to **71% surge** that year
- Simons described as "simply remarkable"
- Even more impressive: gains came in year Federal Reserve surprised investors by hiking interest rates repeatedly, leading to deep losses for many

### Who Was on the Other Side?

- Renaissance team and investors curious: if Medallion was big winner in most trades, who was on other side suffering steady losses?
- Over time, Simons concluded losers probably weren't infrequent traders (buy-and-hold individual investors) or even "treasurer of a multinational corporation" adjusting foreign currency portfolios occasionally
- Instead, Renaissance was **exploiting foibles and faults of fellow speculators**, big and small

> "The manager of a global hedge fund who is guessing on a frequent basis the direction of the French bond market may be a more exploitable participant." —Jim Simons

### Laufer's Explanation: Dentists

- Laufer had slightly different explanation for heady returns
- When Patterson asked about source of money being raked in, Laufer pointed to different set of traders: those infamous for excessive trading and overconfidence predicting market direction

> "It's a lot of dentists." —Henry Laufer

### The Behavioral Economics Revolution

- Laufer's and Simons's perspectives can be seen as profound, even radical
- At the time, most academics convinced markets were inherently efficient—no predictable ways to beat market's return
- Financial decision-making of individuals was largely rational
- Simons and colleagues sensed professors were wrong
- Believed investors prone to **cognitive biases** leading to panics, bubbles, booms, busts
- New strain of economics emerging to validate instincts: In 1970s, Israeli psychologists **Amos Tversky** and **Daniel Kahneman** explored how individuals make decisions, demonstrating irrationality
- Economist **Richard Thaler** used psychological insights to explain anomalies in investor behavior, spurring growth of **behavioral economics**
- Field explored cognitive biases of individuals and investors, including:
  - **Loss aversion**: investors feel pain from losses twice as much as pleasure from gains
  - **Anchoring**: judgment skewed by initial piece of information or experience
  - **Endowment effect**: investors assign excessive value to what they already own

### Nobel Prizes and Market Inefficiency

- Kahneman and Thaler would win Nobel Prizes for their work
- Consensus emerged: investors act more irrationally than assumed, repeatedly making similar mistakes
- Investors overreact to stress, make emotional decisions
- No coincidence Medallion made largest profits during times of extreme market turbulence—phenomenon that would continue for decades

### Simons Maintained Faith in the Model

- Like most investors, Simons became nervous during rocky times
- In rare circumstances, reacted by paring firm's overall positions
- On whole, maintained faith in trading model
- Recalled how difficult it had been to invest using his instincts
- Made commitment to refrain from overriding model, ensuring neither Medallion's returns nor employee emotions influenced fund's moves

> "Our P&L isn't an input. We're mediocre traders, but our system never has rows with its girlfriends—that's the kind of thing that causes patterns in markets." —Nick Patterson

### Modeling Human Behavior

- Simons hadn't embraced statistics-based approach because of economists or psychologists
- Hadn't set out to program algorithms to avoid or exploit investor biases
- Over time, Simons and team came to believe errors and overreactions were at least partially responsible for profits
- Developing system seemed uniquely capable of taking advantage of common mistakes of fellow traders

> "What you're really modeling is human behavior. Humans are most predictable in times of high stress—they act instinctively and panic. Our entire premise was that human actors will react the way humans did in the past . . . we learned to take advantage." —Kresimir Penavic

## Chapter 9

### The Challenge of Stock Trading

- Jim Simons seemed to have discovered perfect way to trade commodities, currencies, bonds: predictive mathematical models
- To grow Renaissance to anything meaningful, he'd have to get computers to make money in stocks
- Wasn't clear why Simons thought he had chance of success
- Early 1990s was golden age for **fundamental investors**: those who chat up companies, digest annual reports, financial filings à la Warren Buffett
- About brainpower, not computing power
- When it came to stocks, Simons seemed well out of his depth

### Peter Lynch and Fundamental Investing

- **Peter Lynch** was paragon of fundamental approach
- From 1977 to 1990, Lynch's prescient stock picks helped Fidelity Investments' **Magellan mutual fund** grow from $100 million pip-squeak to $16 billion power
- Averaging annual gains of 29%, beating market in eleven of those years
- Ignoring historic and overlooked pricing patterns (stuff Simons obsessed over), Lynch said investors could trounce market by sticking with companies they understood best

> "Know what you own" —Peter Lynch's mantra

### Lynch's Story Stocks

- Searching for *story stocks* he believed would experience surging earnings
- Made killing on **Dunkin' Donuts** (doughnut retailer beloved in Fidelity's Massachusetts home state)
- Purchased partly because company "didn't have to worry about low-priced Korean imports"
- Another time, Lynch's wife Carolyn brought home pair of **L'eggs** (pantyhose in distinctive egg-shaped plastic containers sold in supermarket/drugstore checkout aisles)
- Carolyn loved L'eggs, so her husband backed up truck to buy shares of manufacturer **Hanes**
- Even though most hosiery products sold in department stores and women's clothing stores, not drugstores
- Lynch did research: found average woman goes to supermarket or drugstore once a week vs. woman's specialty store or department store once every six weeks
- "All the good hosiery, all the good pantyhose, is being sold in department stores. They were selling junk in the supermarkets"
- When rival brand introduced, Lynch bought forty-eight pairs, had employees test them, determined couldn't match quality of L'eggs
- Over time, Lynch rode Hanes to gain of ten times fund's initial investment

### Lynch's Communication Tools

- Most important tool was telephone, not computer
- Regularly called or visited network of well-placed executives for business updates, competitor/supplier/customer info
- Legal tactics at time, even though smaller investors couldn't access same information

> "The computer won't tell you [if a business trend] is going to last a month or a year." —Peter Lynch

### Lynch's Influence

- By 1990, one out of every one hundred Americans was invested in Magellan
- Lynch's book *One Up on Wall Street* sold more than a million copies
- Inspired investors to search for stocks "from the supermarket to the workplace"
- As Fidelity came to dominate mutual funds, began sending young analysts to call on hundreds of companies each year
- Lynch's successors (including **Jeffrey Vinik**) used trips to gain legal information advantage over rivals
- **J. Dennis Jean-Jacques** (Fidelity analyst): "Vinik would ask us to have conversations with cabdrivers on our way from and to the airport to get a sense of the local economy or the particular company we were visiting. We would also eat in the company cafeteria . . . or at a nearby restaurant, so we could ask the waiter questions about the company across the street"

### Bill Gross: The Bond King

- As Lynch and Vinik racked up gains in Boston, **Bill Gross** was on other side of country on shores of Newport Beach, California
- Building bond empire at company called **Pacific Investment Management Company (PIMCO)**
- Gross paid his way through business school with blackjack winnings after reading Ed Thorp's book on gambling
- Especially adept at predicting direction of global interest rates
- Became well known for thoughtful, colorful market observations and unique look
- Each day, wore open-collared, custom-made dress shirts with tie draped loosely around neck
- Style adopted after vigorous exercise and yoga sessions left him overheated and unwilling to knot tie in office
- Like Simons, Gross used mathematical approach to dissect investments
- Gross melded formulas with heavy dose of intuition and intelligence
- Emerged as true market savant in 1995 after huge wager on falling interest rates generated gains of 20% for bond mutual fund
- Became largest ever of its kind
- Investors crowned him **"the Bond King"**, name that would stick as Gross began extended reign atop debt markets

### Macro Investors

- Around same time, so-called **macro investors** grabbed headlines, instilled fear in global political leaders with their own distinct style
- Instead of placing thousands of bets like Simons, these traders made bulk of profits from limited number of gutsy moves aimed at anticipating global political and economic shifts

### Stanley Druckenmiller

- **Stanley Druckenmiller** was one of traders on ascent
- Shaggy-haired Pittsburgh native who dropped out of PhD program in economics
- Top-performing mutual-fund manager before taking over **George Soros**'s billion-dollar hedge fund, the **Quantum Fund**
- Thirty-five years old at time
- Arrived at investment decisions after scrutinizing news, studying economic statistics and other information
- Aimed to place trades well ahead of big global events
- Only took six months for Soros to regret hiring Druckenmiller
- As Druckenmiller flew to Pittsburgh, Soros dumped bond positions without warning, worried they were losers
- Apprised of move after
<!-- pp. 153-172 -->

## Druckenmiller's German Currency Bet (1990-1992)

### Berlin Wall Falls, Deutsche Mark Bet Begins

- After Druckenmiller's airport meltdown and resignation, Soros gave him a second chance with six-month European trip
- **Berlin Wall opened** (late 1989) — investors feared **deutsche mark** would collapse as West Germany merged with poorer East Germany
- Druckenmiller saw opposite: cheap labor influx would strengthen German economy, and German central bank obsessed with inflation would prop up currency

> "I had a very strong belief that the Germans were obsessed with inflation. There was no way they would let the currency go down."

- Druckenmiller placed huge bet on deutsche marks — **Quantum Fund gained nearly 30% in 1990**

### British Pound Short (1992)

- Two years later (1992), Druckenmiller approached Soros with prediction: Britain would break from **European Exchange Rate Mechanism**, pound would fall
- Druckenmiller's stance unpopular but confident — Soros initially reacted with bewilderment

> "That doesn't make sense," Soros told him.

- Before Druckenmiller could defend thesis, Soros cut him off

> "Trades like this only happen every twenty years or so." — **George Soros** (urging Druckenmiller to expand bet)

- Quantum Fund sold short **$10 billion** of British currency
- Other rival funds arrived at same conclusion, creating coordinated pressure on pound
- September 16, 1992: British government abandoned efforts to prop up pound, **devaluing currency 20%**
- **Druckenmiller and Soros earned over $1 billion in 24 hours**
- Fund gained **over 60% in 1993**, controlled over **$8 billion** in investor cash
- Trade considered greatest ever for more than a decade

## Renaissance Struggles with Stock Trading

### Jim Simons and Statistical Arbitrage

- While Druckenmiller dominated macro trading, **Jim Simons** still struggling to make money in stocks
- **Kepler Financial** (launched by former Morgan Stanley quant **Robert Frey**, backed by Simons) plodding along
- Kepler strategy: **statistical arbitrage** using market-wide factors (stock sensitivity to overall market, oil prices, interest rates)
- Applied to pairs trading: buy stocks that underperformed based on historic factor returns, short stocks that overperformed
- Searched for **trading errors** — deviations from patterns not fully explained by historic data, assuming they'd revert

### Market Neutral Strategy

- Betting on **relationships between stock groups**, not outright market direction — portfolio was **market neutral**
- Frey's models focused on **reversion-to-the-mean** strategy
- Constructing diversified portfolio dampened volatility, produced high **Sharpe ratio** (risk-adjusted returns measure)
- Kepler renamed **Nova**, later subsumed into **Medallion**

### The Problem: Actual vs. Predicted Returns

- Frey's system good at identifying profitable trades and forecasting group movements
- **Problem**: profits paled compared to model predictions
- Like "chef with delicious recipe who cooked memorable meals but dropped most on way to dinner table"

### Renaissance Frustration with Stock Models

- Renaissance staffers (Laufer, Patterson, others) losing patience with Frey
- Their commodities system featured **betting algorithm** adjusting holdings based on probability ranges
- Frey's stock system had nothing comparable for stocks
- Staffers complained Frey's model **too sensitive to tiny market fluctuations** — bought/sold shares before they had chance to rise
- Too much market noise for Frey's system to hear signals

## Two IBM Oddballs Join Renaissance

### Robert Mercer's Background

#### Father: Thomas Mercer
- **Thomas Mercer**: brilliant scientist, world expert on **aerosols**
- Professor of radiation biology/biophysics at University of Rochester
- Department head of foundation curing respiratory disease in Albuquerque, New Mexico
- Showed son Robert punch cards of **IBM 650** (earliest mass-produced computers)

#### Robert's Computer Obsession
- At age 10, Thomas explained computer workings — Robert created own programs in oversize notebook
- Carried notebook for years before accessing actual computer
- At **Sandia High School** and **University of New Mexico**: chess club, auto club, Russian club member
- Won top honors in national mathematics contest (1964)
- **National Youth Science Camp** (West Virginia): discovered donated **IBM 1620** computer, played all summer
- Learned **Fortran** programming language
- **Neil Armstrong** visited camp five years before moon landing, told campers about computer technology in space program

> "I couldn't see how that would ever be possible." — **Robert Mercer**

#### University and IBM Career
- While studying physics/chemistry/mathematics at University of New Mexico, worked at **Kirtland Air Force Base** weapons lab to access supercomputer
- Loved "solitude of computer lab late at night, air-conditioned smell, sound of discs whirring, printers clacking"
- **Mid-1960s computer culture**: young specialists stayed up late **coding** (writing instructions for computers using algorithms)
- Counterculture rebels exploring future

> "We suffered socially and psychologically for being right." — **Aaron Brown** (early coder, became quant-trading executive)

- Summer job: rewrote electromagnetic fields program, made it **100 times faster** — bosses didn't care, ran old computations at faster speed instead
- Left Mercer cynical about **government-financed research**

> "I took this as indication that one of most important goals of government-financed research is not so much to get answers as it is to consume the computer budget."

#### IBM Speech-Recognition Group (1972)
- Earned **PhD in computer science** at University of Illinois
- Joined **IBM** (1972), dismissive of company's computers
- Impressed by **Thomas J. Watson Research Center** (Yorktown Heights) — hard-charging staffers discovering innovations
- Joined **speech-recognition group**

### Peter Brown's Background

#### Father: Henry Brown
- At age 17 (1972), Peter watched father **Henry Brown** face business challenges
- Henry and partner created world's **first money-market mutual fund** (higher rates than bank savings)
- Peter stuffed envelopes, mailed letters to potential customers
- Henry worked every day except Christmas, ate peanut-butter sandwiches, took second mortgage
- Wife **Betsey** worked as family therapist

> "A combination of starvation and pure greed drove us." — **Henry Brown** to *Wall Street Journal*

- Lucky break: **New York Times article** (next year) about fledgling fund
- Soon managing **$100 million** in **Reserve Primary Fund**
- Fund grew to billions, but Henry resigned (1985) to move to Virginia farm, raise cattle on 500 acres
- Also competed in **trebuchet** competitions (mechanical catapult)
- **Decade-long feud** with former partner **Bruce Bent** over company control, lawsuit filed
- Deal reached (1999) — Brown sold half-ownership to Bent
- (2008: Fund lost massive money from Lehman Brothers debt, troubles spread throughout financial system)

#### Peter's Path to IBM
- Peter anxious about finances despite family wealth, reserved ambitions for science/math
- Graduated **Harvard University** with undergraduate degree in mathematics
- Joined **Exxon** unit developing speech-recognition technology
- Earned **PhD in computer science** from **Carnegie Mellon University** (Pittsburgh)
- Joined **IBM's speech group** (1984, age 29) where Mercer worked

### IBM Speech-Recognition Team

#### Revolutionary Approach to Language
- Team led by **Fred Jelinek** — viewed language differently from traditionalists
- Language modeled like **game of chance**: any point in sentence, certain probability of what comes next
- "Pie" more likely to follow "apple" than "him" or "the"
- Similar probabilities exist for pronunciation

#### Statistical Model Development
- Goal: feed computers enough recorded speech and written text to develop **probabilistic, statistical model**
- Computer wouldn't *understand* what it was transcribing, but would learn to transcribe nonetheless
- Viewed sounds as output of sequence where each step is random yet dependent on previous step — **hidden Markov model**
- Employed **Baum-Welch algorithm** (codeveloped by Simons's trading partner **Lenny Baum**) to zero in on language probabilities
- Rather than manual programming, created program that **learned from data**

#### Bayesian Mathematics
- Relied on **Bayesian mathematics** (from **Reverend Thomas Bayes**, 18th century)
- Bayesians attach probability to every guess, update estimates as they receive new information
- Continuously narrows range of possibilities
- Example: spam filter assigns odds to emails, constantly learning from previous classifications
- Approach natural — linguists say people unconsciously guess next words in conversation, updating expectations

### IBM Team Culture

#### Robert Mercer's Personality
- Tall, fit, jumped rope to stay in shape
- Resembled actor **Ryan Reynolds** as younger man
- Laconic, efficient style — few words, avoided speaking unless necessary
- Sometimes yelled **"I cracked it!"** after solving difficult computation
- Generally hummed or whistled classical music all day
- Didn't drink coffee, tea, alcohol — stuck with **Coca-Cola**
- When frustrated, yelled **"bull-twaddle"** (amalgam of "bullshit" and "twaddle")
- Wife sewed dress shirts with extended sleeves due to long arms
- Arrived office **6 a.m.**, met colleagues for lunch **11:15 a.m.**
- Ate same thing daily: peanut-butter-and-jelly or tuna sandwich in reusable Tupperware or folded brown paper bag
- Ate potato chips in order of size: broken ones first, then smallest to largest
- Friday afternoons: team met for soda, tea, cookies, coffee cake
- Occasionally shared sections from **etymological dictionary**
- Once declared he thought he'd **live forever**

#### Peter Brown's Personality
- More animated, approachable, energetic
- Thick, curly brown hair, infectious charm
- Forged friendships within group, sneaky sense of humor

#### Team Dynamics and Culture
- Brown showed impatience with intern **Phil Resnik** (grad student from University of Pennsylvania, later Harvard academic)
- Grabbed marker from Resnik's hand during whiteboard session, sneered **"This is kindergarten computer science!"**
- Brown developed insulting nicknames for junior colleagues
- Called **Meredith Goldsmith** (only woman): **"Merry Death"**, **"Jennifer"** (previous member's name), **"little Miss Meredith"**
- Mercer shared opinion women belonged at home, not working world
- Brown (whose wife headed NYC public health) viewed himself as progressive, valued Goldsmith's contributions, said she was like daughter
- Didn't stop inappropriate jokes in locker-room environment

> "They told dirty jokes all the time; it was a sport." — **Meredith Goldsmith**

> "In a sense they were both nice and sexist to me. I definitely felt objectified and not taken seriously."

- Goldsmith eventually quit due to uncomfortable environment
- **Fierce, ruthless culture** inspired by Jelinek's ornery personality
- Researchers posted ideas, colleagues eviscerated them with personal jabs
- Twin brothers **Stephen and Vincent Della Pietra** (Princeton undergrad physics, Harvard physics doctorates) raced to whiteboard for vicious intellectual combat
- **David Magerman** (intern): **"We ripped each other to shreds. And then we played tennis together."**

#### Brown's Commercial Instincts
- Beyond nicknames, Brown stood out for commercial instincts (father's influence)
- Urged IBM to use team's advances to sell products (credit-evaluation service)
- Tried to manage **IBM pension-fund investments** with statistical approach — failed to garner support
- Learned of Carnegie Mellon team programming computer to play chess
- Convinced IBM to hire team — use publicity when machine beat world champion
- Team brought **Deep Thought program**
- Machine's name caused problems — reminded people of **1972 pornographic film *Deep Throat***
- Wife of chess team member (Catholic college teacher) and nun sister kept referring to "IBM's amazing Deep Throat program"
- IBM renamed machine **Deep Blue** (nod to IBM's "Big Blue" nickname)
- **1997**: millions watched **Deep Blue defeat Garry Kasparov**, chess world champion

### Breakthrough in Translation
- Team made progress transcribing speech
- Brown realized probabilistic models could also translate
- Used data from thousands of pages of **Canadian parliamentary proceedings** (paired French/English passages)
- Made headway toward translating text between languages
- Advances laid groundwork for computational linguistics/speech processing revolution
- Influenced future tech: **Amazon Alexa, Apple Siri, Google Translate**, text-to-speech synthesizers

### Frustration and Family Tragedy
- Despite progress, frustrated by **IBM's lack of clear commercialization plan**
- Weeks after Patterson threw his letter in garbage, Brown and Mercer forced to reexamine life direction
- **Late-winter 1993** (southeastern Pennsylvania): Mercer's mother killed, sister injured in ice-skid car crash
- That Easter (20 days later): **Mercer's father succumbed to progressive illness**
- Few months later: Patterson called asking why no response to previous letter
- Mercer began considering move
- Third daughter starting college, family lived in modest split-level home near electrical power lines
- Eating lunch from used brown paper bags losing charm

> "Just come and talk to me. What have you got to lose?" — **Nick Patterson**

## Brown and Mercer Recruited to Renaissance

### Initial Skepticism
- Mercer skeptical hedge funds added anything to society
- Another IBM staffer said trading effort "hopeless" because markets so efficient
- Mercer impressed by Renaissance's **Stony Brook campus offices** in high-tech incubator
- Originally chemistry lab (tiny windows high up) — layout suggested science focus, not finance
- Brown heard of Simons, but accomplishments meant little (Simons was geometer, different field)
- When Brown learned Simons's original partner was **Lenny Baum** (coinventor of **Baum-Welch algorithm** used by IBM speech team), became more enthused
- Simons's wife **Margaret** gave birth to first child, Brown faced own financial concerns

> "I looked at our newborn daughter, and thought about Bob struggling with college bills, and began to think that it might actually make some sense to work in the investment area for a few years."

### Joining Renaissance (1993)
- Simons offered to **double Brown's and Mercer's salaries**
- Both came on board **1993** — just as tension building over firm's continued stock trading struggles
- Some urged Simons to terminate Frey's effort — spent enough time, didn't have much to show
- Futures team said Frey should give up stock research, work on projects with them
- Publicly and privately, **Simons defended Frey**

> "Let's just wait a little longer." — **Jim Simons**

> "That's good work. Never give up." — **Jim Simons** to Frey

### Brown and Mercer's Role
- Arrived from IBM, split up initially
- Mercer sent to futures group, Brown helped Frey with stock picks
- Simons hoping to integrate them into firm like kids in classroom (feared they'd only talk to each other)
- In spare time, Brown and Mercer met, searching for ways to solve Simons's stock dilemma
- Thought they might have solution
- For true breakthrough, needed help from another unusual IBM staffer

<!-- pp. 173-192 -->

## Chapter 10 (continued): The Stock-Trading System Crisis

### Frey's Model Problems

- **Mercer** diagnosed the core issue with Frey's system: "There's many a slip 'twixt the cup and the lip"
- System generated brilliant trade ideas but implementation failed—something prevented executing trades and making money
- Frey admitted: "I wasn't the best person to get the trains running on time"
- **Brown-Mercer partnership**: Brown (blunt, argumentative, loud, energetic) paired with Mercer (reserved, emotionally controlled, poker-faced)
- Brown acknowledged Mercer's influence: "Time and time again, I would come up with some idea and then realize that it was just something that Bob had told me to try months before"

### Fatal Flaws in Frey's Stock Model

- **Leverage limits**: Nova fund faced broker-imposed limits on borrowed money—when leverage crossed threshold, Frey and staffers manually overrode model recommendations
- **Unavailable stocks**: Model recommended shorting stocks that weren't actually available to sell
- **Missed trades = systemic risk**: Unlike futures (where missed trades had few consequences), stock trading's intertwined portfolio meant failing to execute a few moves made the entire portfolio more sensitive to market shifts, jeopardizing overall health
- Missed trades cascaded into bigger problems that compromised model accuracy
- Mid-1990s technology and subpar software engineering skills couldn't handle the complexity
- Frey: "It was like finding a common solution to hundreds of equations simultaneously"

### Brown-Mercer's Revolutionary Solution

- **Automated single system**: Programmed all limitations and qualifications into one trading system that automatically handled complications
- **Computer science advantage**: Their IBM experience with large-scale software gave them the coding skills Renaissance lacked
- **Math problem approach**: Treated challenge like language recognition at IBM—inputs were trading costs, leverages, risk parameters, limitations
- System solved to construct ideal portfolio, making optimal decisions all day long to maximize returns
- **Adaptive system**: Self-correcting, like Laufer's futures system—if recommended trades weren't executed, it searched for buy-or-sell orders to nudge portfolio back
- Optimization loop ran several times per hour, weighing thousands of potential trades before issuing electronic instructions
- **Half million lines of code** vs. tens of thousands in Frey's old system
- This was the automated trading system Simons had dreamed of years earlier

### Core Strategy Preserved

- Retained Frey's **prediction model** from his Morgan Stanley experience
- Continued identifying winning trades by wagering on **reversions after stocks got out of whack**
- For over a decade, these would be **second order complements** to the firm's core reversion-to-the-mean predictive signals
- Employee: "We make money from the reactions people have to price moves"

### Implementation and Initial Disappointment (1995)

- Brown and Mercer made **partners** in Renaissance, elevated to managers, receiving **points** (percentage of firm's profits)
- **System couldn't handle much money**: Renaissance placed only $35 million in stocks—when more money traded, gains dissipated (like Frey's system earlier)
- Brown and Mercer couldn't figure out why their system was running into so many problems
- Recruited IBM team: **Della Pietra twins**, then **Magerman**

## Magerman's Debugging Heroics

### Magerman's Integration

- Convinced staff to adopt **C++** instead of C: "C is *so* 1980"
- True motive: wanted to become indispensable to his officemates
- Strategy worked—mathematicians and others begged Magerman for help day and night: "I became their pet"
- Spent free time learning firm's stock-trading tactics, devouring information
- Brown manipulated him with compliments: "I really thought it would take you more time" to develop such deep knowledge

### The Joshua Script Scandal

- At IBM, Magerman developed **script** to monitor memory/resources and commandeer underutilized machines for coding competitions
- Called it **Joshua** after the computer in 1983 hacker film *WarGames*
- Caught by furious IBM executive who threatened federal crime charges—machine purchased under top-secret government contract
- Magerman's defense: "How was I supposed to know?"
- Hacking continued; colleagues sidestepped angry executive's computer when needed

### The Computer Virus Incident

- At Renaissance, Magerman rewrote monitoring tool, tricked systems administrator, launched it as backdoor
- **Unleashed computer virus** infecting Renaissance's computers mid-trading day, jeopardizing research
- Staffers furious—equities team wasn't making money, now network crashed
- **Brown confrontation**: "This isn't *IBM*! We're trading real money here! If you get in the way with your stupid stunts, you're going to ruin things for us!"
- Magerman became sudden outcast, "huge blunder, socially speaking"

### The Breakthrough Discovery

- **Stock-trading system's inexplicable losing streak**—futures team whispered problems stemmed from "just computer guys"
- Simons publicly confident: "We have to keep trying" (summer 1995 meeting)
- Privately wondered if equities were a waste of time—Laufer, Patterson, and futures group already reached same conclusion
- Patterson: "We had given it years already. If I was calling the shots, I might very well have pulled the plug"
- **Simons's ultimatum**: Get your system to work in six months, or I'm pulling the plug
- Brown slept on Murphy bed in office; Mercer worked equally intense hours
- System scored gains with tiny amounts but profits evaporated when leverage increased
- Simulations said they should be making money with larger sums, but actual moves were losers

### The Static S&P 500 Bug

- Magerman lived in apartment with no working stove, nothing in refrigerator—"effectively lived in the office"
- Spotted odd line in simulation code: **Standard & Poor's 500 at unusually low level**
- Test code used figure from 1991 (roughly half current number)
- Mercer had written it as **static figure** rather than variable updating with market moves
- **Second bug**: algebraic error appeared after fixing the first
- Magerman solved both, spent most of night on them
- Now simulator's algorithms could recommend ideal portfolio for Nova system

### Mercer's Validation

- Magerman brought work to Mercer, who examined code line by line
- Mercer grabbed paper and pencil, worked on formula for ~15 minutes
- **"You're right,"** Mercer told Magerman
- Mercer convinced Brown; when they told other staffers, met with incredulity and laughter
- Junior programmer fixed the problem? Same guy who crashed system weeks after being hired?
- Brown and Mercer ignored doubts, restarted system with Simons's backing
- **Instant gains** resulted—long losing streak over
- Magerman received cherished pat on back from Brown
- Simons at weekly meeting: "This is great. Let's keep it going"

## Chapter 11: The Medallion Powerhouse

### Summer 1997 Success

- **Medallion fund**: $900+ million, mostly futures contracts (commodities, currencies, bonds, stock indexes)
- **Laufer's strategies** continued winning: buying on propitious days of week and ideal moments of day; mapping two-day trajectories
- Stock-trading profits tiny (few million dollars/month) but enough to merge Nova into Medallion—**single hedge fund trading almost every investment**

### Persistent Challenges

- **Haven't solved the market**: Medallion gained 21% (1997), down from 32% (1996), 38% (1995), 71% (1994)
- **Data-entry error**: Fund purchased 5× as many wheat-futures contracts as intended, pushing prices higher
- Next day's *Wall Street Journal*: analysts attributed price surge to poor wheat harvest fears (not Renaissance's mistake)
- **Patterson's options model**: generated only modest profits, frustrating Simons

### The Madoff Comparison

- Simons pointed to **Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities** making huge gains trading equity options
- Patterson's retort: "Maybe you should hire Bernie"
- Years later, Simons would become suspicious of Madoff's results and pull invested money
- 2008: Madoff acknowledged running **history's largest Ponzi scheme**

### The Academic Paper Initiative

- **Nervous about slipping returns**, Simons proposed new idea
- Tens of thousands of peer-reviewed research papers published annually in economics, finance, psychology
- Many demonstrate methods of scoring outsize returns but are "left in history's dustpan"
- **Book club for quants**: Each week, Simons, Brown, Mercer, and senior executives assigned three papers to read, digest, present
- **After several hundred papers**: gave up—tactics sounded tantalizing but trade recommendations failed when tested
- Reinforced cynicism about academics' ability to predict financial moves
- Brown: "Any time you hear financial experts talking about how the market went up because of such and such—remember it's all nonsense"

### Simons's Core Principles

- Emphasized principles from IDA code-breaking and Stony Brook years
- **Scientists and mathematicians need to interact, debate, share ideas**—radical approach
- Many of Renaissance's smartest staffers had enjoyed recognition earlier in careers toiling on individual research
- Talented quants often least comfortable working with others
- Industry joke: "Extroverted mathematicians are the ones who stare at *your* shoes during a conversation, not their own"

### The Single Monolithic System

- Rival firms allowed researchers to work in silos, sometimes competing
- **Simons insisted**: Medallion would have single, monolithic trading system
- **Full access**: All staffers enjoyed complete access to source code for money-making algorithms
- Readable in cleartext on firm's internal network
- No code corners accessible only to top executives
- Anyone could make experimental modifications to improve trading system
- Simons hoped researchers would swap ideas rather than embrace private projects
- Even secretaries had source code access (ultimately proved unwieldy)

### Culture of Openness

- Staffers wandered into colleagues' offices offering suggestions, initiating collaborations
- When frustrated, scientists shared work and asked for help rather than move to new projects
- Ensured promising ideas weren't "wasted"
- Groups met regularly, discussing intimate progress details, fielding probing questions from Simons
- Staff ate lunch together, ordered from local restaurants, squeezed into tiny lunchroom
- Annual exotic vacation for employees and spouses, strengthening camaraderie

### Peer Pressure as Motivation

- **Crucial motivational tool**: Researchers/programmers/others spent time working on presentations
- Burned to impress each other—or at least not embarrass themselves—spurring ingenious approaches
- Frey: "If you didn't make much progress, you'd feel pressure. That was how your self-worth was determined"

### Compensation Structure

- **Every six months**: employees received bonus, but only if Medallion surpassed certain profit level
- Firm paid money over several years, helping keep talent around
- Didn't matter if staffers uncovered new signals, cleaned data, or other lower-profile tasks
- If they distinguished themselves and Medallion thrived, rewarded with **bonus points** (percentage of Renaissance's profit pool)
- **Glen Whitney** (top infrastructure manager): "You know your formula from the beginning of the year. It's the same as everyone else's with just a couple of different coefficients, depending on your position. You want a bigger bonus? Help the fund get higher returns in whatever way you can: discover a predictive source, fix a bug, make the code run faster, get coffee for the woman down the hall with a great idea, whatever... bonuses depend on how well the fund performs, not if your boss liked your tie"

### Equity Distribution

- Simons shared equity, handing **10% stake to Laufer**
- Later gave sizable slices to Brown, Mercer, **Mark Silber** (CFO), and others
- Reduced Simons's ownership to just over 50%
- Top-performing employees could buy shares (equity in firm)
- Could invest in Medallion—**biggest perk of all**

### The Risk of Openness

- **Immense risk**: Hotshot researchers liable to become frustrated in flat organization
- Full source code access enabled staffers to walk out, join rival, tap Renaissance's secrets
- Most were PhDs from academia with limited Wall Street familiarity—Simons believed chance of defection relatively small
- **Lifetime nondisclosure agreements** and **noncompete contracts** reduced danger (later learned agreements couldn't eliminate risk of employees defecting with firm's intellectual property)

### Lack of Wealth Focus

- Beyond few old-school traders, many at Renaissance didn't prioritize wealth
- **Peter Weinberger** (celebrated computer scientist) interviewed 1996, stood in parking lot sizing up researchers
- "It was a lot of old, crappy cars. Saturns, Corollas, and Camrys"
- Some employees didn't know if fund was making/losing money daily
- Few had no idea how to locate monthly performance figures on Renaissance's web page
- During losing streaks, oblivious staffers walked around happy-go-lucky, annoying more conscious employees

### Wealth Embarrassment

- Some seemed embarrassed by swelling wealth
- 1997 lunchroom: researcher asked if colleagues flew first-class—table turned silent
- Finally, embarrassed mathematician spoke up: "I do. My wife insists on it"

### Recruiting Challenges

- Despite impressive gains, hiring presented challenge
- Few recruits heard of Renaissance
- Joining meant sacrificing individual recognition for projects that would never garner publicity/acclaim
- Foreign concept to most academics
- Simons, Patterson, others emphasized positive aspects: rewards of solving difficult trading problems, camaraderie, fast pace
- Academics could slog for years on papers; Simons pushed for results within weeks/days
- Atmosphere informal and academic, yet intense
- Visitor likened it to "perpetual exam week"

### Mercer's Perspective

- At IBM, frustrated with speech-recognition world where scientists could pretend to make progress with "parlor tricks"
- At Renaissance, couldn't fool anyone
- Told Sharon McGrayne: "You have money in the bank or not, at the end of the day. You don't have to wonder if you succeeded... it's just a very satisfying thing"

### Interview Process

- Ad hoc: discuss achievements, tackle challenging probability problems
- See if there might be fit at firm
- Candidates grilled by half dozen staffers for 45 minutes each
- Then asked to present lectures about scientific research to entire firm
- Simons and Patterson focused on hiring seasoned academics with series of accomplishments, or new PhDs with strong dissertations
- Even big-name recruits had to pass **coding test**—message that everyone expected to program computers and do menial tasks at other firms
- Had to get along with each other
- Current executive: "The chemistry is important. It's like joining a family"

## The Three-Step Trading Signal Discovery Process

### By 1997: Statistical Significance Framework

- **Trading signals**: identify anomalous patterns in historic pricing data
- Make sure anomalies were **statistically significant**, **consistent over time**, and **nonrandom**
- See if identified pricing behavior could be **explained in reasonable way**

### Understandable Patterns

- Most patterns wagered on were primarily those Renaissance researchers could understand
- Resulted from relationships between price, volume, other market data
- Based on historic behavior of investors or other factors
- **Enduring success**: betting on retracements—~60% of investments experiencing big, sudden price rises/drops would snap back (at least partially)
- Profits from retracements helped Medallion do well in volatile markets when prices lurched before retracing some ground

### Nonintuitive Signals (1997+)

- More than half of trading signals were **nonintuitive**—couldn't fully understand
- Most quant firms ignore signals without reasonable hypothesis
- Simons and colleagues never liked spending too much time searching for causes of market phenomena
- If signals met statistical strength measures, comfortable wagering on them
- Only steered clear of most preposterous ideas

### Statistical Validity Examples

- Renaissance executive: "Volume divided by price change three days earlier, yes, we'd include that"
- "But not something nonsensical, like the outperformance of stock tickers starting with the letter *A*"
- Not that they *wanted* trades that didn't make sense—these were statistically valid strategies they were finding

### Recurring Patterns and Competitive Advantage

- Patterns without apparent logic had added bonus: **less likely to be discovered and adopted by rivals**
- Most wouldn't touch these trades
- Brown: "If there were signals that made a lot of sense that were very strong, they would have long-ago been traded out. There are signals that you can't understand, but they're there, and they can be relatively strong"

### Data Overfitting Danger

- **Obvious danger**: embracing strategies that don't make sense
- Patterns could result from meaningless coincidences
- Spending enough time sorting data can identify trades that seem to generate stellar returns but are produced by happenstance
- Quants call this **data overfitting**

### David Leinweber's Absurd Example

- Quant investor determined US stock returns can be predicted with **99% accuracy** by combining:
  - Annual butter production in Bangladesh
  - US cheese production
  - Population of sheep in Bangladesh and US

### Renaissance's Solution

- Place head-scratching signals in trading system but **limit money allocated** (at least at first)
- Work to develop understanding of why anomalies appeared
- Over time, frequently discovered reasonable explanations
- Gave Medallion leg up on firms that had dismissed phenomena
- Settled on mix of: **sensible signals**, **surprising trades with strong statistical results**, and **a few bizarre signals so reliable they couldn't be ignored**
- Simons (few years later): "We ask, 'Does this correspond to some aspect of behavior that seems reasonable?'"

### Machine Learning Evolution

- Like astronomers scanning galaxy for unusual phenomena, Renaissance scientists programmed computers to monitor financial markets
- Ground away until discovered overlooked patterns and anomalies
- Once determined valid, firm determined how much money to place in trades
- Signals placed into system and left to do their thing without interference
- **Medallion increasingly relied on strategies system taught itself**—form of machine learning
- Computers fed enough data, trained to spit out own answers
- Consistent winner might automatically receive more cash without anyone approving shift or being aware

## Renaissance's New Headquarters (Late 1990s)

### The Wood-and-Glass Compound

- Simons moved firm into nearby one-story, wood-and-glass compound
- Each office enjoyed relaxing, bucolic view of nearby woods
- Headquarters featured: gym, lighted tennis courts, library with fireplace, large auditorium with exposed beams
- Simons hosted biweekly seminars from visiting scholars (usually little to do with finance)
- Trading room: 20 or so people, no bigger than conference room
- Cafeteria and common areas expansive—allowed staffers to meet, discuss, debate, filling whiteboards with formulas and diagrams

### IBM Reunion

- As stock-trading results improved, Brown and Mercer wooed former IBM colleagues
- Email to IBM staffer: "How would you like to sell out and join our technical trading firm?"
- **Half dozen IBM alumni** soon contributing, including Della Pietra twins
- Brothers known for massive nutcracker figurine collection and Stephen's insistence on name before brother's on group emails
- Managed to speed up parts of stock-trading system relying on multiple programs, network of computers, hundreds of thousands of lines of code

### Brown's Work Ethic

- Intense and energetic
- Hustled from meeting to meeting, rode unicycle through halls, almost ran over colleagues
- Worked much of night on computer near Murphy bed in office
- Grabbed nap when tired
- Once, late evening working on complicated project, picked up phone to call junior associate at home with pressing question
- Colleague stopped him: "Peter, you can't call him. It's *two a.m.*"
- Brown confused: "He doesn't get paid enough to answer questions at two a.m."
- "Fine, let's give him a raise, then. But we *have* to call him!"

### Margaret Hamburg's Career

- **Brown's wife**: spent six years as NYC health commissioner, instituting needle-exchange program to combat HIV transmission
- 1997: Hamburg and children moved to Washington, DC
- She took senior job at US Department of Health and Human Services
- Later became commissioner of US Food and Drug Administration
- Brown flew to Washington for weekends
- Seemed to spend even more time at work, creating pressure for other group members to match focus
- Brown to friend after dragging feet for weeks about meeting for dinner: "When I'm away from my family, I just like to work"

### Mercer's Balance

- Analytical and unemotional
- Natural sedative for jittery partner
- Worked hard but liked to go home around 6 p.m.
- Became involved with drama away from office
- Years earlier, **youngest daughter Heather Sue** persuaded father to accompany her to football field, hold toy football so she could practice placekicking
- "I thought she'd get this kicking out of her system"
- Heather Sue blasted ball through uprights, astonishing father
- Became high school's starting kicker, enrolled at **Duke University**
- Won spot on varsity football team—**first woman on Division I football roster**
- Following year, pushed off team by coach (later admitted feeling embarrassed that rival coaches mocked him for having female kicker)
- After graduating 1998, **Heather Sue sued Duke for discrimination**, winning **$2 million in punitive damages**

### Mercer's Controversial Views

- At office, began showing new side to personality
- At lunch, mostly steered clear of controversial topics
- Not Mercer—hardly spoke during work meetings but turned oddly loquacious over meals
- Support for **gold standard** and affection for *More Guns, Less Crime* (John R. Lott Jr. book arguing crime falls when gun ownership rises)—reflected conservative beliefs
- Others more iconoclastic
- "Gas prices are up... we really should fix that"—enjoyed goading colleagues (many liberal or libertarian) with increasingly radical views
- "Clinton should be in jail"—referring to President Bill Clinton (accused of perjury and obstruction of justice in 1998 related to Monica Lewinsky relationship)
- Called Clinton "rapist" and "murderer," repeating conspiracy theory about secret drug-running scheme with CIA
- Most colleagues inched away, unwilling to get into heated debate
- Patterson (fellow political junkie) remained at lunch table, debating Mercer
- Stunned smart scientist could hold opinions with such flimsy support
- Over time, colleagues would have more reason for surprise

## Wall Street's Quant Revolution (Mid-1990s)

### Industry Shift

- Internet era in full swing, activity heating up in Silicon Valley
- Investment banks and trading firms hiring own computer pros, high-IQ scientists, mathematics PhDs
- Finally convinced quantitative strategies could help score gains
- **Simons and team remained blips on industry's radar screen**—partly by design
- Simons instructed troops to keep tactics to themselves, fretting competitors might adopt most successful methods

### Secrecy Obsession

- "At the NCA, the penalty for leaking is twenty-five years in prison"
- Simons liked to tell employees, somewhat ominously: "Unfortunately, all we can do is fire you"
- **Brown borderline maniacal** about silencing staffers and investors
- Once, Japanese insurance company representative placed **tape recorder** on conference room table to play conversation back later (ensure nothing lost in translation)
- Walking into room, Brown saw machine and nearly had nervous breakdown
- "There's a recorder on the table!" (startling guest and Renaissance client representative)
- Almost convulsing, Brown pulled colleague out of room
- "I don't want anyone recording us!" (screamed, appearing frightened)
- Embarrassed representative had to ask visitor to kindly turn off machine

## The Competitive Landscape

### Long-Term Capital Management (LTCM)

- At that point, no one cared what Simons and team were up to
- Two largest rivals: **Long-Term Capital Management** and **D. E. Shaw** commanded full investor attention
- **Founded by John Meriwether** (former mathematics instructor)
- Filled ranks with professors: **Eric Rosenfeld** (MIT-trained finance PhD and computer devotee), Harvard's **Robert C. Merton** and **Myron Scholes** (would become Nobel laureates)
- Team (mostly introverts, all intellectuals) downloaded historic bond prices, distilled overlooked relationships, built computer models predicting future behavior

### LTCM's Strategy

- Like Renaissance, didn't care where overall market or individual investments headed
- Models identified pricing anomalies between similar investments
- Greenwich, Connecticut hedge fund wagered irregularities would converge and dissipate
- Favorite trades: buying bonds fallen below historic levels while selling short (betting against) similar bonds that seemed overpriced
- Waited for convergence of bond prices, profiting as it happened
- Grew positions with leverage to amplify gains
- Banks eager lenders—hedge fund eschewed big, risky trades, placing thousands on seemingly safe bets

### LTCM's Dominance

- Mesmerized by all-star team of brainiacs
- Investors poured money into fund
- After launching 1994, LTCM gained **average of nearly 50%** in first three years
- Managing close to **$7 billion** (summer 1997)
- Made Simons's Medallion fund look like pip-squeak
- After rivals expanded own arbitrage trades, Meriwether's team shifted to newer strategies (even those with little experience): merger-stock trading, Danish mortgages

### The 1997 Warning

- Annual golf outing (summer 1997): LTCM's partners announced investors would have to **withdraw about half their cash**
- Result of diminishing market opportunities
- Clients lost minds, pleading with Meriwether and colleagues: "please, keep our money!"

### The 1998 Collapse

- Models weren't prepared for several shocking events (summer 1998):
  - **Russia's effective default on debt**
  - Resulting **panic in global markets**
- As investors fled investments with risk attached, prices of all kinds of assets reacted in unexpected ways
- LTCM calculated unlikely to lose more than **$35 million in a day**
- Somehow dropped **$553 million on one Friday in August**
- Billions evaporated in matter of weeks

### Meriwether's Desperate Plea

- Dialed investors, trying to raise cash
- Confident prices would revert to historic norms (as models predicted)
- Reality sunk in when visited **Vinny Mattone** (veteran trader: black silk shirts, ~300 pounds, gold chain and pinkie ring)
- "Where are you?"
- "We're down by half"
- "You're finished" (shocking Meriwether)
- "When you're down by half, people figure you can go down all the way. They're going to push the market against you.... You're *finished*"
<!-- pp. 193-212 -->

## LTCM Collapse Aftermath

### Impact on Quant Investing

- **LTCM collapse** devastated confidence in quantitative investing
- As LTCM's equity fell below $1 billion with skyrocketing leverage, Federal Reserve intervened
- Consortium of banks took control, fearing systemic collapse
- **John Meriwether** and colleagues lost nearly $2 billion in personal wealth
- *BusinessWeek*: "The reputation of quantitative investing itself has been dealt long-term damage"

### D. E. Shaw's Response

- **D. E. Shaw** hedge fund largely unaffected by LTCM troubles
- By 1998: several hundred employees, claimed 18% annual returns since launch
- Accounted for ~5% of daily NYSE trading volume
- Portfolio was **market neutral** — immune to broad market movements
- Different hiring approach: **brainteasers** and probability puzzles
  - **Monty Hall problem** used in interviews (from *Let's Make a Deal*)
  - Employees were *Doctor Who* fans, dressed informally
- *Fortune* 1996: D. E. Shaw called "the most intriguing and mysterious force on Wall Street"

### D. E. Shaw's Expansion and Fall

- Shaw launched **Juno** (first free email service), joint venture with BankAmerica for $1.4 billion
- Leveraged bond portfolio to $20 billion, hired 600+ employees globally
- **Fall 1998 market turmoil**: D. E. Shaw lost $200 million in bond portfolio
- Fired 25% of employees, retrenched operations
- Would recover but never regain former dominance

## Renaissance's Lessons from LTCM

### Key Differences

- **Patterson** analyzed rivals' setbacks — Medallion gained 42% in 1998
- Renaissance didn't borrow as heavily as LTCM
- LTCM's trades needed specific time frames; Renaissance's were more flexible
- Renaissance hired **mathematicians and computer scientists, not economists**

### Reinforced Philosophy

- **Never place too much trust in trading models** — all formulas are fallible
- When strategies fail or volatility surges, system automatically reduces positions
- Example: Medallion cut futures trading 25% in fall 1998
- Contrast: LTCM *increased* positions when strategies floundered

> "LTCM's basic error was believing its models were truth. We never believed our models reflected reality—just some aspects of reality." — Patterson

- LTCM drifted into unfamiliar markets (Danish mortgages, online banking)
- Reminder for Renaissance: **hone approach, don't enter new businesses**

## Stock Trading Still Secondary (1998)

- Despite Brown/Mercer's efforts, stocks contributed only ~10% of profits in 1998
- **Henry Laufer's futures trades** powered Renaissance
- Simons pushed equities team to improve

### David Magerman's Rise

- **Magerman** had located and fixed the computer bug plaguing Brown/Mercer's stock system
- Given more responsibility as architect of Medallion's **production** software
- Became watchdog of system changes, boss of dozen PhDs
- Well paid, garnered praise from Brown, Mercer, and Simons
- Upgraded wardrobe, began wearing suspenders to emulate Mercer

### The Rift with Mercer

- Magerman sensed iciness from **Mercer's family**, especially daughter **Rebekah**
- No more restaurant outings or home invitations
- Magerman wrote five-page letter to renew friendship — no reply
- Possible cause: publicly berated Rebekah over her trading work
- Or: romantic canoe trip with **Heather Sue** left Bekah jealous

> "I was persona non grata in their house and at family-hosted events." — Magerman

## Magerman's 1999 Bug

### The Crisis

- 1999: Magerman tweaked stock-trading code for efficiency
- Medallion's futures immediately went from winners to losers
- Magerman had unleashed a **powerful bug** infecting the firm

> *I caused this!*

- Beat himself up for weeks over the "dumb error"
- Worked through nights but couldn't find the bug
- Quarter ended with Medallion's **first quarterly loss in a decade**
- Racked with worry, diagnosed with **generalized anxiety disorder**
- Started weekly therapy sessions

### Recovery

- Medallion's returns slowly rebounded, Magerman relaxed
- Concluded he probably hadn't been responsible after all
- **January 2000**: Medallion surged 10.5%, best one-month return in years
- By early March: sitting on $700 million profits as Nasdaq hit records

## The Dot-Com Crash (March 2000)

### The Meltdown

- **March 10**: tech bubble burst, shares plummeted
- Month later: Nasdaq down 25%, eventually 78% drop from peak
- Medallion faced inexplicable losses
- Lost **$90 million in a single day** in March (unprecedented)
- Next day: **$80 million more**
- Had never lost more than $5 million in a day before

### The Mystery

- Mounting losses weren't the only concern — it was *why* things were so bad
- Portfolio held commodities, currencies, bond futures; stock portfolio was largely **offsetting positions**
- Losses *shouldn't be happening*
- Trading signals developed through **machine learning** made it hard to pinpoint exact causes
- Machines seemed out of control

### Team Response

- Recruit visited Long Island office during sell-off
- Next morning: not a single person remembered meeting the recruit
- Losses left researchers in "utter daze"
- **Mercer** remained stoic, joking with colleagues as if nothing unusual happening
- **Brown**: never experienced deep sudden losses, showed strain
- High-strung, emotional, couldn't hide building fears
- Unable to sleep, spent night checking computer for updates
- Looked pale around office, shocking colleagues

### Magerman's Alert

- Third day of meltdown: Magerman checked futures, "received fresh jolt"
- Drove to work nauseous
- Brown and Mercer already in emergency meeting with Simons and executives
- Magerman slowly opened heavy door, whispered to Brown: "We're down another ninety million"
- Brown froze, Medallion losses approached **$300 million**
- Brown looked at Simons desperately: "Jim, what should we do?"

> "Trust the model. We have to let it ride; we can't panic." — Simons

## Finding the Problem

### The Momentum Strategy Bug

- After all-nighters, researchers identified the culprit
- **Once-trusted momentum strategy** was bleeding money
- Simple logic: if stocks rallied in previous weeks, system bought more assuming surge would continue
- For years, this trending signal worked as fund bought rising Nasdaq shares
- Now algorithms instructed Medallion to buy *more* shares even in vicious bear market

### Simons's Approach

- Simons emphasized importance of not overriding trading system
- But in crisis, he pulled back reliance on certain signals
- Chagrin of researchers who believed in never adjusting programs
- Even those staffers agreed to dump faulty momentum signal
- System better at predicting **short-term moves**, not longer-term ones the defective signal focused on
- Quickly ditched momentum strategy, stemmed losses
- Soon gains piling up again

### Brown's Resignation Offer

- Brown remained shaken, offered to resign
- Simons rejected offer, told Brown he was more valuable now

> "Never put your full faith in a model."

## Medallion's 2000 Success

### Performance

- Fall 2000: Medallion soared **99%** even after charging clients 20% of gains + 5% of money invested
- Managed nearly **$4 billion**
- Previous decade: outperformed Soros, Robertson, Tudor Jones
- **Sharpe ratio of 2.5** in recent five-year period (low volatility relative to returns)

### Media Attention

- **Hal Lux** (*Institutional Investor*) interviewed Simons over coffee and gin
- Simons expressed confidence:

> "The things we are doing will not go away. We may have bad years, we may have a terrible year sometimes, but the principles we've discovered are valid." — Simons

- Brown, Mercer, Laufer confident in rare opportunity
- Pushed to hire new employees

> "The markets are dripping with inefficiencies. We're leaving money on the table." — Senior staffer

- New hires would **transform the firm** in ways Simons couldn't anticipate

