## Internal Tensions at Renaissance (Late 2002-2003)

### Cultural Shifts and Old Guard vs. New Blood

- **Simons** employed old-school traders alongside computer advocates, creating friction
- **Magerman** couldn't understand Simons' distrust of automated systems in unstable markets
- Trivial disputes escalated: cottage demolition debate split staff along "caring vs. greedy" lines
- **Whitney** (math professor, joined 1997) created pro-demolition website; **Magerman** printed "Dump the Shacks!" bumper stickers
- Deeper issue: veterans sensed Renaissance shifting from collegial culture to mercenary atmosphere

### Fee Increases and Medallion Investor Ejections

- 2002: Simons raised Medallion fees to **36% of profits**
- Early 2003: boosted to **44%**, then ejected all outside investors
- Simons worried growth would hurt performance; preferred employees keep all gains
- Some loyal outside investors "crushed" by the move—saw it as betrayal

### Alexey Kononenko's Rise and Division

- **Alexey Kononenko**: Ukrainian mathematician, fled USSR in 1991 amid anti-Semitism
- PhD from Penn State (1996), studied with geometer **Anatole Katok**
- Postdoc work at U. Penn; influential research on billiard ball trajectories
- Disappointed by Berkeley postdoc offer (wanted Princeton/Harvard/Chicago tenure track)
- Left academia for Renaissance (shocking peers); motivated by financial security after Soviet hardship
- By 2002: earning **$40M+/year** (half salary, half Medallion investing)

### "Deadwood" Complaints and Resentment

- Kononenko and newer hires complained about overpaid "deadwood" employees
- Growing sentiment: **Brown** and **Mercer** were expendable
- Brown suffered carpal tunnel; Mercer had joint pain—both working less
- Kononenko bad-mouthed executives, questioned stock portfolio construction errors
- Complaints even targeted **Simons**, who spent less time at office but took half the profits

> "He doesn't do anything anymore. He's *screwing* us." — staffer to Magerman

### Departures and "Lord of the Flies" Culture

- **Nick Patterson** quit after decade analyzing markets—joined Cambridge institute to study human genome
- Veterans worried newcomers targeted high-equity employees to free up money for themselves
- Eastern Europeans stayed late, charged company for dinner, mocked others' work next day
- Sense of entitlement and "Lord of the Flies" atmosphere

### Belopolsky and Volfbeyn Defection (July 2003)

- Two senior scientists on Brown/Mercer's stock team began quit discussions
- HR had mistakenly given them **nondisclosure agreements** but not **noncompete agreements**
- July 2003: **Belopolsky** and **Volfbeyn** joined **Millennium Management** (billionaire **Israel Englander's** hedge fund)
- Simons feared they had "millions of lines of Medallion source code"

> "They stole from us!" — Simons

### Nicholas Simons' Death (2003)

- **Nicholas Simons** (Jim's third-eldest son) worked in Kathmandu on hydroelectric project
- Planned medical clinic in Nepal, around-world adventure, then organic chemistry and med school
- Week before returning home, stopped in Amed (Bali) for freediving
- Diving 100 feet down, partner's mask fogged; partner went ashore to adjust
- Gone five minutes—**Nick found drowned on sea floor**
- Jim and Marilyn inconsolable at funeral; "apocalyptic" rainstorm

### Simons' Response to Tragedy

- Simons had "unswerving belief in logic, rationality, and science"
- Fought daily odds in trading, usually victorious—now suffered two tragic, unpredictable accidents

> "Robert, my life is either aces or deuces. I don't understand." — Simons to Robert Frey

- **Paul's** death had been crushing; **Nick's** was equally painful but mixed with **anger**
- Turned "crusty, even ornery" with colleagues

> "He saw the death as a betrayal." — friend

- September 2003: Jim, Marilyn, family traveled to Nepal to continue Nick's legacy
- Funded maternity ward at Kathmandu hospital; later founded **Nick Simons Institute** (health care for rural Nepal)
- Simons contemplated retirement, worked on math with **Dennis Sullivan** as "refuge"

## The Kononenko Crisis (Spring 2004)

### Dinner Meeting at Simons' Home

- Spring 2004: **13 top Renaissance executives** met at Simons' East Setauket estate
- None wanted to be there—had to decide what to do about **Kononenko**
- Kononenko regularly ignored assignments, didn't show up to meetings about his behavior
- Dilemma: firing him risked mass exodus (like Belopolsky/Volfbeyn)
- Nondisclosure agreements hard to enforce; noncompete only prevented US trading
- Kononenko could return to Eastern Europe beyond US law reach

### The Dinner Confrontation

- Brown energized, argued to **retain Kononenko's group**—they were 1/3 of stock researchers
- Training investment would be wasted if they left
- Mercer quiet but seemed to agree
- Simons also favored keeping the team

> "We can fire these guys. But if they leave, they'll compete with us and make our lives harder." — Simons

- Simons thought Kononenko could be groomed into team player, effective manager
- Magerman tensed—Kononenko's team had forced Simons to take pay cut, challenged collaborative culture

> "This is disgusting! If we don't shut them down or fire them, I'm quitting." — Magerman

- Whitney also threatened to quit if Alexey wasn't fired
- Simons and others knew Magerman/Whitney were bluffing (wouldn't leave)
- **Consensus: Kononenko and gang would stay, get promotion**

> "Give us time, David, we'll manage it." — Brown
> "We have a plan." — Simons

### Aftermath and Rebellion Plans

- Magerman and Whitney left "solemn and distressed"
- Would soon form their own plans

