## Life at Renaissance (2007)

### Medallion and RIEF Performance

- **Peter Brown** so confident: bet colleague if Medallion scored **100% return in 2007**, he'd get colleague's new **Mercedes E-Class**
- Brown's competitive streak extended beyond work (squash matches, gym strength tests)
- Bermuda vacation: Brown at pool in knee-high black socks/sandals watching water volleyball
- Commotion: someone lunging for ball, elbows near child's face

> "Who's the maniac?" — alarmed mother
> "Oh, that's just Peter." — staffer

### The Quant Personality

- Brown and Mercer logic-focused, not feelings
- Many hired scientists "brilliant, driven, seemingly detached from human emotion"
- Bermuda trip return: suggestion to clear way for pregnant woman boarding
- Some Renaissance scientists refused—if she wanted to board early, she logically would have arrived early

> "It was like being with a bunch of Sheldons." — outsider (referring to *The Big Bang Theory*)

### Brown's Intensity

- Assumed more responsibility, dealt with marketing execs unfamiliar with his brusque style
- Irreverent, mischievous when fund doing well
- Unhinged about small things
- Example: meeting where underling's phone vibrated (not turned off)
- Phone shook, toppled book stack
- Brown's eyes widened, stared at phone, then employee

> "Get that fucking thing out of here!" — Brown screaming

> "Take it easy, Peter. Everything will be all right." — Mark Silber (CFO)

### The Brown-Mercer Dynamic

- Mercer calmed Brown—just being around Mercer improved Brown's spirits
- Mercer didn't interact much with colleagues, whistled during day
- Huddled with Brown to improve trading models
- One emotional/outgoing, other taciturn/circumspect
- "A bit like Penn & Teller (but much less funny)"

---

## The Quant Quake (August 2007)

### Early Warning Signs

- July 2007: RIEF minor loss; Medallion **up 50%** for year (Brown positioned to win Mercedes)
- Subprime mortgage troubles brewing (aggressive lenders, scuffed/limited credit borrowers)
- Worrywarts predicted spread, few thought it could cripple broader markets
- Brown/Mercer's statistical-arbitrage trades market-neutral (jitters unlikely to affect returns)

### The Dominant Quant Funds

- By summer 2007: group of quant hedge funds emerged dominant
- Inspired by Simons' success, market-neutral strategies, computer models, automated trades
- **Peter Muller** (blue-eyed quant, piano player): led **$6B PDT** at Morgan Stanley
- **Clifford Asness** (U. Chicago PhD): led **$39B AQR Capital Management**
- **Ken Griffin**: **$13B Citadel** using statistical-arbitrage trades

### Friday, August 3, 2007

- Dow Jones Industrial Average plummeted **281 points** (Bear Stearns investment bank health concerns)
- Drop didn't seem major; most senior investors on vacation

### Monday, August 6, 2007

- All quant traders hit with sudden, serious losses
- **AQR**: Asness closed office blinds, called contacts to understand
- Smaller quant fund **Tykhe Capital** in trouble
- Goldman Sachs division suffering
- Unclear who was selling or why it impacted so many "unique" firms
- Later theory: fire sale by at least one quant fund + borrowing slashes sparked brutal downturn (**"quant quake"**)

### Previous Quant Crises

- 1987 stock crash: investors failed by sophisticated models
- 1998: Long-Term Capital historic losses
- Algorithmic traders braced for latest fiasco

> "It's bad, Cliff. This has the feel of a liquidation." — Michael Mendelson (AQR global trading head) to Asness

### Simons' Initial Response

- Most of Monday: Simons not focused on stocks (in Boston for mother **Marcia's** death/funeral)
- Afternoon: Simons and cousin **Robert Lourie** (ran Renaissance futures business) flew back on Simons' **Gulfstream G450**
- Learned Medallion and RIEF getting crushed

> "We always have very good days after difficult ones." — Simons

- Tuesday worse: computer screens flashed red, no apparent reason, Brown's mood grim

> "I don't know what the hell is going on, but it's not good." — Brown

### Wednesday Crisis Meeting (August 8, 2007)

- Simons, Brown, Mercer, ~6 others in central conference room around table
- Focused on charts showing losses magnitude, when banks would demand more collateral
- One stock basket already plunged so far Renaissance had to provide additional collateral to forestall sale
- Deeper losses → more collateral needed → massive forced stock sales

### The Great Debate: Sell or Hold?

- Conference room bordered by open atrium where researchers worked
- Staffers studied faces entering/leaving, gauging desperation levels
- 2000 tech meltdown: Brown didn't know what to do
- 2007: Brown was sure—**sell-off wouldn't last long**
- Renaissance should stick with system, maybe even **add positions**
- System programmed to buy/sell on its own, already expanding positions

> "This is an opportunity!" — Brown

> "Trust the models—let them run." — Henry Laufer

- **Simons shook his head**—didn't know if firm could survive more pain
- Scared: if losses grew and couldn't provide collateral, banks would sell Medallion positions → huge losses
- Even if Renaissance suffered smaller losses than banks, no one would deal with them again (likely death blow)

### Simons Overrules the Scientists

- Medallion needed to **sell, not buy**

> "Our job is to survive. If we're wrong, we can always add [positions] later." — Simons

- Brown shocked—Simons overruling him publicly, taking issue with trading system
- Thursday: Medallion began reducing equity positions to build cash
- Simons, Brown, Mercer stared at computer updating profits/losses
- First share batch sold → market dropped further, affirming Simons' fears


<!-- pp. 233-252 -->

## August 2007 Crisis: Medallion's Near-Death Experience

### The Quant Meltdown

- **PDT's losses spread to entire market**: Lost $600 million of Morgan Stanley's money over two days
- Thursday crash: S&P 500 down 3%, Dow fell 387 points
- **Medallion devastated**: Lost more than $1 billion that week (20% down)
- **RIEF plunged**: Down nearly $3 billion (~10%)
- Eerie silence at Renaissance lunchroom — researchers stayed past midnight trying to understand

> "Are our models broken?" — Researchers' fear

### Internal Tensions

- Renaissance shared ~25% of positions with rivals — plagued by same contagion
- **Senior scientists upset at Simons**: Not over losses, but interference with trading system
- Some saw position reduction as "personal affront" and "ideological weakness"
- One researcher emailed: "You're dead wrong"
- Another: "You believe in the system, or you don't"

### Simons' Defense

- Simons believed in the system but acknowledged unprecedented losses
- **Twenty standard deviations from average** — "most had never come close to experiencing"

> "How far can it go?" — Simons wondered

### Lenders' Panic

- **Deutsche Bank and Barclays** faced potential billions in losses if Medallion kept losing
- Few at banks aware of basket-option arrangements
- **Martin Malloy** (Barclays executive) called Brown for reassurance — "sounded harried but in control"
- **Mark Dwyer** (RIEF salesman) left to pitch reinsurance company
- RIEF down 10% for year while overall stock market up
- Dwyer had sold home, invested in Medallion, borrowed from Deutsche Bank — now down nearly $1 million
- **Crohn's disease flared** from stress — "sharp aches, fever, terrible abdominal cramping"

> "Just let the brakes fail." — Dwyer's thought boarding ferry to Massachusetts

### Recovery

- Friday morning: Medallion stabilizing when fund sold positions
- Market handled trades without weakening
- Some attributed turnaround to **Asness of AQR** buy order that day
- Monday: Both Medallion and RIEF making money again "as if a fever had broken"
- Later complaints: gains would have been larger without Simons' interference

> "We gave up a lot of extra profit," a staffer told him.
> "I'd make the same decision again," Simons responded.

### 2007-2008: Triumph and Struggle

- Renaissance regained footing by late 2007
- **Growing market turbulence aided Medallion's signals**
- **2007 gains: 86%** — nearly enough for Brown to win the Mercedes
- RIEF lost money but "didn't seem a huge deal"
- Early 2008: subprime crisis infected global markets, **Medallion thrived** (rose over 20% in first few months)
- Simons revived idea of selling up to 20% of Renaissance

### May 2008: Qatar Trip

- Simons, Brown, executives flew to Qatar to meet sovereign-wealth fund
- Arrived Friday (Muslim prayer day) — meetings delayed
- Hotel concierge recommended **dune bashing** (off-roading in sand)
- **Stephen Robert** (Oppenheimer exec hired for marketing) joined Simons in desert

### Simons' Physics Epiphany in the Dunes

- Vehicle almost tipped over on steep dunes at breakneck speeds
- Simons turned pale, terrified

> "Jim, are you okay?" Robert shouted.
> "We could get killed!" Simons yelled back, fear in voice.
> "Relax, they do this all the time," Robert told him.
> "What if this tips over?" Simons responded. "People think I'm pretty smart—I'm going to die in the dumbest way possible!"

- Five minutes later, Simons relaxed and smiled

> "I got it!" Simons yelled. "There's a principle in physics: We can't tip over unless the tires have traction! We're in sand, so the tires have nothing to grab on to!"

## Chapter Fourteen: Spending the Fortune

### Jim Simons' Lifestyle

- Worth ~$11 billion by time of stepping down
- **220-foot yacht _Archimedes_**: $100 million vessel
  - Named for Greek mathematician/inventor
  - Formal dining room for twenty, wood-burning fireplace, Jacuzzi, grand piano
  - Sometimes flew friends on Gulfstream G450 to join yacht abroad
- **Taxi driver Kenny Macrae** in Scotland: "He gave me a reasonable tip, too"
- BBC speculated Simons might buy British soccer team when _Archimedes_ visited Bristol
- **$50 million NYC apartment**: limestone Fifth Avenue building with Central Park views
- Neighbor: **George Soros**

### Philanthropy: Autism Research

- **2003**: Convened roundtable of top scientists (family member diagnosed with autism)
- **$100 million commitment** — largest private donor in field
- Three years later: tapped **Columbia neurobiologist Gerald Fischbach** to expand efforts
- **Simons Simplex Collection**: Repository of genetic samples from thousands with autism + family members
- Helped identify over 100 genes related to autism
- Research discovered mutations playing role in disorder

### Philanthropy: Mathematics Education

- Disturbed by limited math education in US schools
- Earlier pitched **Chuck Schumer** (Democratic senator) on stipends for best math teachers
- Schumer's repeated promise: "That's a great idea! We'll get right on it"
- Realized couldn't count on politicians
- **2004**: Launched **Math for America**
  - Eventually spent millions annually
  - **$15,000 annual stipends** to 1,000 top math/science teachers in NYC (10% of city's teachers)
  - Hosted seminars and workshops

> "Instead of beating up the bad teachers, we focus on celebrating the good ones. We give them status and money, and they stay in the field." — Simons

### Simons' Post-Renaissance Life

- Remained chairman and main shareholder
- Regular contact with Brown, Mercer, others
- Sometimes acknowledged difficulty transitioning

> "I feel irrelevant," he told Marilyn one day.

- Found philanthropy ventures as challenging as mathematics and finance
- Gave over $300 million to **Stony Brook University** among other institutions

## 2008 Financial Crisis: Who Predicted It?

### Congressional Testimony

- Simons called to testify before House committee on financial collapse causes
- Prepped with PR advisor **Jonathan Gasthalter**
- With **George Soros** and **John Paulson** present, Simons supported:
  - Push to force hedge funds to share info with regulators
  - Higher taxes for hedge-fund managers
- Simons "something of an afterthought" — all eyes on Paulson, Soros, and others who anticipated meltdown

### John Paulson's Prescient Bet

- **2005**: Colleague **Paolo Pellegrini** developed price chart showing housing market **40% overpriced**

> "This is our bubble! This is proof." — Paulson to Pellegrini

- Purchased protection via **credit default swaps** on riskiest mortgages
- **$20 billion windfall** over 2007-2008
- **George Soros**: CDS bets scoring over $1 billion in profits

### David Einhorn's Vindication

- **Thirty-nine-year-old** at May 2008 conference accused **Lehman Brothers** of accounting tricks
- Attributed success to "critical thinking skill"
- Vindicated when Lehman declared bankruptcy later that year

### Lesson: Old-Fashioned Research Won

> The lesson was obvious: One _could_ outsmart the market. It just took diligence, intelligence, and a whole lot of gumption.

- Simons' quantitative models, mathematicians, scientists "too hard to understand, their methods too difficult to pull off"

### Renaissance's 2008 Performance

- **RIEF dropped ~17%** after losses
- Researchers waved off losses — within simulations, seemed puny vs. S&P 500's **37% drubbing** (including dividends)
- 2009 concerns grew: **RIEF lost over 6%**, S&P 500 soared **26.5%**
- Investors who convinced themselves RIEF would generate Medallion-like returns realized "serious" difference
- Some grumbled Medallion still killing it while RIEF struggling — "something unfair was going on"

### May 2009: Investor Revolt

- RIEF investors "no longer in awe of Simons"
- Peppered seventy-one-year-old with tough questions in conference call
- Simons wrote about fund suffering "performance onslaught" during "extreme market rally"

> "We certainly understand our clients' discomfort," he said.

- Investors began fleeing RIEF — **soon down to less than $5 billion**
- Second stock futures fund also took on water, lost investors

> "No client on earth would touch it," says Dwyer, senior salesman

### 2010: Passing the Torch

- Year later, underwhelming RIEF performance continued
- **Simons turned seventy-two** — decided time to pass torch to Brown and Mercer
- **Medallion performance**: Managing $10 billion, posted **~45% average annual returns after fees since 1988**
- Outpaced Warren Buffett and every other investing star
- (Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway: 20% annually since 1965)
- Brown told reporter: unsure if would keep RIEF/RIFF going — "latest sign investors had soured on quantitative approach"

> "If we assess that it's not something that's going to sell, then we'll decide it's not good to be in that business," Brown said.

- Simons devoted two decades to building wealth — "Now he was going to spend it"

## Renaissance's Continued Dominance (2010)

### Medallion's Unmatched Record

- Managing ~$10 billion
- **~65% annual gains before investor fees** — near-record profits
- "Medallion's long-term record was arguably the greatest in the history of the financial markets"
- Investors and others becoming fascinated with secretive firm

> "There's Renaissance Technologies, and then there's everyone else," _The Economist_ said in 2010.

### Trading Characteristics

- Held thousands of long and short positions simultaneously
- Holding period: **one or two days to one or two weeks**
- Some trades described as **high-frequency**
- Many for hedging purposes or to gradually build positions
- Refined risk management and trading techniques

> "I'm not sure we're the best at all aspects of trading, but we're the best at estimating the cost of a trade," Simons told colleague years earlier.

### Staff Expansion

- **~250 staffers, over 60 PhDs**
- Experts in: AI, quantum physics, computational linguists, statisticians, number theorists, scientists, mathematicians

### Astronomers as Traders

- **Astronomers** especially capable — accustomed to scrutinizing large, confusing data sets
- **Elizabeth Barton**: PhD from Harvard, studied galaxy evolution with telescopes in Hawaii
- As firm diversified: hired **Julia Kempe** (former Elwyn Berlekamp student, quantum computing expert)

### Trading Strategies

- Bond, commodity, currency trades
- Money from trending and reversion-predicting signals
- Particularly effective signal: **Déjà Vu**
- Powered by **complex equity trades** with mixture of complex signals (not simple _pairs_ trades like Coke/Pepsi)

### Modest Edge, Massive Scale

- Gains on each trade never huge
- Only got it right **slightly more than half the time**

> "We're right 50.75 percent of the time . . . but we're 100 percent right 50.75 percent of the time. You can make billions that way." — Mercer to friend

### The Real Advantage

- Mercer's point: **slight advantage in collection of thousands of simultaneous trades**
- Large and consistent enough to make enormous fortune

### Beyond Traditional Factors

- Stocks influenced by more factors than sophisticated investors appreciated
- Example (predicting Alphabet/Google): Investors forecast earnings, interest rates, US economy, etc.
- Also anticipate: search/advertising future, broader tech industry, global companies trajectory, metrics/ratios

### Renaissance's Insight: Hidden Inefficiencies

- Deduced **even more influences** — forces not readily apparent or logical
- Analyzed hundreds of financial metrics, social media feeds, barometers of online traffic, "pretty much _anything_ that can be quantified and tested"
- Uncovered new factors "some borderline impossible for most to appreciate"

> "The inefficiencies are so complex they are, in a sense, hidden in the markets in code. RenTec decrypts them. We find them across time, across risk factors, across sectors and industries." — Staffer

### Mathematical Relationships Between Stocks

- Concluded **reliable mathematical relationships _between_ forces**
- Better sense of when factors relevant, how they interrelated, frequency of influence
- Tested subtle, nuanced mathematical relationships between shares
- **Multidimensional anomalies** — other investors oblivious or didn't fully understand

> "These relationships have to exist, since companies are interconnected in complex ways. This interconnectedness is hard to model and predict with accuracy, and it changes over time. RenTec has built a machine to model this interconnectedness, track its behavior over time, and bet on when prices seem out of whack according to these models." — Former Renaissance executive

### The Engineering Advantage

- Outsiders didn't quite get it
- Real key: **firm's engineering** — how it put factors/forces together in automated trading system
- Bought stocks with positive signals (combination of granular signals)
- Shorted stocks with negative signals
- Moves determined by **thousands of lines of source code**

> "There is no individual bet we make that we can explain by saying we think one stock is going to go up or another down. Every bet is a function of all the other bets, our risk profile, and what we expect to do in the near and distant future. It's a big, complex optimization based on the premise that we predict the future well enough to make money from our predictions, and that we understand risk, cost, impact, and market structure well enough to leverage the hell out of it." — Senior staffer

### Execution Matters as Much as Prediction

- **_How_ firm wagered at least as important as _what_ it wagered on**
- Example: If Medallion discovered dollar rose 0.1% between 9-10 a.m., wouldn't buy at 9 a.m.
- Instead: spread buying throughout hour in unpredictable ways to **preserve trading signal**
- Developed methods trading strongest signals **"to capacity"** — moving prices so competitors couldn't find them
- Like hearing huge markdown at Target, buying all discounted merchandise when store opens

> "Once we've been trading a signal for a year, it looks like something different to people who don't know our trades," an insider says.

### Simons' 2014 Summary

> "It's a very big exercise in machine learning, if you want to look at it that way. Studying the past, understanding what happens and how it might impinge, nonrandomly, on the future." — Simons, South Korea speech

## Bob Mercer: The Enigma

### Personal Style

- Silver-haired, dark eyebrows, wire-rimmed glasses, high-end shoes
- Whistled a lot, teased liberal colleagues
- Mostly just spoke with **Peter Brown**

### Self-Contained Lifestyle

> "He comes up with all the ideas. I express them." — Brown (likely with excess modesty)

- Truly self-contained
- Once told colleague: preferred company of cats to humans
- At night retreated to **Owl's Nest** (Long Island estate)
- **$2.7 million model train** — ran on track half size of basketball court
- 2009: sued manufacturer claiming $700,000 overcharge (costs ballooned finishing rush before daughter's wedding)

> "I'm happy going through my life without saying anything to anybody," Mercer told _Wall Street Journal_ in 2010.

### Political Views

- **Political conservative**
- **NRA member** with machine gun collection
- Gas-operated **AR-18 assault rifle** used by Schwarzenegger in _The Terminator_
- Few at Renaissance focused on these views

> "Bob talked about the need to protect oneself from the government, and the need to have guns and gold. I didn't think he was for real." — Early Medallion investor

### Annual Ohio State Trips

- Every year or two: flew to Ohio State for computer projects with grad school colleagues
- Treated group to lunch at local steakhouse
- Hummed to himself, often with serene smile
- When speaking to academics about unrelated project: shared disdain for taxes, skepticism of climate change
- **Tim Cooper** (physics professor) recalls: Mercer demonstrated nature emits more carbon dioxide than humans
- Later Cooper checked: data accurate, but **Mercer overlooked nature absorbs as much CO2 as it emits** (mankind does not)

> "It sounded like someone had got to him. Even a smart guy can get the details right but the big picture wrong." — Cooper

### Philanthropy: Fringe Causes (Until 2008)

- Family foundation mostly gave to fringe causes
- Helped fund **Arthur Robinson** (biochemist in southern Oregon)
  - Collecting thousands of vials of human urine
  - Believed key to extending human longevity
  - Newsletter argued low nuclear radiation "not very harmful, could even be beneficial"
  - Climate science is hoax
- Mercer gave Robinson **$1.4 million** to buy freezers for urine stockpile

### Political Donations (Post-2008)

- After Obama elected 2008: began **sizable political donations**
- Two years later: when **Robinson ran for Congress**, Mercer paid **$300,000 for attack ads** vs. **Peter DeFazio**
  - DeFazio wanted to close tax loopholes, enact new taxes on financial trades
  - Mercer never told Robinson he was sponsoring ads
  - Robinson lost in surprisingly close race

### Political Philosophy

- Emergence as high-profile right-wing donor caused head-scratching in Republican circles
- Serious contributors usually want something from politicians
- **Mercer never asked for much**
- Political operatives concluded: **rare breed, ideologue driven by long-held principles**
- Intense suspicion of government and resentment of establishment
- At least partly from frustrating summer writing code at air force base in New Mexico
- Also equally intense loathing of **Bill and Hillary Clinton**

### Libertarian Views (2010)

- By age sixty-four (2010): convinced **government should play minimal role**
- Partly because governments empower incompetence
- Worked in private industry most of life, hadn't demonstrated much public service interest
- Policy errors gnawed at him
- Alleged hypocrisy of elected officials in conversations
- Emphasized importance of personal freedoms
- Some considered him **"extreme libertarian"**
- **Ayn Rand** might have imagined hero like Mercer — tall, ruggedly handsome individualist, huge capitalism fan, _always_ rational and in control

### Desire to Alter Nation's Direction

- Now with enormous wealth, wanted to do something
- His timing was perfect
- **2010**: Supreme Court handed down landmark **_Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission_**
  - Election spending by wealthy donors = free speech (First Amendment protected)
  - Paved way for **super PACs**
  - Could accept unlimited money to support candidate (as long as no official coordination)

### Political Shift

- After decision: **Simons began donating heavily to Democratic causes**
- **Mercer stepped up Republican support**
- Mercer's penchant for privacy limited activity
- Focus remained on Renaissance
- **Second-oldest daughter Rebekah** started showing up at conservative fund-raisers, became family's public face, drove political strategy

### Rebekah Mercer

- **"Bekah"** to friends/family
- Tall, auburn-haired
- Favored glittery, 1950s-style cat's-eye glasses
- Resembled actor **Joan Cusack**
- **Stanford biology and mathematics graduate**
- Worked for Magerman at Renaissance before leaving
- Homeschooled four children, ran gourmet cookie store with sisters

### Spring 2010: Trump Place Purchase

- Made headlines: with then-husband **Sylvain Mirochnikoff** spent **$28 million** for six adjoining units
- **Heritage at Trump Place** (forty-one-story, Manhattan Upper West Side)
- Created **triplex with seventeen bedrooms** — twice size of Gracie Mansion

### Early Political Activity

- Backed traditional right-wing groups: **Freedom Partners Action Fund** (conservative PAC by Koch brothers and Heritage Foundation)
- Sometimes Rebekah and Bob walked through Republican fund-raisers arm-in-arm
- Rebekah (more sociable) did most talking, father stood silently beside

### Controversial Causes (Post-2010)

- Lost patience with established organizations
- Drifted to more controversial causes
- **$1 million** to group running attack ads vs. proposed mosque near World Trade Center's Ground Zero (lower Manhattan)
- **2011**: Met conservative firebrand **Andrew Breitbart** at conference
- Intrigued with **Breitbart News Network**
- Breitbart introduced Mercers to **Steve Bannon** (former Goldman Sachs banker)
- Bannon drew up term sheet: **Mercer family purchased nearly 50% of Breitbart News for $10 million**

### March 2012: Bannon's Death and Succession

- Breitbart collapsed on LA sidewalk, died of heart failure at forty-three
- Mercers convened emergency meeting in NYC to determine network's future
- Decided **Bannon would become site's executive chairman**
- Over time: site popular with **"alt-right"** (loose conglomeration including white supremacy groups viewing immigration/multiculturalism as threats)
- Bannon preferred calling himself **"economic nationalist"**
- Argued racist elements would get "washed out" of populist movement

### After Romney's 2012 Loss

- Mercers became even more disenchanted with establishment
- That year: **Rebekah stood before Romney supporters at University Club of New York**
- Delivered scathing critique of Republican Party
- Argued poor data and canvassing operations held candidates back
- Time to **"save America from becoming like socialist Europe"**

### Cambridge Analytica Investment

- Bannon brokered deal for Mercer to invest in **Cambridge Analytica** (US arm of British behavioral research company **SCL Group**)
- Specialized in advanced data Mercer accustomed to parsing at Renaissance
- Type of info **Rebekah said GOP lacked**
- Urged organizations benefiting from family funds to tap Cambridge's sophisticated technological capabilities

### Patrick Caddell's Data (2013)

- **Patrick Caddell** (former Democratic pollster turned party critic) shared data with Bob Mercer
- Suggested voters becoming alienated from both parties and most mainstream candidates
- Mercer asked Caddell to do another polling round as he collected own data
- Concluded **major shift was under way**

> "My God, this is a whole new world," he told Caddell.

### February 2014: Pierre Hotel Strategy Meeting

- Mercer and conservative donors gathered at Pierre hotel (NYC) to strategize 2016 election
- Told attendees: saw data indicating mainstream Republicans (Jeb Bush, Marco Rubio) would have difficulty winning
- Only **true outsider** sensing voters' frustrations could emerge victorious
- Others didn't seem convinced by his data
- He and Rebekah began searching for outsider to shake up Washington

> "It's a philosophical thing. They think the establishment has failed and is deserving." — Caddell

### Turning to Bannon for Guidance

- For guidance: Mercers turned to Bannon
- At time: Breitbart's online traffic soaring, validating faith in political provocateur
- Mercer hosted Bannon on **203-foot yacht _Sea Owl_**
- Bannon wore shorts, cursed freely, belched, held forth like close relation
- Advised Mercers on political/media ventures to invest in
- Escorted potential beneficiaries to Rebekah's triplex at Trump Place

### Mercer's Impact Across Atlantic

- Impact extended across Atlantic
- After Breitbart started London office (2012): began supporting **Nigel Farage** (UK politician, former commodity trader)
- Fledgling efforts to catapult **UK leaving European Union** from fringe to mainstream
- At some point: Mercer and Farage became friendly

### 2015: Cambridge Analytica and Leave.EU

- Cambridge Analytica discussed ways to help **Leave.EU** leaders (political group supporting UK withdrawal from EU)
- Bannon included in email traffic between groups (unclear if he read/responded)
- Following month: **Leave.EU publicly launched campaign** to persuade British voters to support referendum for EU exit
- Cambridge Analytica officials would deny charging for work for Leave.EU

> "Even if the firm was not paid for its services, it laid some of the early groundwork for the Leave.EU campaign," argues journalist **Jane Mayer**.

### June 2016: Brexit

- UK voted to exit European Union
- **Farage was one of leaders** (though Leave.EU wasn't selected as official organization)

> "Brexit could not have happened without Breitbart," Farage says.

### 2016 Presidential Campaign: Initial Support for Cruz

- Mercers initially backed **Texas Senator Ted Cruz**
- Impressed by willingness to shut government down over debt concerns (2013)
- Gave pro-Cruz super PAC **more than $13 million**
- When Cruz dropped out (May): **Rebekah accepted invitation to meet Donald Trump's daughter Ivanka and husband Jared Kushner** for lunch at Trump Tower
- Over sandwiches and salads: bonded over parenting young children

### Shift to Trump

- Soon Mercers shifted support to Trump (by then party's effective nominee)
- Launched super PAC to oppose **Hillary Clinton**
- Charged **Kellyanne Conway** (veteran Republican pollster) with running organization
- Eventually became **Trump's largest financial backers**

### August 13, 2016: Campaign Crisis

- Mid-summer: Trump losing ground to Clinton, victory didn't seem possible
- Saturday, August 13: _New York Times_ published front-page story detailing campaign's ongoing chaos
- Trump wouldn't use teleprompter, couldn't stay on message, wasn't able to tame embarrassing leaks
- Republican donors jumping ship
- Landslide victory for Clinton seemed possible, even likely

### Mercer's Call to Bannon

- Later that day: **Bob Mercer called Bannon** asking what could be done
- Bannon outlined series of ideas including **making Conway more frequent TV presence** to defend Trump

### East Hampton Meeting (August 13)

- Same day: Mercers boarded helicopter to **Woody Johnson's East Hampton beachfront estate** (NY Jets owner)
- GOP backers including Wall Street investors **Carl Icahn and Steve Mnuchin** gathering to meet Trump
- Clutching _Times_ story, **Rebekah made beeline for candidate**

> "It's bad," Trump acknowledged.
> "No, it's not bad—it's over," she told Trump. "Unless you make a change."

- Told Trump she had way to turn election around

> "Bring in Steve Bannon and Kellyanne Conway. I've talked to them; they'll do it."

### August 14: Bedminster Meeting

- Next day: **Bannon took Uber to Trump National Golf Club** (Bedminster, NJ)
- After impatiently waiting for Trump to finish golf, eat hot dogs, finish ice-cream, **Bannon made pitch**

> "No doubt you can win. You just have to get organized."

- Before long: **Bannon running campaign**, Conway its manager
- Became ubiquitous, effective TV presence
- Bannon helped instill order
- Made sure Trump focused on two things: disparaging Clinton's character, promoting **nationalism** (Bannon branded **"America First"**)
- Slogan seemed to echo **short-lived America First Committee** (group that levied pressure to prevent US from entering WWII, opposing Hitler)

### October 7: Access Hollywood Tape

- Bannon made headway on Trump's current behavior
- Couldn't do anything about past actions
- October 7: _Washington Post_ broke story about outtake footage from _Access Hollywood_
- Trump bragged (lewd, graphic language) about kissing, groping, trying to bed women

> "When you're a star, they let you do it," Trump said.

- Mainstream Republicans condemned Trump
- **Mercers rushed out full-throated statement of support**

<!-- pp. 253-272 -->

## Chapter 14 (continued): Political Divides

### Mercer and Simons: The Widening Political Rift

- **Mercer** quote to Rebekah and Bob: "We are completely indifferent to Mr. Trump's locker-room braggadocio. We have a country to save, and there is only one person who can save it."
- **Jim Simons** leaned left politically, shaped by witnessing hardships experienced by minorities with childhood friend **Jim Harpel**
- By mid-2016, **Simons** had become the most important supporter of the **Democratic Party's Priorities USA Action super PAC**
- By end of 2016, **Simons** donated over **$27 million to Democratic causes**
- **Marilyn Simons** even more liberal than her husband; son **Nathaniel** founded nonprofit focused on climate change and clean energy
- The Trump campaign generally mocked or ignored

### Simons' Dilemma with Mercer

- As **Mercer's** political influence grew with Trump support, **Simons** heard complaints from associates: "Can't you do something about him?"
- **Simons** in difficult position: only recently became aware of Mercer's alliance with **Bannon** and political opinions
- **Simons** disagreed with Mercer's views on global warming but still liked Mercer personally
- **Simons** noted it's illegal to fire someone for political beliefs

> "Professional performance and political views are two separate things." — Jim Simons

- Both **Medallion** and **RIEF** enjoyed strong performance; **Mercer** doing good job leading Renaissance with **Brown**
- **Peter Brown** didn't like spending his money on politics, but wife's government experience "soured him" on politics
- **Brown** told someone the election might help the hedge fund by bringing volatility to financial markets
- **Mercer** remained outlier at firm politically; no obvious signs his outside activities harmed the firm

### Election Night 2016

- Trump's team didn't think they'd win; Republican data team projected **no more than 204 electoral votes**
- At 5:01 p.m., **David Bossie** received early exit numbers: Trump down in 8 of 11 crucial states by 5-8 points
- Trump snapped his flip phone closed and threw it across the room

> "What a waste of time and money." — Donald Trump (to no one in particular)

- Around 9 p.m., **Bob Mercer** arrived at war room in **posh three-piece gray suit**
- **Bannon** joked someone had invited **Rich Uncle Pennybags** (the Monopoly mascot)
- Around 1 a.m., **Kellyanne Conway** received call from Associated Press editor

> "We're not calling a state. We're calling the race." — AP editor to Conway

### Simons' Reaction to Trump Victory

- As election approached, **Simons** expressed concern; **Clinton** led in most polls but seemed to be making strategic miscalculations
- Clinton's team reached out to **Simons** saying if he was going to donate more, direct to party's effort to win Senate
- Clinton camp seemed so confident they deemed additional help unnecessary
- On election night, **Jim and Marilyn** watched results at friend's home with Clinton supporters
- Around 9:30 p.m., **Simons** had had enough: "I'm going back to the apartment to have a drink"
- **Simons** and **Abe Lackman** (political advisor) quietly sipped red wine as Trump sealed election
- Before midnight, they turned television off

> "We were pretty depressed." — Abe Lackman

## Chapter 15: The Political Aftermath

### Morning After: Simons Foundation Staff Meeting (November 9, 2016)

- Nearly **50 scientists, researchers, employees** spontaneously assembled at **Simons Foundation headquarters** in lower Manhattan
- Staff concerned about nation's future and their own; worried incoming Trump administration would target charitable foundations
- Some wondered if foundation's **tax-exempt status** could be stripped as retribution
- **Simons** in blue blazer and tan chinos reminded staff of importance of their work: autism research, understanding origins of universe, worthy endeavors

> "We're all disappointed. The best we can do is focus on our work." — Jim Simons

- Employees slowly returned to offices, some newly reassured
- **Simons** was somber, but **Bob Mercer** was celebratory

### Mercer's Holiday Party: Trump Visits Owl's Nest

- **Mercers** preparing for annual holiday party at **Owl's Nest** (Long Island estate), held early December each year
- Since 2009, family welcomed hundreds for elaborate, themed costume affair
- 2016 theme: **"Villains and Heroes"** — invitation featured sword-wielding centurion facing Medusa
- **Mercers** directed guests to secret website with costume suggestions: Superman, Captain Hook, Mother Teresa
- **Peter Thiel** dressed as **Hulk Hogan**; **Kellyanne Conway** as **Superwoman**
- **Steve Bannon** came as himself (jab at those who deemed his activities villainous, or suggestion he was election's hero)
- **Bob Mercer** dressed as **Mandrake the Magician** (comic-book superhero who hypnotizes targets)
- **Rebekah** came as **Black Widow** in black latex
- **Donald Trump** took break from transition meetings to join the group
- Between **$26 million** Mercer spent on Republican causes, daughter's insistence Trump hire Bannon/Conway, and **Breitbart News** support, **Bob and Rebekah Mercer** among those most responsible for Trump's victory

> "The Mercers laid the groundwork for the Trump revolution. Irrefutably, when you look at the donors during the past four years, they have had the single biggest impact of anybody." — Steve Bannon

- Trump made way through guests, stopped to greet **Mercer**, addressed crowd
- Trump joked he'd just had his longest conversation with Mercer — **"two words"**
- Trump lauded **Mercer's** support, thanked him and **Rebekah** for urging hire of **Bannon, Conway, Bossie**

### Post-Election: Mercer's Influence Grows

- In aftermath, **Mercer** focused on running Renaissance, working closely with **Peter Brown**
- **Mercer** didn't seek ambassadorship or other obvious rewards
- **Bannon** became **White House chief strategist**
- **Conway** became **counselor to the president** — ensured **Mercer** had unparalleled access to Trump
- **Mercer** remained one of Republican Party's most important patrons, controlled **Breitbart News**
- **Rebekah Mercer** assumed more active role: ensconced in **Bannon's office** in Trump Tower for weeks as advisor on cabinet nominee selection
- **Mercer** successfully lobbied for **Senator Jeff Sessions** as attorney general
- Pushed hard to prevent **Mitt Romney** from becoming secretary of state
- Played role in choice of **Jay Clayton** to lead **US Securities and Exchange Commission** (raised eyebrows since her father was co-CEO of major hedge fund)
- President turned to **Rebekah's** longtime associate **Leonard Leo** (ran conservative **Federalist Society**) for guidance on judicial nominees
- **Rebekah** made plans to lead outside group to support Trump's agenda
- Early 2017, ***GQ* magazine** named **Mercer** the **17th most powerful person in Washington, DC** — "First Lady of the alt-right"

### David Magerman's Growing Discontent

- **David Magerman**: registered Democrat, political centrist, sometimes voted Republican
- 2016 different story: Trump disparaged immigrants, spoke of shifting funds from public schools to charter schools, promised border wall
- Trump's view to restrict abortion rights worried **Magerman** and horrified his wife **Debra**
- After election, **Magerman** unfriended almost everyone on Facebook to avoid painful reminders
- After inauguration, **Magerman** reconsidered position — thought he might move administration in benign direction
- Forty-eight-year-old had spent decade working on education-related issues

### Magerman Confronts Mercer (January 2017)

- **Magerman** called **Rebekah Mercer** but she didn't pick up; tried again, left message
- **Magerman** got return call from **Bob Mercer** (unusual — Mercer rarely called)
- Despite shyness, **Mercer** eager to discuss Trump and contentious political topics
- They disagreed about climate change, Obamacare, border wall, but tone remained civil
- **Mercer** said about Trump: "He will blow things up"
- **Magerman** worried about bringing back fear of nuclear war
- **Mercer** said he wasn't all that concerned about nuclear war; enjoyed their back-and-forth
- **Magerman** left more frustrated

### Magerman Watches Trump's Early Actions

- Late January 2017: Trump signed executive order banning foreign nationals from **seven predominantly Muslim countries** for 90 days, suspending Syrian refugee entry
- Senate confirmed **Sessions** as attorney general
- Trump continued attacking credibility of US intelligence community and media
- **Magerman** wanted to temper or counteract administration's policies
- Made plans to donate to local Democrats, called **Planned Parenthood**
- Tried calling **Jared Kushner** (Trump's son-in-law) to warn about policies and Mercer's influence — failed to reach him
- **Magerman** felt guilt: Mercer's foundation invested in **Medallion fund**, so Magerman felt he'd personally helped provide Mercer resources to put Trump in office

> "It pisses me off. I've made software that makes white rich guys like Mercer even richer." — David Magerman to Debra

### Magerman and Mercer's Phone Confrontation

- In phone calls with colleagues, **Magerman** complained about how **Mercer** made Trump presidency possible
- **Magerman** shared conversation where **Mercer** argued **African Americans** had been better off **before enactment of Civil Rights Act of 1964**
- Word reached **Mercer**; one day **Mercer** called **Magerman** at home office
- **Mercer** accused **Magerman**: "I hear you're going around saying I'm a white supremacist"
- **Magerman** stammered: "Those weren't my exact words"
- **Magerman** cited **Mercer's** earlier comments about Civil Rights Act
- **Mercer**: "I'm sure I never would have said that"
- **Mercer** recited data claiming **African Americans** enjoyed better standard of living in decade before legislation, including statistics about percentage in various professions
- **Mercer** promised to send **Magerman** a book to prove his points
- **Mercer** told **Magerman**: Civil Rights Act **"infantilized"** African Americans **"by making them dependent on the government"**
- **Magerman** now really upset: "Bob—they had to use separate bathrooms and water fountains!"
- **Magerman** outlined concerns about Trump's policy positions, rhetoric, cabinet choices
- **Mercer** responded he wasn't involved in decisions by Trump or those close to him; simply wanted to prevent Clinton from being elected
- **Magerman** screamed: "How can you say you're not involved?" — pointing to **Rebekah Mercer's** group to boost Trump's agenda, close relationships with Bannon and Conway
- **Magerman** told **Mercer**: "You should meet Bannon. He's a sweet guy. If what you're doing is harming the country, then you have to stop!"
- **Mercer** didn't seem especially perturbed; used to having it out with liberal staff members — almost a sport for him

### Mercer Sends Book to Magerman

- Few days later, **Mercer** sent **Magerman** book: ***Civil Rights: Rhetoric or Reality?*** (1984) by **Hoover Institution economist Thomas Sowell**
- ***New York Times*** called it "brutally frank, perceptive, and important"
- Book argues minorities began moving into higher-paying jobs **before passage of Civil Rights Act**
- Claims affirmative action caused most disadvantaged segments of minority population to fall behind white counterparts
- **Magerman** says **Sowell's** argument "focuses on narrow financial measures, but ignores overall human factors" — one of many criticisms

### Magerman Goes Public

- **Magerman** unsettled by conversation with **Mercer**; wanted to do something to stop his boss
- **Magerman** dug through **Renaissance** employee handbook to see what discipline he might face
- Spoke with **Peter Brown** and **Mark Silber** — they doubted **Mercer** had made racist comments
- (Another executive joked **Mercer** didn't speak enough for anyone to know if he was racist)
- **Magerman** understood from conversations he was likely safe criticizing **Mercer** if he avoided saying anything about Renaissance
- February 2017: **Magerman** sent email to ***Wall Street Journal*** reporter: "I'm ready to take action. Enough is enough."
- In resulting interview at restaurant **Magerman** owned in **Bala Cynwyd, Pennsylvania**, held little back

> "His views show contempt for the social safety net that he doesn't need, but many Americans do. Now he's using the money I helped him make to implement his worldview" by supporting Trump and proposing "government be shrunk down to the size of a pinhead." — David Magerman

- **Magerman** shared concern about own future: "I'd like to think I'm speaking out in a way that won't risk my job, but it's very possible they could fire me. This is my life's work—I ran a group that wrote the trading system they still use."
- Morning online version appeared, **Magerman** received phone call from **Renaissance**
- Representative told **Magerman** he was **being suspended without pay** and prohibited from having contact with company

### Backlash Against Mercer Intensifies

- Election starting to cause discomfort for **Mercer**
- **Mercer** and **Rebekah** closely associated with **Bannon** and far-right segment — became targets for those unhappy with nation's lurch to right
- **New York State Democratic Committee** ran TV ad flashing **Bob and Rebekah Mercer's** faces: "same people who bankrolled Trump's social media bot army and Steve Bannon's extremist Breitbart News"
- March 2017: about **60 demonstrators** gathered outside **Mercer's** home, decrying funding of far-right causes, calling for higher taxes on wealthy
- Week later, second protest with signs: **"Mercer Pay Your Taxes"**
- Police officers closed road in front of **Owl's Nest**; protesters stood in pouring rain for hours
- **Bill McNulty** (82-year-old local resident): **"Mercer played a major role in bringing about the election of Donald Trump. We saw the corrosive and contaminating effect of dark money on politics."**
- **Mercers** received death threats, forcing family to hire security

### Renaissance's Dilemma with Magerman

- **Renaissance** rarely fires employees — risk too great
- Even lackluster, midlevel researchers and programmers privy to insights that may prove helpful to rivals
- **Magerman** had committed cardinal sin: attacked boss in public, suggested he was racist
- Few companies as publicity-shy as **Renaissance** — one reason many reluctant to welcome **Magerman** back
- **Magerman** had mixed feelings: made so much money didn't have to worry about financial pain of getting fired
- **Magerman** loathed what **Mercer** was doing to country, wanted to stop political activity
- But **Magerman** remembered how kind **Mercer** and wife had been when he first joined firm (dinners at Friendly's, movie nights with family)
- **Magerman** respected **Bob** for intelligence and creativity; big part still yearned to please powerful men in his life
- Had spent two decades at **Renaissance**, felt appreciation for firm
- Decided if he could go on speaking about **Mercer's** politics, he'd return to old job

### Magerman's Attempted Reconciliation

- As **Magerman** discussed future with **Brown** and others, didn't make it easy: "I can't take hush money"
- **Magerman** visited Long Island office — hurt that many staffers seemed unfriendly
- Either that, or left-leaning staffers thought he went about protest wrong way: "People I expected to be warm and fuzzy were standoffish. They see me as the bad guy."
- Two sides worked out tentative agreement for **Magerman** to return, with conditions on what he could say about **Mercer**
- Deal wasn't finalized
- To repair relationship, **Magerman** decided to attend **April 20 poker tournament** at **New York's St. Regis hotel** benefiting **Math for America** (nonprofit **Simons** had founded)
- Event highly anticipated annual showdown for quants, professional poker players
- **Magerman** knew **Simons, Mercer, Brown**, other **Renaissance** executives would be there
- Wondered if **Rebekah Mercer** would show up: "I wanted to reintroduce myself and be part of the culture again, to show I was making an effort."

### Poker Tournament Confrontation

- As **Magerman** made three-hour drive from home, began feeling anxious
- At hotel, **Magerman** pledged **$5,000** to enter tournament
- Immediately noticed he hadn't dressed appropriately: most of ~200 players in carpeted, second-floor ballroom wore suits or sports jackets
- Security team wore tuxedos; **Magerman** went with jeans and open-collared dress shirt — mistake that added to discomfort
- **Magerman** entered poker room, immediately saw **Bob Mercer**
- Walked right up, complimented him on color of suit (unusual shade of blue)
- **Mercer** smiled, said one of his daughters had picked it out — exchange seemed to go well
- *Phew*, **Magerman** thought
- Just after 7 p.m., **Magerman** began playing **No-Limit Hold'em** at table with **Simons**, **Poker Hall of Fame** member **Dan Harrington**
- When **Simons** ducked into side room to smoke, **Magerman** followed
- Apologized for negative attention thrust on firm after criticism of **Mercers**

> "I'm sorry how things played out. I respect you and want you to know that." — David Magerman to Jim Simons

- **Simons** accepted apology, said standoff seemed to be coming to resolution
- Back at table, **Magerman** lost some early hands but remained in good spirits, pledging additional **$15,000** for buy-ins
- Few tables away, **Mercer** playing against investors including **sport-finance executive Chris English**
- **Mercer** won several early hands; **English** detected tell: when **Mercer** played great hand, he whistled patriotic songs including **"The Battle Hymn of the Republic"**
- When less confident of cards, **Mercer** hummed those songs
- **English** quickly won pot over **Mercer**
- Around 10:30 p.m., after consuming several glasses of twelve-year-old scotch, **Magerman** out of tournament
- Too early to go home, still on high from rapprochement, decided to walk room and watch others play
- Approached table that included **Rebekah Mercer** — she was staring at him
- As **Magerman** got closer, **Mercer** became agitated, called to him in anger: **"Karma is a bitch."**
- Shaken, **Magerman** walked around table and stood next to **Mercer**
- She told **Magerman** his criticism of **Mercers'** support for Trump had put her family in danger

> "How could you do this to my father? He was so good to you." — Rebekah Mercer to Magerman

- **Magerman** said he felt bad, noting her family had played supportive role when he joined **Renaissance**
- She wouldn't hear it
- **Rebekah** told him repeatedly: **"You're *pond scum*. You've been pond scum for twenty-five years. I've always known it."**
- Security member approached, telling **Magerman** to back away from table
- **Magerman** refused, dodged security detail, approached **Simons** asking for help: "Jim, look what they're trying to do to me"
- **Simons** told him: It's best if you left the event
- Security forced **Magerman** outside to curb, threatening to call police if he didn't leave
- **Boaz Weinstein** (another hedge-fund investor) saw how distraught **Magerman** was, urged him to walk off drinks and drive home
- Took some convincing, but **Magerman** complied, heading for car

> "I'm not denying I was a little impacted by the alcohol. . . . It wasn't one of my finest moments. It wasn't my intent to create a scene. But that doesn't change what she said to me . . . I didn't start the fight, and I didn't resort to the petty name calling." — David Magerman

- Back upstairs, players buzzed about confrontation, but tournament went on
- Soon, **Bob Mercer** on tear, rebounding from earlier setback
- **Simons, Peter Muller** of **PDT Partners**, **Brown** all exited play, but **Mercer** kept going
- In evening's last big pot, around 1 a.m., knocked **English** out of tournament
- **English**: "He might have been humming to reverse his tell. It was so loud, I couldn't tell."
- As **Mercer** smiled and accepted congratulations, **Magerman** on way back to Philadelphia
- Received text from **Brown**: "Best to rise above all this and just live your life without getting caught up in a battle. I honestly think you will be happier."
- **April 29, Renaissance fired Magerman**

### Anthony Calhoun's Growing Anger

- By early fall 2017, **Anthony Calhoun's** anger had intensified
- Executive director of **Baltimore City Fire and Police Employees' Retirement System** — the more he read about **Mercer's** political activities, the more they bothered him
- Backing Trump wasn't problem for **Calhoun** — it was **Breitbart**, which had become associated with white nationalists
- By then, **Bannon** had been pushed out as chief strategist to president, back at **Breitbart** — some expected him to push publication to further extremes
- **Mercer** also backed **Milo Yiannopoulos** (right-wing provocateur who called feminism **"cancer"**, appeared to endorse pedophilia, barred from Twitter for abusing others)
- All too much for **Calhoun**
- **Baltimore retirement system** had **$25 million invested in RIEF**; **Calhoun** decided to share displeasure with **Renaissance**
- Called **RIEF** representative: "We've got real concerns"
- Representative said **Calhoun** wasn't only one calling with complaints about **Mercer**
- When **Calhoun** began speaking with industry consultants, heard other **Renaissance** clients sharing own unhappiness
- Soon, **Calhoun** and rest of **Baltimore retirement system** board voted to pull money out of **RIEF**
- Cash tiny part of **Renaissance** fund; no one at firm worried about exodus of investors
- But October 2017, nearly **50 protesters** picketed hedge fund itself, saying **Mercer** was their target — added to discomfort of executives not accustomed to negative publicity
- By October 2017, **Simons** worried controversy jeopardizing **Renaissance's** future
- Firm's morale deteriorating; at least one key employee close to quitting, another mulled departure
- Among most important employees to convey concerns: **Wolfgang Wander** (earned PhD in high-energy physics at **University of Erlangen–Nuremberg** in Bavaria, Germany)
- **Wander** headed firm's infrastructure group — effectively **Renaissance's most senior technology officer**
- **Simons** became convinced **Renaissance** would have tougher time competing for talent
- For more than year, **Simons** had ignored **Mercer's** growing role in politics
- Now felt compelled to act
- On crisp October morning, **Simons** dropped by **Mercer's** office
- Sat in chair opposite **Mercer**, came quickly to point: **"I think it's best if you stepped down"**
- Wasn't political decision but one made to ensure firm's future
- Scrutiny on firm **"isn't good for morale"**
- **Mercer** wasn't prepared for news, looked sad and hurt, but accepted **Simons's** decision without protest
- Later, **Simons** told group of students and others at **MIT's business school**: **"there was a problem of morale at Renaissance . . . morale was getting worse."**

> "It wasn't an easy decision." — Jim Simons (to a friend)

### Mercer's Resignation Letter (November 2, 2017)

- **Mercer** wrote letter to **Renaissance** investors saying he was resigning as co-CEO but would remain researcher
- Blamed **"scrutiny from the press"**, said media had unfairly linked him to **Bannon**

> "The press has . . . intimated that my politics marches in lockstep with Steve Bannon's. I have great respect for Mr. Bannon, and from time to time I do discuss politics with him. However, I make my own decisions with respect to whom I support politically." — Bob Mercer

- **Mercer** clarified political views: supports **"conservatives who favor a smaller, less powerful government"**
- Said he supported **Yiannopoulos** in effort to back free speech and open debate, but regretted move and was severing ties
- Selling stake in **Breitbart News** to daughters

### Robert Frey's Lunch with Mercer (Early 2018)

- Few months after stepping down, **Mercer** received call from **Robert Frey** (former **Renaissance** executive who founded quantitative finance program at **Stony Brook University's College of Engineering and Applied Sciences**)
- **Frey** invited **Mercer** to lunch at pedestrian restaurant in nearby **Hilton Garden Inn** (only restaurant on Stony Brook's campus with waiter service)
- Couple students recognized **Frey**, said hello, but no one seemed to notice **Mercer** — likely relief to him
- **Mercer** looked drained; **Frey** wanted to get something out before food arrived
- During election, **Frey** unhappy with both candidates, couldn't bring himself to vote for either Trump or Clinton
- Told **Mercer** he was fully within his right to actively support Trump in any way he saw fit
- Despite widespread criticism, didn't believe **Mercer** had done anything improper

> "There's been an imbalance in how you were treated. Soros and other people influence politics as much as you do, but they aren't vilified like you are." — Robert Frey to Bob Mercer

- **Mercer** smiled, gave nod, but didn't say much in response: "Thanks"
- **Mercer's** reaction gave **Frey** feeling he should change subject
- Friends talked about math and market, steering clear of politics for rest of meal

> "I felt bad for him." — Robert Frey

### Rebekah Mercer's Continued Backlash

- **Rebekah Mercer** having even harder time
- **Mercer** shared frustrations with friends about how she and father had been portrayed, said some unfairly accused her of supporting racist causes
- Criticism sparked backlash: once received fecal matter in mail; another time stranger insulted her in public, leaving her shaking
- January 2018: more than **200 scientists and academics** who supported policy action to stop climate change endorsed open letter calling on **American Museum of Natural History** to remove **Mercer** from board (served five years)
- Urged museum to **"end ties to the anti-science propagandists and funders of climate science misinformation"**
- Over dozen protesters marched outside museum on Manhattan's Upper West Side with placards: **"Get Rebekah Out of Our Museum"** and **"Climate Change Is Real"**
- Museum never took action, but February 2018 **Mercer** felt need to shift public perception
- Wrote op-ed in ***Wall Street Journal*** denying she supported **"toxic ideologies such as racism and anti-Semitism"**
- Added she believed in **"a kind and generous United States"**
- Month later, new controversy: **Cambridge Analytica** accused of acquiring private Facebook data of millions of users
- **Mercer** on **Cambridge's board of directors**, helped oversee company's operations — came in for new round of scrutiny and negative media coverage
- By middle of 2018, **Bob and Rebekah Mercer** pulling back from politics
- **Mercers** had broken with **Bannon** soon after he was quoted making critical comment about Trump's family
- Left **Mercers** without political consigliere
- In lead-up to 2018 midterm elections, **Mercer** made just under **$6 million** in disclosed political contributions (down from almost **$10 million** in 2014, over **$25 million** in 2016)

> "They've fallen off the grid. We don't hear much from them." — Leading member of conservative movement (late 2018)

- Friends said unexpected blowback prompted shift to lower-key approach with smaller political contributions, little regular communication with Trump or administration members
- Part of reason for disappointment: most biggest donors to Trump campaign received something for generosity
- **Mercers** never asked for anything; yet other financial executives (even those who hadn't supported Trump, like **Blackstone Group Chief Executive Stephen Schwarzman**) were ones regularly speaking with president
- **Mercers** also made strategic flubs: June 2018, **Bob Mercer** gave **half million dollars** to PAC backing **Kelli Ward** (drew criticism for accusing family of **Senator John McCain** for timing announcement of end of McCain's cancer treatment to undercut her campaign)
- **Ward** trounced in Arizona Republican Senate primary
- As president and Republican Party geared up for 2020 election, **Mercers** remained well positioned to influence campaign
- Still close to **Conway**; while no longer had **Bannon** as conduit, **Mercers** big backers of PAC that supported **US National Security Advisor John Bolton**
- **Mercers** told friends they were happy Trump administration had cut taxes and chosen conservative judges — didn't regret becoming so involved in national politics
- Still, **Rebekah Mercer** seemed more focused on other issues far from headlines, such as working to boost free speech on college campuses
- October 2018, when honored at Washington, DC gala, **Mercer** shared concerns about level of discourse on college campuses

> Schools "churn out a wave of ovine zombies steeped in the anti-American myths of the radical left, ignorant of basic civics, economics, and history, and completely unfit for critical thinking." — Rebekah Mercer (October 2018 gala)

- Wearing red, flowing gown and distinctive diamond-studded glasses, **Mercer** served notice she'd continue to push to limit role of government, make sure politicians emphasized **"personal liberty"**
- Calling President Trump **"a force of nature"**, **Mercer** indicated she'd continue to play active role in nation's politics despite backlash

> "I will not be silenced." — Rebekah Mercer

