## Chapter Sixteen: The Rise of Quantitative Investing

### December 2018: Simons's Moment of Doubt
- Late December 2018, **Jim Simons** worried at Beverly Hills Hotel as S&P 500 fell 10% (worst December since 1931)
- Worth ~$23 billion but felt each day's loss like "a fresh punch to the gut"
- Made substantial charitable commitments through foundation employing hundreds
- Called **Ashvin Chhabra** at **Euclidean Capital** (manages personal money) to discuss shorting stocks for protection
- Chhabra advised waiting; stocks firmed next day

> "Should we be selling short?" — Jim Simons to Ashvin Chhabra, Dec 2018

### The Irony: Pioneering Quant Investing, Falling Back on Emotion
- Simons spent three decades revolutionizing finance through quantitative methods
- By 2018, the establishment embraced "the Renaissance way": data digestion, mathematical models, automated trading
- **JPMorgan Chase** now trains investment bankers with mandatory coding lessons
- Yet Simons—quant pioneer—was relying on gut instinct and emotions after market turbulence

> "Jim Simons and Renaissance showed it was possible." — **Dario Villani**, PhD theoretical physicist & hedge fund operator

### The Decline of Traditional Active Management (by 2019)
- Confidence in traditional stock picking waned after years of poor performance
- Actively managed stock-mutual funds held only 50% of stock-mutual fund money (down from 75% a decade earlier)
- Other 50% in **index funds** and **passive vehicles** acknowledging the difficulty of beating the market
- Failed stars: **John Paulson** (predicted 2007 subprime crisis, then suffered deep losses), **David Einhorn** ("King David" lost clients after poor performance), **Bill Gross** (PIMCO returns slipped), **Warren Buffett** (Berkshire Hathaway trailed S&P 500 over five, ten, fifteen years to May 2019)

### Information Asymmetry Has Disappeared
- Traditional funds once had luxury of finding overlooked nuggets in annual reports
- Today: any financial figure available instantly via keystroke/news feed, captured by machines
- Crackdown on insider trading + regulatory changes leveled the playing field
- No longer could big hedge funds receive advance calls from brokers about news or bank views
- Example: August 2018, **Geron Corporation** shares soared 25% after **Johnson & Johnson** job listing suggested regulatory approval imminent—only those with tech to scour job listings instantly benefited

### The Quant Ascendancy (Early 2019)
- **Quant investors** represented ~1/3 of all stock-market trades (share more than doubled since 2013)
- **2018 earnings**: Simons $1.5B, **Two Sigma** founders $700M each, **Ray Dalio** (Bridgewater) $1B, **Israel Englander** $500M
- **Ken Griffin** (Citadel) spent $238M on NYC penthouse (most expensive US home ever sold), owned Chicago condo floors + Miami penthouse + $500M in Jackson Pollock and Willem de Kooning paintings

### The Data Explosion Ahead
- **IBM estimate**: 90% of world's data created in last two years; 44 trillion gigabytes expected by 2020 (three-hundred-fold increase from 2005)
- The rage: **alternative data**—satellite images, executive tone on conference calls, parking-lot traffic at retail stores, auto-insurance applications, social media influencer recommendations
- Examples: farm equipment sales (not agricultural production reports), bills of lading for cargo, cell phone data on store aisles/shelves, Amazon reviews, FDA commissioner backgrounds analyzed by algorithms
- Hedge funds hire **data analysts/data hunters** (like **Sandor Straus** at Renaissance in 1980s)

### Exponential Computing Power
- **Singularity Hub** prediction: by ~2025, $1,000 buys computer with human-brain processing power
- **Two Sigma** already built system with 100+ teraflops (100 trillion calculations/second) + 11 petabytes memory (5x all US academic libraries)
- Allows quants to test millions of formulas via machine-learning engines instead of hit-and-miss creativity

> "Instead of the hit-and-miss strategy of trying to find signals using creativity and thought, now you can just throw a class of formulas at a machine-learning engine and test out millions of different possibilities." — Renaissance computer specialist

### Machine Learning Spreads
- Years after Renaissance adopted machine learning, other quants embraced these methods
- Renaissance anticipated transformation now sweeping business and life
- Companies/individuals embrace models that continuously learn from successes and failures
- **Matthew Granade** noted: Amazon, Tencent, Netflix rely on dynamic, ever-changing models

> "When the shrinks for their kids are replaced by algorithms, that'll be the end; there'll be nothing left." — Novelist **Gary Shteyngart** on finance industry's future

### Limitations of Quantitative Investing
- Not easy to process information and discover signals in noisy data
- Some argue picking stocks harder for machines than recognizing faces, choosing songs, driving cars
- Hard to teach machines to distinguish blueberry muffin from Chihuahua
- Some big firms (London's **Man AHL**) use machine learning for timing/mapping connections, not automated investment decisions
- **Five years to spring 2019**: quant hedge funds gained 4.2%/year average vs 3.3% for average hedge fund (excludes secretive funds like Medallion)
- Challenges: information always changing (unlike physics), limited pricing histories for stocks

> "Say you're trying to predict how stocks will perform over a one-year horizon. Because we only have decent records back to 1900, there are only 118 nonoverlapping one-year periods to look at in the US." — **Richard Dewey**, veteran quant

- Difficult for troubled investments (debt, judge rulings, legal maneuverings, creditor negotiations)—traditional investors may prosper in longer-term investing that algorithmic investors avoid

### The Flash Crash and Systemic Risks
- **May 6, 2010**: Dow Jones plummeted 1,000 points in minutes (**"flash crash"**)—hundreds of stocks momentarily lost nearly all value
- Investors blamed computer-programmed trading; prosecutors later charged West London trader for manipulating stock-market-index futures
- Automated trading by computers scary like autopilot/self-driving cars, despite safety improvements
- **Richard Bookstaber** argues risks significant because quant models "system-wide across investment world"—future troubles could have greater impact
- As more embrace quantitative trading, market nature could change; new error types not yet experienced

### Dangers Overstated: Quant Diversity Stabilizes Markets
- So many quant investing varieties impossible to generalize
- Some employ momentum strategies (intensify selling); others use **smart beta**, factor investing, **style investing** (largest/fastest-growing categories)—practitioners programmed to buy when stocks cheap, helping stabilize
- Market participants always pulled back during crises—quant reluctance not very different
- Markets more placid as quants assumed dominant positions
- Humans prone to fear, greed, panic (sow volatility); machines could make markets **more** stable
- Computer-driven decision-making in other fields (airline industry) generally led to fewer mistakes

### Renaissance's Continued Dominance (Summer 2019)
- **Medallion fund**: 66% average annual gains before fees since 1988, 39% after fees (despite RIEF's early stumbles)
- Three hedge funds open for outside investors also outperformed rivals and indexes
- June 2019: Renaissance managed $65 billion (one of largest hedge funds), sometimes 5% of daily stock-market trading volume (excluding high-frequency traders)

### Why Renaissance Succeeds: Predictability of Human Behavior
- Renaissance studies the past, confident investors make similar future decisions
- Staffers embrace scientific method to combat cognitive/emotional biases
- Propose hypotheses, test, measure, adjust theories—let data (not intuition/instinct) guide

> "The approach is scientific. We use very rigorous statistical approaches to determine what we think is underlying." — Jim Simons

### More Factors Influence Markets Than Most Realize
- Investors focus on basic forces, but dozens of factors (whole dimensions) missed
- Renaissance aware of more overlooked mathematical relationships affecting stock prices than anyone else
- Like bees seeing broad color spectrum in flowers invisible to humans—Renaissance sees enough market hues to profit (aided by ample leverage)
- Firm endured challenging periods; stands to reason matching past success difficult as markets evolve
- Current/former employees marvel at gains and acknowledge hurdles ahead

### Market Inefficiencies Likely Fewer Than Assumed
- Renaissance's gains suggest more inefficiencies exist than most assume
- Truth: likely fewer inefficiencies/opportunities than generally presumed
- Despite unique data, computer firepower, talent, expertise, Renaissance profits on barely >50% of trades—sign of difficulty beating market

### Renaissance Avoids Pure Stock-Move Predictions
- Simons and colleagues generally avoid predicting pure stock moves
- Not clear any expert/system can reliably predict individual stocks long-term or financial market direction
- What Renaissance does: anticipate stock moves **relative** to other stocks, to an index, to a factor model, to an industry

### Elwyn Berlekamp's View: Quants Breed Misplaced Confidence
- **Elwyn Berlekamp** (Medallion fund manager) came to view narratives most investors latch onto as dangerous—breed misplaced confidence
- If up to Berlekamp, stocks would have numbers attached, not names

> "I don't deny that earnings reports and other business news surely move markets. The problem is that so many investors focus so much on these types of news that nearly all of their results cluster very near their average." — Elwyn Berlekamp

### The David Magerman Lawsuits (Post-Firing)
- After **Rebekah Mercer** had **David Magerman** tossed from poker night at St. Regis, Renaissance fired the computer scientist
- Magerman filed two lawsuits: federal civil rights claim against **Robert Mercer**, wrongful termination suit against Renaissance and Mercer
- Alleged Mercer terminated him for "engaging in protected activity"
- Magerman acknowledged employee handbook prohibited public disparagement, but said he obtained approval from at least one Renaissance executive before sharing concerns with **Wall Street Journal**
- Magerman nursed hurt feelings about cold shoulder from old workmates

> "I worked for Renaissance for over twenty years, they're the one place I ever worked in my professional life. I had an obligation to inform the public. . . . And that was the end of it, as far as I'm concerned, except that I got suspended and fired." — David Magerman

- **2018**: After months of negotiations, amicable settlement—Magerman exited Renaissance with right to invest in Medallion like other retirees
- Age fifty, Magerman adopted new cause: combating powerful social media companies
- Gave nearly $500K to coalition lobbying to break up Facebook, accepted senior position at Philadelphia venture-capital firm working with fledgling data-related companies

> "I feel very good about where I am now, mentally and personally. I wouldn't quite go as far to say there's no hard feelings. But, you know, I've definitely moved on." — David Magerman, late 2018

### Peter Brown Takes the Helm (Post-Mercer, November 2017)
- After Mercer stepped down as co-chief executive (November 2017), staffers skeptical much would change
- Mercer still employed at Renaissance, continued within earshot of Brown
- Unlike other researchers, Mercer reported directly to Brown (sign of continued prominence)
- Employees worried Brown would rush into ill-advised decisions without Mercer to guide him
- Feared change would hurt returns as more firms rushed into quant trading (more competition)

### Brown's Management Shift: Collaboration Over Dictatorship
- Brown responded by tweaking management style
- Still kept manic pace, sleeping in Murphy bed in office most weekday nights
- Began leaning on other senior staffers, asking input from mixed group of colleagues
- Shift steadied firm, helped Medallion end 2018 with flourish
- Gains of ~45% in 2018, besting almost every investment firm in year S&P 500 dropped >6% (worst since 2008)
- Renaissance's three investor funds (Renaissance Institutional Equities Fund, Renaissance Institutional Diversified Alpha Fund, Renaissance Institutional Diversified Global Equity Fund) all topped market
- Money poured in; overall assets surged past $60 billion (one of largest hedge funds worldwide)

> "I think everything is under control. As long as you keep making money for investors, they're generally pretty happy." — Jim Simons, late 2018

### Simons's 80th Birthday Celebration (Spring 2018)
- Family's foundation marked occasion with lecture series focused on Simons's physics contributions
- Academics/others toasted Simons at nearby hotel
- Month later, hosted family/friends on ship **Archimedes** for nighttime cruise around Manhattan
- Distinct stoop in shoulders accented advancing age, but razor-sharp with probing questions and humorous quips

> "I promise not to turn eighty again." — Jim Simons, joking to crowd

- Seemed to have arrived at comfortable landing spot: pushed Mercer out of top job, company thriving with Brown at helm, even Magerman imbroglio seemed in rearview mirror

### Simons's Daily Routine: Still Pursuing Unmet Goals
- Still felt pressures; important life goals remained unmet
- Didn't take PhD in mathematics to understand limited time to accomplish them
- Maintained daily routine aimed at improving chances of satisfying remaining ambitions
- Most mornings: woke ~6:30am, headed to Central Park for miles-long walk/exercise with trainer
- Daylong hikes organized by foundation: Simons usually led the way, leaving young staffers huffing and puffing
- Switched to slightly healthier electronic cigarettes (at least during some meetings), beloved Merits tucked in breast pocket

### Simons's Continued Renaissance Involvement
- Continued checking in with Brown and other Renaissance executives, chairing board of directors meetings
- Once in long while, suggested idea to improve operation
- Focus elsewhere: spent $20M in 2018 backing Democratic political candidates, helping party regain House control

### The Simons Foundation: Second-Largest Private Research Funder
- **Simons Foundation** annual budget $450M—nation's second-largest private funder of research in basic science
- **Math for America** (organization Simons helped found): provided annual stipends of $15K to over one thousand top math/science teachers in NYC
- Hosted hundreds of annual seminars and workshops, creating community of skilled and enthusiastic teachers
- Signs initiative helping public schools retain kinds of teachers who previously bolted for private industry

### Contradictions in Simons's Choices
- Renaissance spent years legally converting short-term gains into long-term profits, saving billions in taxes
- Yet Simons decried lack of government spending on basic education in science, mathematics, other areas
- Strident critics (including **Naomi Klein**) questioned growing influence of "benevolent billionaires" who single-handedly allocate resources and determine priorities in nonprofit world at time of stretched government budgets
- Simons can be criticized for hiring waves of top scientists/mathematicians for hedge fund, even while lamenting talent private industry siphoned from public sphere and schools unable to retain top teachers

### Simons's Charitable Legacy: Potential for Real Breakthroughs
- Simons hasn't poured billions into vanity projects
- Dedicated cash and creativity to efforts that may benefit millions
- Convincing signs charitable investments could lead to real change, maybe breakthroughs, perhaps during his lifetime
- Simons could be remembered for what he did with his fortune, as well as how he made it

## Epilogue: The Universe, Autism, and the Search for Meaning

### Simons's Focus at 81 (Spring 2019)
- Approaching eighty-first birthday, consumed with two new difficulties (likely most imposing of his life):
  1. Understanding and curing **autism**
  2. Discovering origins of universe and life itself
- Earlier in life: focused on mathematics problems and enemy codes, later hidden patterns in financial markets

### Autism Research Progress
- True breakthroughs in autism research hadn't been achieved; time ticking
- Six years earlier (2013): **Simons Foundation** hired **Louis Reichardt** (professor physiology/neuroscience, first American to climb Mount Everest and K2)
- Simons handed Reichardt daunting challenge: improve lives of those with autism
- Foundation helped establish repository of genetic samples from 2,800 families with at least one child on autism spectrum, accelerating development of animal models (step toward potential human treatments)
- By spring 2019: researchers succeeded in gaining deeper understanding of autistic brain function, closing in on drugs with potential to help those battling condition
- Trial drew closer to test drug that might help as many as 20% of those suffering from disorder

> "It will be the first drug to have some effect on some people. I think we have a better than even chance of success." — Jim Simons on autism drug trial

### Cosmology Research: The Origins of the Universe
- Just as hopeful about making headway on existential challenges confounding humankind from earliest moments
- **2014**: Simons recruited **Princeton University** astrophysicist **David Spergel** (known for groundbreaking work measuring age and composition of universe)
- Simons tasked Spergel with answering eternal question of how universe began ("Oh, and please try to do it in a few years, while I'm still around")

### The Simons Observatory in Chile's Atacama Desert
- Simons helped fund $75M effort to build enormous observatory with array of ultrapowerful telescopes in **Chile's Atacama Desert**
- Plateau 17,000 feet above sea level, especially clear, dry skies
- Ideal spot to measure cosmic microwave radiation, get good look into creation's earliest moments
- Project led by group of eight scientists including Spergel and **Brian Keating** (astrophysicist who directs Simons Observatory, son of Simons's early partner **James Ax**)
- Expected completion: 2022
- Observatory will search for distant evidence of **Big Bang** (theorized event universe came into existence)

### Searching for Cosmic Inflation Evidence
- Many scientists assume universe instantaneously expanded after creation (**cosmic inflation**)
- Event likely produced gravitational waves and twisted light (**"the fingerprint of the Big Bang"** per Keating)
- Scientists spent years searching for evidence of phenomenon, each effort meeting crushing defeat (decades of close calls, ultimate futility)
- Simons Observatory represents one of best chances yet of discovering faint echoes of universe's birth pangs, providing potential evidence universe had a beginning

> "Jim is pushing to get answers soon." — David Spergel

### Simons's Cosmological Bets: Big Bang vs. Bouncing Model
- Simons expressed passion about Big Bang theory and whether giant telescope will meet goal and produce evidence of cosmic inflation
- Subscribing to view that time never had starting point, Simons simultaneously supports work by **Paul Steinhardt** (leading proponent of noninflationary **bouncing model**, opposing theory to Big Bang)

> "It's always been aesthetically pleasing to me to think time has gone on forever." — Jim Simons

- Sounding like hedge-fund trader: Simons figures he'll be winner no matter what different teams discover
- If instincts accurate and inflation isn't found, Simons feels vindicated; scientists like Steinhardt will pick up torch
- If Spergel-Keating group finds evidence backing Big Bang theory: "We win a Nobel and we're all dancing in the streets"

### Other Foundation Research Initiatives
- Foundation supported scientific collaborations aimed at understanding how life began, what early life was like, whether there might be life elsewhere in solar system or on planets outside solar system

> "All religions have covered the topic and I've always been curious. I feel we're getting closer to finding out." — Jim Simons on origins of life

### March 2019: MIT Lecture
- Brisk day mid-March 2019: Simons and wife flew on Gulfstream jet to airport outside Boston
- Met and driven to Cambridge, Massachusetts campus of **MIT** (Simons's alma mater) for scheduled lecture
- Wearing tweed sports jacket, tan khakis, crisp blue shirt, loafers (no socks)
- Addressed hundreds of students, academics, local businesspeople
- Reflected on career and post-election turbulence at Renaissance
- Asked why he didn't stop Bob Mercer's political activities: "I think he's a little crazy, to a smattering of cheers. But he's extremely bright. I couldn't fire him because of his political beliefs."

### Investment Advice: Skepticism Remains
- Asked which professional investors students should turn to for guidance
- Simons struggled for answer—quant still skeptical investors can forecast markets
- Finally mentioned neighbor in Manhattan, hedge-fund manager **George Soros**

> "I suppose he's worth listening to, though he sure talks a lot." — Jim Simons on George Soros

### Life Lessons from Simons
- Shared life lessons with school's audience:
  - "Work with the smartest people you can, hopefully smarter than you"
  - "Be persistent, don't give up easily"
  - "Be guided by beauty . . . it can be the way a company runs, or the way an experiment comes out, or the way a theorem comes out, but there's a sense of beauty when something is working well, almost an aesthetic to it."

### Simons's Most Recent Passions
- Discussed efforts to understand universe's creation and mankind's origins
- "It's entirely possible we're alone," arguing intelligent life might solely exist on planet Earth (thanks to confluence of favorable factors likely not found elsewhere)
- Brief moment: Simons looked at Marilyn, sitting in audience's front row next to their grandson (graduate student at Harvard)

> "We've had a lot of luck." — Jim Simons

- After ovation from audience, Simons extended modest wave
- Walking slowly, made his way out of hall, family close behind

